<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0803 10-19 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0803,0315</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: No separates moved for the AMs cycle.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Hipple</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Hipple, a reporter whose career spanned
five decades working for Trans-Radio Press, the Honolulu Star
Bulletin, The Associated Press and Newsweek, died Friday of cancer.
He was 74.
   He was greeting cruise ships for the Honolulu Star Bulletin when
the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor. Hipple quickly left the islands
to begin working as a war correspondent for AP and Newsweek
magazine.
   He landed with American forces on Guadalcanal, Tarawa, Guam and
Bougainville.
   With Newsweek, Hipple interviewed the two biggest names in the
Pacific Theater, Adm. Chester W. Nimitz and Gen. Douglas A.
MacArthur. Those interview coups resulted in a White House summons.
   President Franklin D. Roosevelt asked Hipple to relate what
Nimitz and MacArthur, who made a point of avoiding each other,
might have said about their sometimes-strained relationship.
   After the war, Hipple became northern European director of
public relations for American Overseas Airlines, and when those
routes were sold to Pan American Airways, he joined American
Airlines, first in Dallas and then in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Cedric Davern</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Cedric I. Davern, 57, international
scholar in the fields of genetics and microbiology, died Monday,
but the cause of death was withheld pending a state medical
examiner's report.
   Davern was a widely respected researcher and administrator. He
joined the faculty for the University of Utah in 1976. A former
vice president for academic affairs, he was professor of biology
and professor of cellular, viral and molecular biology.
   Davern was dean of the College of Medicine, now the School of
Medicine, from 1976 to 1977, when he was appointed vice president
for academic affairs. He held that position until 1983. He served
on the university faculty 12 years.
</TEXT>
