<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Romania-Environmnent     10-19 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Romania-Environmnent,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underground Report Warns of Ecological Catastrophe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania's industrialization, the absence
of environmental protection measures and official carelessless
spell ecological disaster for that communist nation and its 23
million citizens, an underground study says.
   A copy of the 22-page, hand-written report was received this
week by The Associated Press. The study was signed by 13 members of
the little-known Romanian Democratic Action, a small, underground
opposition group reportedly established in 1985.
   Western analysts said the survey, written this year, was the
first concrete attempt to define a platform for a possible
ecological opposition in Romania.
   Although its authors had no access to official statistics, the
study contains many facts and details in contrast to scant and
sporadic information in the state-run media, which usually avoid
discussing ecological failures.
   It said Romania's economic crisis ``threatens to become an
ecological catastrophe,'' with the Bucharest authorities pursuing
``a primitive concept of intensive and pitiless exploitation of the
soil and nature.''
   The survey denounced the regime of President Nicolae Ceausescu
for allegedly ignoring the general deterioration of the environment.
   It reported heavy pollution in the metallurgical centers of
Galati in eastern Romania, Hunedoara in the west and Tirgoviste in
the south.
   ``The effort to write off at any cost Romania's foreign debt
(now estimated at about $4 billion) has led to the aging of
industrial installations,'' said the study.
   ``That's why the industrial complexes, left at the level of the
1970s, are big energy spenders and polluters.''
   ``A huge, red-colored cloud hangs day and night over
Tirgoviste,'' it went on, noting that an attempt to provide a
filtering system for the local alloyed-steel combine was a ``total
failure.''
   Similarly, the chemical industry poses a ``particularly high
risk'' for the environment, it said.
   Six major accidents took place at a pharmaceutical plant in
Bucharest in the past 10 years, followed by ``considerable leaks of
unidentified toxic gases which alarmed residents'' living in the
area, said the report.
   ``Nobody said anything and no measures of any kind were taken,''
the report said.
   A dense chlorine gas that repeatedly escaped in recent years
from a chemical complex in Giurgiu in southern Romania drifted over
the northern Bulgarian city of Ruse, causing a rift between the two
Soviet bloc allies.
   The Bulgarian BTA news agency said in February that the sharp
smell of chlorine made breathing difficult, forcing people to clamp
handkerchiefs over their mouths and race for shelter.
   In an attempt to stop what Bulgarian media called ``an
ecological disaster'' in Ruse, the two countries last fall set up a
joint commissiom to take measures toward ending the chlorine
pollution in the border area.
   It was not known if the problem still exists in the area.
   The report said weapons factories at Mirsa and Zarnesti in
central Transylvania pose a ``constant danger'' for the local
population, following ``catastrophic explosions'' in 1980, 1983 and
1984.
   The study appeared to confirm unofficial accounts of the
accidents which purportedly led to the death of hundreds of people
and triggered ``enormous leaks of chlorine and a mixture of
chemical solvents.''
   It said the ecological balance is being destroyed in the
vicinity of Romania's paper factories for apparent lack of filters
and other preventive installations, damaging the health of nearby
residents.
   According to the survey, Romania's coal-fired power plants,
using low-grade coal, ``spew hundreds of thousands of tons'' of
toxic gases and residues into the atmosphere.
   Abuse of chemical fertilizers and insecticides in Romania's
state-owned agriculture reportedly led to ``advanced'' land
deterioration and erosion in some areas.
   Even Ceausescu publicly complained in February about ``overuse
of herbicides and of various chemical products to combat various
diseases in agriculture,'' following official reports about
livestock deaths resulting from contaminated fodder.
   Western observers and Romanian sources said it was the first
time Ceausescu warned of the dangers of ``chemicalized
agriculture,'' a long-standing practice of Communist planners to
increase crop yields.
   The report said water pollution was also a serious problem, and
many rivers have been turned into virtual sewers.
   Drinking water is already reported rationed in many towns. To
compensate for lack of adequate filters ``large amounts of
chlorine, above admissible doses,'' are being used, it said.
   Improvised dumping sites are being tolerated, toxic substances
are thrown directly into rivers, and car batteries, lubricants and
expired drugs are being indiscriminately dumped, the report said.
</TEXT>
