<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Dukakis     10-19 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Dukakis,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Passion Should Come from Electorate Not Candidate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters must provide the passion to elect
Michael Dukakis while the Democratic presidential nominee should
devote his attention to the issues, says former candidate Jesse
Jackson.
   ``The issue is not Dukakis' passion; it's Bush's lack of
compassion,'' Jackson told a rally Tuesday at Tulane University.
``When Dukakis talks about housing, energy, jobs, day care and the
rights of women _ he's going in the right direction. ... We the
people provide the passion. Let him provide the priorities.''
   The former contender for the Democratic nomination has come
under attack recently for his less than passionate support for his
party's ticket. Jackson, in a telephone interview earlier in the
day, said that it's absolutely false to say his support has been
less than strong.
   ``No Democrat since Atlanta has traveled more miles, spoken to
more people and registered more Democrats for the ticket than I
have,'' the Democratic runner-up said from his Chicago home.
   During the Tulane rally _ one of two New Orleans campus rallies
added to Jackson's schedule Tuesday night _ he listed an itinerary
of 18 appearances in 16 cities around the country.
   ``A week ago, my schedule was _ typical, but expresses my own
commitment and determination,'' said Jackson. ``I challenge you to
work, too.''
   Mark Goodin, a Bush spokesman in Washington, said Jackson has
done ``a tremendous disappearing act.''
   ``I think that's probably by design'' of Dukakis strategists,
Goodin said. ``If you're a liberal trying to run as a moderate,
Jesse Jackson, who doesn't hide his liberalism, is not a plus for
you.''
   In his speech, Jackson hit hard at Republican nominee George
Bush's stands on social issues and at his attacks on Dukakis as a
liberal and member of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``Why assume that those who want to change things are somehow
subversive?'' Jackson asked the crowd of 1,900 students at a
get-out-the-vote rally in the Tulane auditorium.
   Jackson's wholehearted support for the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket is
considered essential in a handful of states where he won primaries,
especially those with heavy concentrations of blacks. Those include
Georgia and Louisiana, where the Democrats are still competitive.
   Jackson, in the earlier interview, said he was urging everyone
to do their part rather than judging anyone.
   ``We have 26 Democratic governors, 53 senators, 270 House
members and the majority of urban Democratic mayors,'' he said,
slightly misstating the numbers. ``If each of those leaders with
portfolio will pull their weight ... if they will cast their net
with this ticket ... we'll have enough votes to win.''
   He did single out the Democratic Leadership Council, which was
formed in 1983 to try to draw so-called ``Reagan Democrats'' back
to the fold. Members of that group influenced Dukakis' choice of
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as vice presidential nominee, Jackson said.
   ``This is the time for the DLC to make its presence felt,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
