<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HostageSuit     10-19 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Suit,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Brought By Former Hostage Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was one of the 52 U.S. hostages
held for 444 days in Iran reached a settlement Tuesday in his $60
million libel lawsuit against the Daily News' former publishers,
both sides said.
   The terms of the settlement with the Los Angeles newspaper were
not disclosed, but former hostage Jerry Plotkin said in a statement
that he was compensated for substantial damages.
   ``At last I am truly a free man,'' Plotkin said.
   Plotkin and the other hostages were freed in January 1981. A day
later, the Daily News said in a front-page story that police had
investigated Plotkin before he went to Iran, and that he was the
target of a federal drug trafficking probe.
   The story was attributed to unidentified law enforcement
sources. Police and U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration officials
later denied such allegations had been made.
   At the time the story was published the Daily News was owned by
the Van Nuys Publishing Co., a subsidiary of the Chicago-based
Tribune Co.
   Van Nuys Publishing released a joint statement Tuesday in which
it did not admit to wrongdoing, and said, ``We believe that the
article was published ... with a good-faith belief in the truth of
the statements contained in it.
   ``The article was not intended to convey the impression that Van
Nuys Publishing Company had any information that Mr. Plotkin was in
Iran for any improper or illegal reasons,'' the statement said.
``All of the evidence which has been developed during the pendency
of Mr. Plotkin's lawsuit establishes that he went to Iran for
completely legitimate business purposes. Such evidence further
establishes that he was not the target of any law enforcement
investigation of any kind at the time he left for Iran or since.''
   The statement noted that Plotkin had dropped as defendants in
the case the reporters who wrote the story.
   ``We have settled the case with Mr. Plotkin in order to avoid
further lengthy and costly litigation and to bring this matter to a
close,'' it said. The Daily News now is owned by media and sports
entrepreneur Jack Kent Cooke and its current management and owners
were not involved in the Plotkin lawsuit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
