<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Frey     10-19 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Frey,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Richard Frey, Contract Bridge Master, Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Lincoln Frey, a contract bridge master,
has died of cancer. He was 83.
   Frey, who lived in New York City, died Monday at Calvary
Hospital.
   During his career, he won six national bridge tournaments and
was a runner-up in seven. He was nominated as a life master in
1936, the year the rank was introduced.
   Frey served as writer, editor and business manager of Kem Cards,
a manufacturer of playing cards, and wrote a syndicated daily
bridge column, articles, and several books on bridge.
   He also served as public relations director for the American
Contract Bridge League and as president of the International Bridge
Press Association.
   Survivors include his wife, Mabel, and daughter, Stephanie
Frey-Secor.
   A memorial service is scheduled for Sunday.
</TEXT>
