<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Politics Bjt   10-19 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics, Bjt,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Boards City Bus In Defiance Of Arab Stone-Throwers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, flanked by a
crowd of cheering supporters, rode a city bus through Palestinian
neighborhoods where Israeli passengers often face stone-throwing
attacks.
   Supporters shouted ``Shamir, Shamir'' and clapped their hands
Tuesday as the No. 25 bus rolled through the Arab village of
Shuafat in Arab east Jerusalem on its way to the Jewish
neighborhood of Neve Yaakov.
   Hours later, police fired rubber bullets at Arab stone-throwers
near Shuafat, injuring one, a police spokesman said.
   Shamir, who leads the right-wing Likud bloc, made the symbolic
gesture shortly after declaring that the 10-month-old Palestinian
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip was a ``useless
struggle.''
   The future of the occupied territories is a key campaign issue
in the Nov. 1 national elections.
   Shamir opposes territorial concessions. His main rival, Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres of the left-leaning Labor Party, favors a
land-for-peace deal with Israel's Arab neighbors.
   ``Israel will never move under the pressure of (the uprising),''
Shamir told reporters in Jerusalem. ``All of this suffering, all of
these victims ... it doesn't bring any results. Therefore, it will
come to an end.''
   At least 301 Palestinians have died since violence broke out
Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, captured by Israel in the
1967 Middle East war. Six Israelis also have died.
   Peres, meanwhile, warned Tuesday that keeping the territories,
where 1.5 million Palestinians live, could lead to Israeli
annexation of the region and create an Arab majority in the Jewish
state.
   ``Some Israelis want to give up the people and not the land,''
Peres told members of the U.S.-based United Jewish Appeal. ``We
never would agree to become a nation of slaves and we should not be
tempted to become a nation of masters.''
   Peres said balloting should be held in the occupied lands so a
delegation can be elected to represent the Palestinians, alongside
Jordan, in peace talks with Israel.
   Shamir called Peres' peace plan unworkable and dismissed the
call for elections as a campaign gimmick that ``people will forget
about.''
   A poll published Tuesday in the daily Maariv newspaper showed
that 30 percent of the 1,200 Israelis questioned supported
annexation while 24 percent favored joint Israeli-Palestinian rule
over the territories without PLO participation.
   Israel refuses to deal with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which it views as a terrorist group.
   The radical Moledet (Homeland) movement, which advocates
expulsion of Palestinians from the occupied territories, broadcast
its first campaign ad Tuesday.
   The ad featured a stern-looking Rehovoam Zeevi, the party leader
and a retired army general, telling voters: ``Peace can be achieved
by separation of two peoples ... now it is time to transfer Arabs
(from the occupied lands.)'' Pictures of Arab rioters appeared in
the background.
   Zeevi's Moledet and the Likud are expected to benefit from
Tuesday's Supreme Court decision barring the anti-Arab Kach
movement led by U.S.-born Rabbi Meir Kahane from participating in
the elections.
   The court, in a 5-0 ruling, said Kahane's anti-Arab party
``incites racism and negates the democratic character of the
state.''
   The court also ruled 3-2 that the Progressive List for Peace, a
leftist party that advocates an independent Palestinian state
alongside Israel, could take part in the elections.
   The Likud and other right-wing parties have demanded that the
PLP be disqualified on grounds it threatened to destroy the Jewish
character of the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
