<HEAD>Names in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Kim Basinger says she had few regrets
about abandoning her career as a model, which she says
``devastated'' her at times. ``As much money as I made, modeling
hurt me a lot,'' said Basinger, who later rose to fame in such
movies as ``The Natural'' and ``9{ Weeks.'' ``I had too much
personality inside me to become that android.''
   In an interview in November's Self magazine, the blonde beauty
suggests she was anything but cover-girl material growing up in
Athens, Ga.
   ``I had a strange prettiness that was not accepted,'' she said.
``I was too tall and so uncomfortable around the more boisterous
and outspoken girls that my palms were always sweating.''
   She said she kept her sanity by promising herself, ```I'll get
outta here. I'll get outta here. I'll get outta here.' I talked
myself into my own little cult.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former child star Shirley Temple
Black has filed a lawsuit against companies she contends
misappropriated her name for commercial purposes in sales of
``Shirley Temple Soda Pop.''
   The lawsuit against Shirley's Temple Inc., the soft drink maker,
and Walker International Specialty Foods, both of nearby Santa
Rosa, was filed recently in San Mateo County Superior Court.
   Black's attorney has since written to request that production of
the drink halt, but has been told that would result in financial
ruin for the company.
   Shirley's Temple Inc. attorney, Donal Lewin, said his client has
risked everything he owns to bring the drink to the market and
hasn't used Black's image to promote the product or implied she was
involved.
   Lewin also said similar soft drinks have been sold worldwide for
years. A hearing on the court action is set for Nov. 10.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown has been ordered to
undergo treatment for drug and alcohol abuse, and prohibited from
driving while traffic charges against him are pending.
   Municipal Court Judge Carl C. Brown Jr. imposed those conditions
Tuesday as he granted a motion filed by the singer's lawyers
seeking a jury trial in Richmond County State Court. The
entertainer's case had been assigned to Municipal Court, which does
not have jury trials.
   Brown, on tour in Europe, did not attend the hearing.
   The singer was charged last month with driving under the
influence, driving with a suspended license and improper movement
on the roadway. The arrest was the latest in a string of run-ins
with the law Brown has had this year.
   A trial has not been scheduled.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Diana, in a rare public speech, stressed
the importance of family life as a stepping stone to producing
``stable and confident adults.''
   Diana, whose own parents divorced when she was young, told the
annual conference of a children's charity that the pressures and
demands on modern parents are enormous.
   ``I know that family life is extremely important and, as a
mother of two small boys, I think we may have to find a securer way
of helping our children, to nurture and prepare them to face life
as stable and confident adults,'' she said Tuesday.
   Diana and her husband, Prince Charles, heir to the British
throne, have two sons, Prince William, 6, and Prince Harry, 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Robert Wagner says he thought he'd
``lost everything'' when his wife, Natalie Wood, drowned in 1981.
   ``Fortunately, I had our children and friends,'' Wagner said,
according to this week's TV Guide. ``I had to get up in the morning
and go on with my life. If I hadn't had anybody to get up for, I
would have been finished.''
   He also said that although four years have passed since his hit
television series ``Hart to Hart'' was canceled, he's still stunned
and disappointed.
   ``I wanted to keep it on. I fought them, but they beat me. It
was a big blow for all of us,'' he said.
   But he's ``moving in a very positive direction now,'' Wagner
said during filming of the television remake of ``Indiscreet,''
which originally starred Cary Grant and Ingrid Bergman. His co-star
is Lesley-Anne Down.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Warren G. Magnuson returned home
after spending an extra day in the hospital so doctors could
regulate his insulin and blood sugar levels, his wife said.
   Magnuson, 83, a ``borderline diabetic,'' was admitted to Swedish
Hospital on Friday to determine whether he needed to begin taking
insulin, Jermaine Magnuson said.
   ``He feels good to be sitting in his chair,'' she said Tuesday.
``The doctors took care of him.''
   A Democrat, Magnuson served 44 years in the Senate. He was
defeated in a re-election bid in 1980 by Sen. Slade Gorton.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONDON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientist Linus Pauling, a double Nobel
Prize winner, says he learned a great deal about ``the nature of
the world'' in his hometown of Condon, where his father ran a drug
store.
   The famed chemist returned to the small north-central Oregon
community Saturday to speak at newly named Condon State
Airport-Pauling Field, which was dedicated in his honor.
   The Gilliam County Historical Society presented Pauling, 87,
with a brick from the walkway in front of Herman Pauling's Red
Cross Drug Store.
   ``I may very well owe a lot of my understanding of the nature of
the world to the introduction I received in Condon,'' said Pauling,
who received a Nobel Prize in 1954 for chemistry and the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1962 for promoting a nuclear test ban.
</TEXT>
