<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugTesting     10-19 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Judges Suggest Support for Air Control Drug Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of federal appellate judges is
suggesting that random testing for drug use by air traffic
controllers and guards at chemical-weapons depots might be
justified by concerns about safety.
   An attorney for two employees' unions was confronted with sharp
questioning about the safety issue at a hearing Tuesday about drug
testing of nearly 30,000 Transportation Department and 9,400
civilian Army employees.
   ``Doesn't the government have a legitimate employer concern in
finding out whether the guard watching that nerve gas is on
hard-line drugs?'' Circuit Judge Abner Mikva asked union attorney
Joe Goldberg during the hearing.
   ``We all placidly and docilely go through the airport metal
detectors,'' said Patricia Wald, chief judge of the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals here. ``Why not put the guy minding the nerve gas
on the same side as airport detection'' of potential hijackers, she
asked.
   Goldberg argued that the test the government was using was an
unconstitutional invasion of privacy because it could not determine
whether an employee was impaired by drug use while on the job.
   All the urine test can do is determine that an employee had used
illegal drugs in the past five days, he said.
   ``Before the government can cast its net over assumedly
non-using employees, there must be some reason for the invasion
into the private lives of employees that has some relationship to
work-related conduct,'' Goldberg said.
   He urged the appeals court to apply the standard it adopted last
year when it said testing of District of Columbia school employees
was justified as part of physicals if the test could predict
on-the-job impairment.
   But during repeated questioning by Wald, Mikva and Circuit Judge
David Sentelle, Goldberg conceded that a positive test for an
employee in a sensitive job might raise proper concerns over
whether the person could do the job safely.
   ``In certain positions, a positive drug test could very well
have an employment nexus,'' Goldberg said.
   ``Why is not that the end of the argument?'' Wald said.
   Goldberg said that still didn't resolve the issue of whether the
government could ``justify a warrantless random search'' without
suspicions of drug use by particular people.
   ``The question is: Is the test justified in its inception and is
it narrowly related in scope?'' he said.
   Assistant Attorney General John Bolton argued that the
government had ``taken the step of limiting drug testing to a very
narrowly defined category of individuals'' including guards at
nerve-gas arsenals and a base where directed-energy laser weapons
are being tested.
   The Transportation Department testing, which was upheld last
year by a lower court judge, covers air traffic controllers,
drivers, airplane inspectors, sky marshals and other ``sensitive
and critical'' positions.
   The Army program was declared unconstitutional earlier this year
by another federal judge in the case brought by the American
Federation of Government Employees and the National Federation of
Federal Employees.
   A ruling on both cases might be held up until the court receives
word next spring from the Supreme Court on two other cases
involving drug testing.
   The high court is set to hear arguments Nov. 2 on testing of
railroad crews after accidents and U.S. Customs Service agents
seeking promotions.
   Mikva voiced concern that employees with prostate problems might
lose their jobs if they couldn't provide a urine sample within a
two-hour period mandated by the regulations.
   Bolton replied that two hours was a ``reasonable time period.''
   ``I won't put you to the test, Mr. Bolton,'' Mikva said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
