<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     10-19 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Calls for End to Policy of Isolation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major opposition party has issued a
platform calling for an end to Burma's policy of isolation and the
replacement of the socialist economy with a free enterprise system.
   A nine-page policy statement issued Tuesday by the the National
League for Democracy said it would seek closer relations with
foreign countries along with foreign investments and would
participate in international and regional economic organizations.
   But few observers gave the National League a chance of winning
elections even if they are held.
   After weeks of violent political protests, the military-backed
government reasserted control on Sept. 18 but allowed the formation
of opposition political parties and promised general elections, but
set no date.
   So far 22 parties have registered including the ruling National
Unity Party that has wielded power for the past 26 years.
   The ruling party and military have been in control since the
coup in 1962 led by Ne Win, who stepped down in July. Ne Win's
government adopted isolationatism and socialism and waged war
against a dozen insurgent groups seeking greater autonomy from the
central government.
   The National League for Democracy is headed by ex-Defense
Minister Tin Oo, former military officer Aung Gyi and Aung San Suu
Kyi, the daughter of the legendary freedom fighter Aung San.
   In its policy statment, the league said nationalized firms would
be returned to their original owners and all but a few state
enterprises vital to the nation would be privatized.
   It said the first priority would be ending the insurgencies by
various ethnic groups that are ``draining the country's resources
and hampering development.''
   ``Foreign investments will be permitted and a favorable
investment climate will be created by introducing measures such as
non-nationalization guarantees and favorable tax and labor laws in
accordance with international practice,'' the statement said.
   It also said ownership of land would be restored to the farmers
who would be allowed to grow and market their produce freely.
``Peasant and workers unions, independent of party politics, will
be encouraged as class organizations to protect their legitimate
righjts,'' the statement said.
   Radio Rangoon announced Tuesday that a curfew, in effect since
Sept. 18, has been shortened by one hour and will now be enforced
from 9 p.m. to 4 a.m. But it did not say if the order affected
Rangoon only or the entire country.
   The government has said more than 450 persons have been killed
in the crackdown ordered last month to restore order.
   Independent estimates put the death toll much higher.
</TEXT>
