<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeeSpill     10-19 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bee Spill,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massive Swarm of Bees Under Control; New Worry Is Mite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the 250,000 honeybees that broke
free from an overturned tractor-trailer in rush hour traffic have
been killed or caught, but state officials are still a mite worried
_ or worried, that is, about a mite.
   The state Department of Agriculture on Tuesday quaranteed four
metropolitan Atlanta counties to ensure that the parasite found on
some of the bees doesn't contaminate local hives.
   Samples analyzed from the bees showed traces of the Varroa
jacobsoni mite, which attacks adult and young bees, said
Agriculture Department spokesman Carlton Moor. It can cause bee
mutations and spreads quickly through the hive but poses no threat
to humans.
   The quarantine means no bees can be moved in or out of Cobb,
Fulton, Cherokee and DeKalb counties until the department verifies
the area is free from the Varroa mite.
   The bees were released from 200 hives that shattered when the
18-wheel flat-bed tractor-trailer hauling them from Wisconsin to
Florida flipped over Monday afternoon at the intersection of
Interstates 75 and 285 north of Atlanta.
   Witnesses said the collective hum of the insects was loud enough
to be heard above the sound of car radios as they swarmed through a
busy intersection. No one, however, reported being stung.
   State workers, aided by private beekeepers, used a garden-grade
insecticide to kill ``a whopping pile of them'' Monday night, said
Department of Transportation worker William Haithcock.
   Moore said the department was concerned that some of the
beekeepers that showed up to round up the escaped bees Monday
carried them back to their own hives.
   The bees were being shipped by West Virginia-based JimCo from
Dodgeville, Wis., to De Land, Fla., said JimCo dispatcher John
Holbrook in De Land.
</TEXT>
