<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Cambodia     10-19 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Cambodia,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Dilutes Opposition To Khmer Rouge in Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sponsors of a congressional resolution on
Cambodia are dismayed by administration reluctance to take a
stronger stand against Chinese support for the Marxist rebel group
accused of the mass murder of Cambodian civilians a decade ago.
   On Tuesday, President Reagan signed the resolution, the main
features of which call for an end to Vietnam's military presence in
Cambodia and efforts to ensure the Khmer Rouge, which ruled
Cambodia for 3{ bloody years in the late 1970's, do not return to
power.
   The administration has said repeatedly there must be ``effective
safeguards'' to ensure that the Khmer Rouge, now a powerful
guerrilla force, do not achieve a dominant role again in Cambodia.
   Nonetheless, the State Department fought hard during
negotiations with the Congress to protect the interests of the
Khmer Rouge's chief supplier, China, and the rebels' other regional
ally, Thailand.
   A key clause in the original resolution asserted that the United
States ``should attempt immediately'' to halt the flow of arms and
military equipment to the Khmer Rouge. At administration
insistence, the word ``immediately'' was deleted. There were other
changes which had the effect of watering down the resolution.
   Both China and Thailand have as their highest priority the
withdrawal of the Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and believe that
the Khmer Rouge is in the best position to hasten that process.
   China is worried about being encircled by pro-Soviet regimes and
believes that public commitments by Vietnam to withdraw from
Cambodia by 1990 are the direct result of Khmer Rouge military
pressure, according to administration officials.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest of the three rebel groups
fighting the pro-Hanoi government in Cambodia. The other two, both
non-communist, are supported by the United States.
   Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., a Senate sponsor of the resolution,
has said that the ``self-imposed silence of the American
government'' enabled China to nurse ``the Khmer Rouge beast'' back
to health.
   The chief House sponsors, Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of
the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on East Asian affairs, and
Chester Atkins, D-Mass., were out of town and unavailable for
comment Tuesday.
   But aides said both were disheartened by the administration's
deferential attitude toward China and Thailand at the expense of a
stronger stand against a group which is accused of killing between
1 million and 2 million Cambodians during their rule.
   Solarz and Atkins acquiesced in the change, fearing that a
protracted fight over wording could have led to an impasse, the
aides said. This could have meant congressional adjournment this
week with no Cambodia resolution at all.
   A State Department official, insisting on anonymity, said China
is adamant on continuing its support for the Khmer Rouge and no
amount of congressional pressure could alter the Chinese position.
On that basis, the administration fought the original wording of
the resolution.
   The official said China has come part way toward the
administration view of the Cambodian situation. He noted that China
indicated this past summer for the first time that the Khmer Rouge
should not have a dominant role in the formation of a new
government in Cambodia once Vietnam withdraws its troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
