<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid     10-19 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Stresses Possible Renewed Military Aid To Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mood in Congress is still strongly against
renewing military aid to Nicaragua's rebel movement, but the Senate
says that could change if the leftist government fails to comply
with peace accords calling for more democracy.
   The Senate on Tuesday approved a non-binding ``sense of the
Senate'' resolution declaring its support for unspecified
``continuing efforts to strengthen the internal democratic
opposition and the independent media of Nicaragua.''
   It also called for ``maintaining the Nicaraguan freedom fighters
as one of the few `pressure points' on the Sandinistas by providing
the resistance urgently needed humanitarian assistance.''
   The dwindling Contra forces are subsisting on $27 million in
food, clothing and medical supplies approved by Congress last month
as part of a Pentagon money bill.
   They haven't received any weapons from the United States since
February, when lethal aid was suspended. But Congress has agreed to
permit President Reagan to request the release of $16.5 million in
weapons, if certain conditions are met.
   Reagan said last week he might call the Congress into special
session to release the aid should the Sandinista forces strike hard
against the Contra guerrillas before the 101st Congress convenes
next January.
   ``It's important for the Senate to send a message, not only to
the resistance in Nicaragua, but to people throughout the world,''
said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
   McCain was the chief author of the non-binding ``sense of the
Senate'' resolution. It was approved on a voice vote after an
earlier attempt to kill it was defeated, 54-12.
   The resolution was attached to an unrelated bill affecting more
than 6 million acres of federal wilderness lands in Montana.
   Also attached to the bill before it was passed on a voice vote
were resolutions endorsing Chile's movement toward restoration of
democracy and urging U.S. allies to block Soviet efforts to win the
approval of loans worth millions of U.S. dollars.
   The legislation faces an uncertain future as Congress heads
toward adjournment. The House has yet to approve it, and any
changes from the Senate-passed legislation would have to be cleared
by a House-Senate conference committee.
   The Chilean proposal, sponsored by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, was
added to the Contra measure on a voice vote.
   Chileans voted Oct. 5 to reject a new presidetial term for Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, the military leader who has ruled the nation
since a 1973 coup overthrew the socialist civilian president,
Salvador Allende.
   ``We've had a long night of despair in Chile, from the coup in
1973 to until this year,'' said Harkin. ``It's incumbent on us to
support the Chilean people, to support this election they had, to
say that we are going to work with them in this restoration of full
democracy.''
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., termed the proposal ``a feel-good
amendment'' and said Pinochet had saved Chile from going communist.
   The Soviet loan amendment, approved 64-2, was proposed by Sen.
Steven Symms, R-Idaho.
   He said the Soviets are trying to secure loans of U.S. dollars
through third nations. ``The Soviets are using the eagerness of the
Western allies to play one nation off against another, to get them
to compete with each other for the opportunity to donate hard
currency to finance socialist economic failures and Soviet foreign
policy.''
   The wilderness bill affects more than 6 million acres of Montana
and is the result of a compromise worked out among competing
interests, including conservationists and the timber and lumber
industries.
   The bill designates about 1.43 million acres of Forest Service
land as wilderness, 360,000 acres as special management areas, and
another 20,000 acres as federal study areas. It also releases for
non-wildnerness uses more than 10 million acres in Montana's 10
national forests.
</TEXT>
