<DOCNO> AP881019-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MarketHalts     10-19 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Market Halts,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regulators Approve Plan Designed To Prevent Reoccurrence Of Stock
Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of today's first anniversary of the
October stock market crash, federal regulators approved a plan that
likely would have prevented the 508-point plunge, or at least kept
it from happening all in one day.
   After markets closed on Tuesday, the Securities and Exchange
Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission said they
authorized a one-year experiment providing for coordinated trading
halts _ or circuit breakers _ during steep market dives.
   The plan calls for a one-hour trading halt in the event the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrial stocks plummets by 250 points or
more from the previous day's closing. A drop of 400 points would
trigger a two-hour trading halt.
   One year ago today, the Dow fell a record 508 points, wiping out
an estimated $500 billion in paper wealth in a single day. Because
most of the crash occurred in the last hour of trading, a circuit
breaker plan such as the one approved Tuesday likely would have
limited the damage to 400 points.
   The New York Stock Exchange, the nation's largest stock market,
and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the largest market for trading
stock-index futures, proposed the experiment on July 7.
   Other markets, including the Chicago Board Options Exchange, the
American Stock Exchange and the National Association of Securities
Dealers' over-the-counter system, are joining in.
   Because Congress failed to agree on market reforms this year,
circuit breakers are the most substantive change stemming from the
crash.
   Government approval is effective immediately. It is up to the
exchanges to decide when to begin.
   ``We're ready to implement this as soon as Thursday. We think
this is a very significant action to remedy what problems there
were in the market a year ago,'' said Andrew Yemma, a spokesman for
the Chicago Merc.
   The plan is designed to provide an orderly halt to trading
before one market _ stock or futures _ breaks down, shifting all of
the trading to the remaining market. It is also intended to allow
time for buyers to step in and counter overwhelming sell orders.
   Another part of the plan gives individual investors, as opposed
to pension and mutual funds, preference in trading on the New York
Stock Exchange when the Dow moves either up or down by 25 points.
The rule applies to orders of 2,099 shares and smaller.
   After the crash, many individual investors complained that their
orders were shunted aside, in some cases for hours, while larger
buy and sell orders from institutional investors were executed.
   The market halt plan is one of the key recommendations offered
after the crash by a presidential task force headed by Nicholas
Brady, a New York investment banker who is now Treasury secretary.
   The NASD said earlier this month that it was going along with
the plan only reluctantly because it did not want to be the only
market left open when all others were closed.
   But NASD President Joseph R. Hardiman argued that a
pre-announced trigger for market halts could act as a ``magnet,''
pulling the market down faster. As the market approaches the halt
point, it could be flooded with orders from traders fearful they
will be prevented from selling, he said.
   With the SEC approval, a previous six-month experiment to curb
computerized index arbitrage ends. The earlier program had provided
that when the market moved by 50 points or more, index arbitrage
orders were not allowed through the NYSE's automated trading system.
   Index arbitrage is designed to take advantage of momentary price
discrepancies between the stocks and futures markets. It involves
the buying and selling of massive blocs of stocks and futures
contracts and was criticized for making last year's crash more
precipitous.
   However, the so-called 50-point collar experiment ran counter to
the Brady commission's finding that stock and future markets were
in effect one market and that disconnecting them could be dangerous.
   A new rule taking the place of the collar is aimed at providing
more orderly index arbitrage. When the Standard and Poors 500 index
falls by more than 12 points, the equivalent of 96 points on the
Dow, index arbitrage orders will be shunted into a side file of the
trading computer. If buy and sell orders can be matched, the trades
will go through. If not, trading in individual S&P 500 stocks could
be halted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FishOilSubstitute     10-19 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fish Oil Substitute,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tests Show Soybean Oil Could Supply Fatty Acids Found In Fish Oil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laboratory tests show the human body rapidly
converts a part of the soybean oil used in some ordinary food
products into the same kinds of fatty acids found in fish oil,
according to an Agriculture Department scientist.
   Chemist Edward A. Emken of the department's Agricultural
Research Service, said healthy people on a typical American diet
may have to look no further than their salad dressing for benefits
that some people are seeking from fish oil capsules.
   Two men in a preliminary study consumed the soybean oil
component, linolenic acid, and within a few hours their bodies had
coverted it into the same omega-3 fatty acids found in fish and
marine oil, he said.
   ``Think of it this way: the body can naturally make its own fish
oil omega-3 fatty acids from the linolenic acid in soybean oil,''
Emken said in a report released Tuesday by the USDA agency.
   Emken led the study at the agency's Northern Regional Research
Center, Peoria, Ill., and was helped in the work by St. Francis
Medical Center, Peoria.
   The report said capsules of fish and marine oils have been
``touted by advertisers and debated by nutrionists'' as dietary
supplements. Whatever the merits, it said, the capsules have become
popular with any consumers hoping to ease or prevent conditions
ranging from heart disease to rheumatoid arthritis.
   ``Our study is the first to show that linolenic acid is rapidly
converted to omega-3 fatty acides found in marine oil,'' Emken
said. ``The study also provides direction for further research to
learn which dietary fatty acids, including those in fish and
soybeans, best meet human nutritional needs.''
   Soybean oil is the only major domestic vegetable oil that
contains much linolenic acid and makes up 79 percent of the
vegetable fats in the average U.S. diet, the report said. The fats
are in such foods as shortening, margarine and cooking oil as well
as in salad dressing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
