<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Jews     10-19 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Jews,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Germany Apparently Ready to Pay Some Reparations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist East Germany has agreed to pay some
reparations to Holocaust victims and their families, and is
considering steps to improve ties with Israel, according to the
president of the World Jewish Congress.
   Both steps mark a significant departure from East Germany's
previous policy.
   World Jewish Congress President Edgar M. Bronfman, speaking at
the end of a three-day visit to East Germany, said Tuesday a plan
for East German reparations to Holocaust victims had been completed.
   Bronfman declined to give any details and did not say how much
would be paid out. Heinz Galinski, leader of West Germany's Jewish
community, said earlier that East Germany would pay up to $100
million to Holocaust victims.
   In his news conference, Bronfman referred to an international
Claims Conference backed by the WJC that has handled reparations
issues for Holocaust victims.
   ``I understand that the negotiations that took place between the
(East German) government and the Claims Conference have been
completed,'' Bronfman said. ``They will be lived up to and the
details and communications will be worked out and reported.''
   ``I am completely satisifed with the results,'' he said. ``I
have nothing further to say on the payments question. It is not my
responsibility to discuss the details.''
   Since its founding in 1949, East Germany has argued that it
bears no responsibility for Nazi atrocities because the nation was
born after World War II. It has also stressed that communists had
also suffered under Nazi persecution.
   This summer, however, the government said it would provide
unspecified ``humanitarian aid'' to Holocaust victims.
   State-run media also have reported in recent months on
government efforts to improve relations with East Germany's tiny
Jewish community. There are an estimated 450-600 practicing Jews in
East Germany.
   ``I am totally satisfied on two counts,'' Bronfman said. ``The
first is the one that concerns me the most. That is the moral
position that East Germany is taking on its responsibilities on the
Holocaust. The second point is payment to the sufferers and
survivors.''
   Bronfman, 59, also said he hoped for improved contacts between
East Germany and Israel. The two countries have never had
diplomatic relations and East Germany has been a staunch Arab
supporter.
   During his three-day stay in East Berlin, Bronfman held talks
with East German Communist Party leader Erich Honecker, Foreign
Minister Oskar Fischer and other officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
