<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Veterans     10-19 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Veterans,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Veterans Legislation; Reagan Expected To Sign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the nation's largest block of voters
will receive new status and rights if President Reagan, as
expected, signs into law three major veterans' bills headed for
congressional approval.
   One of the bills, elevating the Veterans Administration to
presidential Cabinet status, is headed for Reagan's desk following
Senate passage by voice vote.
   The other two, also passed Tuesday night by the Senate on voice
votes, must be returned to the House for final votes. But approval
there is considered assured.
   The bills would give veterans, for the first time in 170 years,
the right to have courts review VA decisions denying benefits, and
would provide a package of cost-of-living payment increases to 2.2
million veterans and 310,000 widows and orphans.
   A new Department of Veterans Affairs would be the 14th Cabinet
agency and the fifth created in the past 28 years. It would replace
the VA, the federal government's fifth-largest agency.
   The VA serves 27 million veterans and 49 million dependents or
survivors. Its $30 billion annual budget includes $14 billion
annual payments for income maintenance and $626 million for
education and rehabilitation assistance.
   The agency and its 240,000 employees administer about 90,000
patient beds in 534 health facilities. VA doctors will see about 20
million outpatients this year. It runs 109 national cemeteries and
will bury about 300,000 veterans in the next 12 months.
   The Congressional Budget Office said switching the VA to a
Cabinet department will cost $33 million over five years. Most of
that will go for changing signs on VA buildings.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the Senate Veterans'
Affairs Committee, said the new department's ``first order of
business'' should be to investigate a deficiency in VA hospital
beds.
   ``Sick veterans are being turned away from VA hospitals across
the country,'' Cranston said, because ``the Reagan administration
misled Congress about the VA's real needs'' and the VA medical
system faces a $635 million budget deficit.
   The appellate review bill creates a new, independent ``U.S.
Court of Veterans Appeals'' to replace the current Board of
Veterans' Appeals. That panel is part of the VA and is now the last
resort of veterans who are unhappy with decisions to reject their
claims.
   Decisions of the new court could be appealed to the existing
U.S. Court of Appeals for the federal circuit on any legal matter,
but not on factual findings.
   The measure also eliminates a Civil War-era law which limits
attorney's fees for veterans' claims to $10 per claim. That made it
difficult for veterans to hire lawyers other than those provided by
the VA.
   The bill is a ``historic advance in veterans' rights,'' Cranston
said.
   On Oct. 3, the House approved somewhat similar legislation by a
400-0 tally, but minor differences between the two bills mean
another House vote is required.
   Before passage, the Senate added an amendment which could
provide interim health care payments to some Vietnam veterans who
were exposed to Agent Orange, a highly toxic defoliant used by U.S.
forces in Southeast Asia.
   The VA would assume that two types of cancer _ non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma and soft-tissue sarcoma _ were caused by Agent Orange.
Veterans could receive benefits while the U.S. government, which
hasn't finally agreed that Agent Orange caused cancer, studies the
problem.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a Vietnam veteran, said Agent Orange
provisions will have ``a very limited effect.''
   ``I find it highly disturbing that those people who went to
fight the VC in Vietnam spend too much fighting the VA back here in
this country,'' Kerry said.
   The Senate also added an amendment to permit the VA to offer
Vietnam-era veterans flight training courses under the auspices the
GI bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OzoneLayer     10-19 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ozone Layer,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ozone Layer Has Suffered More Damage Than Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ozone layer that protects the
earth from excessive solar radiation has suffered twice as much
damage as expected, a United Nations environmental expert says.
   The protective layer in the outer reaches of the earth's
atmosphere is 4 percent thinner than it was in 1986, according to
Dr. Mostafa Tolba, the executive director of the United Nations
Environment Program.
   Last year, scientists predicted this year's reduction would only
be 2 percent, Tolba told reporters Tuesday. He is in the Hague for
a two-week conference on the ozone layer problem.
   The sun's ultraviolet rays reaching the earth's surface
unfiltered by the ozone layer have been linked to a variety of
environmental and health problems ranging from stunted plant growth
to skin cancer in humans.
   It is also held partly responsible for the gradual heating of
the earth's atmosphere known as the ``greenhouse effect.''
   Damage to the ozone layer is mainly caused by a group of
man-made chemicals known as chlorofluorocarbons or CFCs, which are
widely used in aerosol cans, refrigerators, air conditioners and
various types of plastic foam used for packaging and insulation.
   The UNEP-organized gathering of scientists from more than 30
nations is the first meeting of its kind since last year's signing
of the Montreal Protocol, which calls for the production of CFCs to
be cut to half its 1986 levels by 1998.
   However, Tolba said chlorofluorocarbons production should
ultimately be cut to 15 percent of those levels or even phased out
completely if there is to be no further damage to the ozone layer.
   Since the late 1970s, the ozone layer, which forms naturally but
is gradually depleted by the emissions, has contained a large hole
over the South Pole.
   Tolba said the hole appeared slightly smaller this year than in
1987, although he added it is normal for its size to fluctuate from
one year to the next. He said climatic factors, and not a lessening
of the CFC problem, were responsible.
   The Netherlands and West Germany, both major CFC-producing
nations, have already called for a complete ban on production of
the dangerous chemicals.
   Under the Montreal Protocol, a review of the ozone layer
situation is scheduled to begin in 1990, but Tolba said that
process will be accelerated and begin next year.
   Later this week, scientists at the conference will discuss the
use of harmless substitutes for CFCs. The conference ends Oct. 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
