<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmTrade     10-19 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Trade,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says US Would Accept Interim Farm Subsidy Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is willing to consider a
``down payment'' on its ambitious goal of eliminating all farm
subsidies by the year 2000, a U.S. official says.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said the Reagan
administration would accept an interim agreement calling for
targets of reducing farm subsidies in 1989 and 1990.
   But he insisted that U.S. negotiators would not go along with
the interim subsidy reductions unless they receive in return a
strong commitment to pursue the total elimination of farm subsidies
as part of the current Uruguay Round of trade talks.
   Those talks, held under the auspices of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, the international body which governs trade,
began in Uruguay in 1986 and are scheduled to conclude in 1990.
   The 96 nations holding the discussions will meet in Montreal
beginning Dec. 5 for a mid-term negotiating session to review
progress so far and set goals for the next two years.
   ``I believe strongly that a short-term down payment in Montreal
would be highly desirable for everyone,'' Yeutter said. ``It would
set an excellent tone for the final two years of the (Uruguay)
negotiations. It would get the reform process underway.''
   Yeutter said the United States ``is not about to embark on this
proposition unless we also receive a satisfactory commitment to
long-term reform.''
   The $200 billion farm subsidy war has been the most heated topic
of discussions in the trade round. Reagan has called for the
elimination of all subsidies by the end of this century, but most
European countries and Japan have called that goal unrealistic.
   At this year's economic summit in Toronto, the administration
was able to get only an agreement for a watered-down proposal to
work toward reducing subsidies, rather than totally eliminating
them.
   Yeutter, at a briefing for reporters Tuesday, insisted that
America's willingness to accept an interim subsidy reduction was
not a signal that the United States was moderating its position.
   He repeated warnings that Congress could very likely increase
farm export subsidies next year, just as lawmakers did in 1985,
unless progress is made on the farm issue at the Montreal meetings.
   He said a proposal advanced recently by Australia and various
other farm exporting nations provided a useful outline for an
interim agreement.
   That proposal, which addresses reductions in domestic subsidies
to farmers, export subsidies for farm products and market access
for other countries ``is in the ball park of potential short-term
reform and with some alterations and editing between now and
December, my guess is that it could constitute the basis for
short-term reform,'' Yeutter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseFraud     10-19 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Fraud,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Says Defense Fraud Imperils US Forces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate sponsor of a procurement fraud bill
says the legislation's severe penalties would give prosecutors a
powerful new tool to use against defense contractors cheating the
government.
   ``Defense fraud rips off American taxpayers and endangers the
lives of our fighting forces'' by providing them with defective
parts, Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said after the Senate
passed the measure by voice vote Tuesday.
   The bill would allow prosecutors to seek up to $10 million in
fines for large-scale procurement fraud against the U.S. government.
   The bill must return to the House, which earlier approved a
similar version.
   The Defense Department estimates procurement fraud cost
taxpayers $99.1 million for fiscal years 1986 and 1987, Metzenbaum
said, adding, ``This bill gives our government a powerful new
weapon aimed at punishing and deterring defense fraud.''
   A person or corporation would be subject to the penalties if
convicted of a scheme or act to defraud the government in
connection with a contract of at least $1 million. The size of the
fine would be determined by the severity of the offense.
   Conviction for each act of fraud could result in maximum
penalties of $1 million and 10 years in prison. There would be an
overall cap of $10 million for a single defendant.
   The Senate bill would prohibit contractors from recovering legal
fees in proceedings where the contractors were found to engage in
wrongdoing.
   This language was not in the House bill, and that chamber must
concur before the bill can go to President Reagan.
   Current law allows contractors to recover significant amounts of
legal fees from the government as an allowable cost of the contract.
   A whistleblower protection provision allows anyone fired or
punished for furnishing information to the government to sue for
reinstatement, and receive twice the amount of lost pay.
   The measure also would authorize $8 million for more U.S.
attorneys to prosecute fraud cases, and increase the statute of
limitations from the current five years to seven years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
