<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--DohenyAuction     10-19 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Doheny Auction,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auction Brings More Than Twice What Was Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-day auction of rare books and manuscripts
from a California seminary, including a 175-year-old edition of
``Pride and Prejudice,'' brought $4.1 million, Christie's auction
house reported.
   The sale from the Edward Laurence Doheny Memorial Library of St.
John's Seminary in Camarillo amassed more than twice the presale
estimate of $1.9 million, Christie's spokeswoman Roberta Maneker
said Tuesday.
   It was estimated, for instance, that the Jane Austen novel
``Pride and Prejudice,'' printed in London in 1813, would be worth
from $4,000 to $6,000 because of worn spines and corners and other
decay. But it brought $49,500.
   The books and manuscripts had been housed in the seminary since
the 1940s. They were left by the will of the late philanthropist
Carrie Estelle Doheny.
   Los Angeles Roman Catholic Archbishop Roger Mahony said,
however, that ``the needs of the seminary system of Los Angeles are
such that we can no longer afford the luxury of maintaining a
valuable and little used asset.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
