<DOCNO> AP881019-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--FreeDog     10-19 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Free Dog,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Sides with Dog Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a ruling that took the bite out of a
city ordinance, the state Supreme Court overturned the conviction
of a man who was fined $50 for allowing his dog to run free.
   The high court Tuesday unanimously reversed a conviction issued
by a municipal court in Bismarck and upheld by a county court,
saying prosecutors presented no evidence that the pet owner knew of
the violation.
   David Sholy of Bismarck, who acted as his own lawyer before the
Supreme Court, had been convicted of violating a city ordinance
that made it ``unlawful for any owner or keeper of a dog to permit
the animal to be at large.''
   The Supreme Court, however, ruled that the word ``permit''
requires some knowledge of the crime or negligence that led to it.
   ``Because the city introduced no evidence of culpability at the
trial, the conviction is reversed,'' the court said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
