<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Upside Down Beer,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brewer Putting Unfriendly Messages On Millions Of Bottles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Scottish brewer plans next week to paste labels
on 36 million bottles of its famous Newcastle Brown Ale upside down
to protest an Australian takeover bid.
   Scottish and Newscastle PLC says a special ``hands off'' message
also will be pasted on the back of 24 million of those bottles,
brewery spokesman Jim Merrington said Tuesday. The message has not
yet been written, he said.
   ``We sell Newcastle Brown to 30 different countries so we expect
this message will soon find its way to Australia,'' Merrington
said. ``The aim of the upside down labels is to demonstrate a
thumbs-down to Elders.''
   Elders, which makes the popular Fosters lager, launched its $2.8
billion takeover bid Monday. Scottish rejected a similar proposal
last summer from Elders, which already owns 9.65 percent of the
company.
</TEXT>
