<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-WarCriminal     10-19 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-War Criminal,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>War Criminal's Widow Barred From Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian authorities say they have barred the widow
of a Nazi war criminal from entering Italy to promote a book about
her husband's escape from prison.
   Annelise Kappler had hoped to tour in connection with the book
that detailed how she helped her husband, Herbert Kappler, flee to
West Germany from a Rome military prison in 1977. He reportedly had
been concealed inside a large trunk.
   Kappler, an SS colonel in Rome during World War II, was
sentenced to life in prison for his role in the reprisal slaying of
335 Italian civilians in 1944. Seventy of the victims were Jews.
   Kappler died of cancer in West Germany a year after his escape.
   Italian officials, including Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti,
a Christian Democrat, and Justice Minister Giuliano Vassalli, spoke
out against the visit, and the Interior Ministry announced Tuesday
she would be turned back at the border as an undesirable if she
tried to enter Italy.
   Mrs. Kappler said Tuesday that she had postponed the trip at
Vassalli's request, but hoped to come to Italy at a future date.
   ``Mr. Vassalli requested in a telegram that I not come out of
respect for those who suffered under the crimes of the Nazis,'' she
told The Associated Press in a telephone interview from her home in
Soltau, West Germany.
   Publication of her book will be delayed, her publisher said.
   ``I believe it opportune to take my distance from the
intransigent attitude of Mrs. Kappler and put off the book
presentation until a calmer moment,'' publisher Cesare Ardini was
quoted as saying by the Italian news agency AGI.
   The outcry arose as Italian Jews were holding a convention to
commemorate the racial laws enacted in 1938 by Benito Mussolini's
fascist dictatorship, which foreshadowed deportations to Nazi death
camps.
   The 200 people attending the convention, held in an annex of the
Parliament building, broke into applause when a message denouncing
the visit by Kappler's widow was received from Nilde Iotti, the
Communist speaker of the Chamber of Deputies.
   ``The gesture of Mrs. Kappler, who wants to exalt the figure of
her Nazi criminal husband, is a challenge to the human conscience
and the Italian people,'' Ms. Iotti's message said.
   Tullia Zevi, president of the Union of Italian Jewish
Communities, which represents the country's 35,000 to 40,000 Jews,
praised the intervention by Italian officials and said Mrs. Kappler
was ``trying to make a mockery of Italian justice.''
   Mrs. Zevi said she sees the Kappler book, an attempt to justify
her husband's role and the reason she spirited him out of the
country, as part of a trend to rewrite the history of World War II
and relegate the suffering of the Jews to no more than an accident
of the war.
   She said the convention is aimed at recalling the Italian
legislation so that today any such laws can be be fought ``no
matter under what form they are presented.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
