<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-19 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Prices Reduce US Food Aid to Needy Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Food for Peace program is expected to
provide less grain and other items to needy countries in the next
year because of higher commodity prices.
   Acting Undersecretary of Agriculture Richard W. Goldberg said
Tuesday that allocations for the 12 months that began Oct. 1 total
about 3 million metric tons of grain equivalent valued at $663
million.
   Under the program a year ago, allocations totaled 4.4 million
tons of food commodities worth $648 million.
   Goldberg said $139.5 million in unallocated funds has been set
aside as a reserve to provide commodities ``for unforeseen needs''
during the year. Last year the reserve was $85.6 million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Urge West Germany To Prosecute or Deport Accused Nazi Collaborator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany should either prosecute an
alleged Nazi collaborator or send him to the Soviet Union ``so he
can be held accountable for his crimes,'' two Jewish activists say
in a letter to the West German ambassador to the United Nations.
   ``It would be an injustice to allow Boleslavs Maikovskis to
escape punishment for his crimes,'' wrote Brooklyn, N.Y., District
Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman and Menachem Rosensaft, founding
chairman of the International Network of Children of Holocaust
Survivors.
   Maikovskis, 83, fled the United States for West Germany, where
he has asked for political asylum, West Germany authorities said
Tuesday. He had been living in Mineola, N.Y., since 1951, but had
been slated for deportation since 1986.
   As chief a Nazi-created police force in Latvia during World War
II, Maikovskis he allegedly ordered the mass arrest of residents in
the village of Audrini. The letter said all the villagers were
later killed.
   In 1965, the Soviet Union sentenced Maikovskis to death in
absentia.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Catholic Patriarch Urges Dialogue With PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem told
American officials he hopes for eventual U.S. recognition of the
Palestinian Liberation Organization.
   Archbishop Michel Sabbah, the first Palestinian to hold the
Latin patriarch post, also said Tuesday he appealed to President
Reagan on behalf of Palestinians living in Israeli-occupied
territories.
   Sabbah said told Reagan in the 10-minute meeting that ``the
Jewish people are enjoying their human rights, the Palestinians are
not. Since 1967 they have been living under Israeli military
occupation.''
   The president said in response that he hopes for an end to
violence and peace in the area through negotiations, Sabbah told
reporters.
</TEXT>
