<HEAD>Illinois Is First U.S. State to Sign International Securities</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Agreement
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Illinois and Great Britain will
begin trading data for securities investigations under a landmark
exchange agreement awaiting final ratification.
   The board of directors of The Securities Association in Great
Britain is expected to approve the accord on Nov. 7, a spokesman
for Illinois Secretary of State Jim Edgar said Tuesday.
   ``We're prepared to start just as soon as they ratify it,''
spokesman Gary Mack said. ``Our people are very excited about it,
hoping it may be a first step toward agreements down the road with
other countries that have comparable regulatory systems.''
