<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Occupation     10-19 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Occupation,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Labor to Annex Areas of Arab Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shimon Peres' Labor Party, which has pledged to
return some occupied territory in exchange for peace, actually
plans to keep West Bank land where the Arab population is growing
fastest, a newly released study says.
   The U.S.-financed study by respected Israeli researcher Meron
Benvenisti also said some 1.75 million Arabs live in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, 250,000 more than Israel's latest figure
of 1.5 million.
   Benvenisti, a former deputy mayor of Jerusalem, told a news
conference that Arab living conditions in the territories have
deteriorated during Israel's 21-year occupation, in contrast to
Israeli claims.
   He blamed the hardships for spurring the 10-month-old
Palestinian uprising, during which more than 300 Arabs and six
Israelis have died.
   ``If you take indicators like the number of hospital beds per
1,000 Palestinians, the length of road per capita, even the amount
of water, the situation is worse,'' said Benvenisti, whose study,
``The West Bank and Gaza Atlas,'' was financed by the Ford and
Rockefeller foundations.
   ``From land expropriation to the pitiful planning to ... the
dual system of infrastructure available for Arabs versus Jewish
settlers ... Here you can find the reasons for the intefadeh,''
Benvenisti said, using the Arabic word for ``uprising.''
   Benvenisti said the left-leaning Labor Party's announced plan to
return parts of the West Bank to Arab control would keep for Israel
large areas where the Palestinian population is growing fastest.
   ``These areas are precisely the areas where the fastest growth
of both Arab and Jewish population have occurred,'' he said, adding
that more job opportunities were causing the expansion.
   According to Labor's plan, about half of the West Bank would be
kept by Israel, including the Arab cities of Ramallah and
Bethlehem, the 50-mile-long Jordan Valley and all of the
territory's 118 Jewish settlements.
   The area Labor would return includes the largest Arab cities of
Nablus and Hebron, as well as Tulkarem, Jenin and Jericho, the
researcher said.
   The rival Likud bloc of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, which
faces Labor in Nov. 1 parliamentary elections, opposes returning
any occupied territory.
   Among the evidence Benvenisti cited to show a decline in West
Bank living conditions was a drop in the number of hospital beds.
He said there were 2.15 beds per 1,000 Arabs in 1970 as compared to
1.8 beds per 1,000 in 1983.
   He also said Palestinians have less water than West Bank Jewish
settlers, as reflected in consumption statistics.
   In 1982, he said, annual water consumption per capita was 15
cubic meters for village Arabs, 35 cubic meters for Arabs in towns,
and 90 cubic meters for Jewish settlers.
   Shlomo Khayat, co-author of the study, noted Palestinian anger
also grows when Israel's lack of planning leads to such practical
problems as delays in granting building permits.
   ``This is why you see so many Arab buildings going up illegally
and then being demolished by the Israeli authorities,'' he said.
</TEXT>
