<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Storm     10-19 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Storm,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Leave Dozens Dead In Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains and whirlwinds have struck
central Vietnam in recent days, killing at least 26 people, news
reports say.
   The storm ruined more than 247,000 acres of fields and pulled
down nearly 2,500 houses as it tore through a stretch from Thanh
Hoa to Phu Khanh provinces, the official Vietnam News Agency said
in a report broadcast Tuesday and seen in Bangkok today.
   Many roads and railway lines were damaged, the report said.
   The official domestic Radio Hanoi said Tuesday that flashfloods
due to swelling rivers submerged many houses and 10 people drowned
in Nghe Tinh province, where the floods affected some 230,000
people.
   Flooding levels in the province's Lam River neared record highs
on Monday and were expected to rise Tuesday, the broadcast said.
The Central Floods and Typhoons Control Committee has ordered
authorities there to protect the major reservoirs and dams.
   Badly hit was Dai Loc district of Quang Nam-Danang province,
where floods and whirlwinds killed 12 people, the radio said. It
reported that 832 houses and classrooms and 82,000 acres of rice
and other crops were destroyed.
   Earlier Vietnamese media reports indicated that the storms began
early last week.
   Tropical storms, some of typhoon force, annually cause
considerable loss of life and damage in Vietnam, one of the world's
poorest nations. Last year, northern Vietnam also was plagued by
what the government said were severe food shortages due to a
prolonged drought.
</TEXT>
