<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-19 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded moderately Wednesday on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the dollar fell against the Japanese
yen.
   The dollar closed at 126.85 yen, down 0.85 yen from Tuesday's
close of 127.70 yen. Opening at 127.15 yen, the currency moved
lower while ranging between 126.85 and 127.60 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Exchange of 225 selected issues, which lost
126.76 points the previous day, regained 151.69 points, or 0.56
percent, to close at 27,293.67, compared to Tuesday's closing at
27,141.98 points.
   News reports predicting lower interest rates on
government-issued bonds and an apparent lack of opposition by the
Bank of Japan spurred buying on the stock exchange Wednesday, said
a dealer with Daiwa Securities.
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading business and financial
daily, reported that interest rates on 10-year government bonds to
be issued in November will be trimmed to 4.8 or 4.9 percent from
the current 5.0 percent.
   When interest rates fall, share prices normally rise because
investors funnel their money out of the credit market and into the
stock market, the dealer said.
   In foreign exchange trading, potential dollar-sellers were
discouraged by another Nihon Keizai Shimbun report that said the
Japanese and U.S. central banks were willing to coordinate action
if the dollar falls to the 125-yen level, traders said.
</TEXT>
