<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>b i AM-India-Crash 8thLd-Writethru a0501 10-19 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Crash, 8th Ld - Writethru, a0501,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Indian Airlines Jet Crashes, 130 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with reports that foreigner on plane, comment
from Boeing spokesman in Seattle, additional details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian Airlines jetliner with 135
people on board crashed Wednesday and exploded in central India and
130 people died, authorities said.
   The Indian Airlines jet slammed to the ground at 7:40 a.m.
(10:10 p.m. EDT Tuesday) on its final approach to Ahmadabad
airport, about 300 miles southwest of New Delhi, according to Capt.
J.D. Rao, operations manager of Indian Airlines in Bombay.
   The plane made more than one attempt to land, said G.K. Rawal,
police inspector at the airport. Rawal said 130 bodies had been
recovered and that five survivors had been taken to hospitals.
   Airline officials said there are several foreigners aboard the
plane, but they did not know their nationalities.
   Authorities did not know immediately what caused the crash of
the Boeing 737, flying to Ahmadabad from Bombay with 129
passengers, including five children, and a crew of six.
   However, Rawal said, the plane was attempting to land in heavy
fog. Airport workers were searching for the plane's ``black box,''
he said.
   There were conflicting reports about the crash.
   An Ahamadabad airport controller said the jet had started its
final approach when it crashed near an industrial area and
exploded. He said no one on the ground was hurt.
   Rawal said the plane exploded in the air.
   News reports said the aircraft suddenly fell from the sky, hit a
tree and then a high-voltage power line and exploded. The wreckage
and bodies were scattered in a field near an industrial area,
reports said.
   Airline officials said the company's managing director, Gerry
Pais, and the federal minister of civil aviation, Shiv Raj Patil,
had gone to the crash site.
   Ahmadabad is about 220 miles from the Pakistan border in Gujarat
state.
   The aircraft, acquired in 1971, is one of the oldest in the
airline's fleet.
   Indian Airlines, the domestic carrier, has come fire recently
for its poor management and maintenance record and frequent delays.
Wednesday's crash was the 16th by an Indian Airlines carrier in the
past 25 years.
   ``Any loss is bad. All crashes are the worst and most
unfortunate,'' said A.K. Vashist, an Indian Airlines spokesman in
New Delhi, the company's headquarters.
   On June 19, an Indian Airlines plane crashed at New Delhi
airport, but everyone on board survived. An investigation showed
the pilot forgot to lower the plane's landing gear.
   On Jan. 1, 1978, 213 people were killed when an Air India jet en
route to the Middle East kingdom of Dubai crashed less than two
minutes after taking off from Bombay.
   In Seattle, Tom Cole of Boeing Commercial Airplanes said an
investigator for the manufacturer was en route to the crash scene
from Bombay.
   Boeing 737s have come under increasingly scrutiny since an Aloha
Airlines aircraft broke apart in April while in flight and made a
miraculous landing with a 20-foot section missing from the top of
the fuselage.
   This week, National Transportation and Safety Board officials
revealed that a foot-long crack and 29 smaller ones were found on a
Continental Airlines 737 as it was stripped for repainting on Oct.
5.
   NTSB chairman James Kolstad called it ``chilling discovering.''
The Aloha plane was No. 152 off the Boeing assembly line and the
Continental was No. 170.
   The Federal Aviation Administration issued an order in May that
all older Boeing 737s, those with at least 30,000 cycles, undergo a
special visual inspection for cracking.
   The Indian airlines plane was the 271st off the assembly line
and company records indicate it was delivered in December 1970,
Cole said.
   In a telephone interview from his home, he said it was
impossible to determine immediately whether any trouble had been
reported earlier about the plane because those records were
available only at company offices.
   Cole said initial reports received by Boeing indicated the plane
was 1,700 feet above the ground 10 miles from the Ahmadabad airport
but added that he was skeptical because ``that's much too low ...
it could even by a typographical error.''
   The pilot might have been trying to duck beneath the fog or
could have descended to that level and then climbed higher again
before the final landing approach, ``but that's all just
speculation,'' Cole said.
</TEXT>
