<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonTrial     10-19 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness, Defense Lawyer Clash at Bess Myerson Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief prosecution witness at the
divorce-fixing conspiracy trial of former Miss America Bess Myerson
admitted deceiving a grand jury and deliberately taping her own
mother, a co-defendant, for prosecutors.
   The fifth day of testimony by Sukhreet Gabel in U.S. District
Court on Tuesday was marked by stormy exchanges between Ms. Gabel
and Miss Myerson's lawyer during cross-examination.
   The lawyer, Frederick P. Hafetz, continued to chip away at the
credibility of the 39-year-old witness in the trial of her mother,
former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel; Miss Myerson and
Miss Myerson's lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso.
   Mrs. Gabel presided over the divorce trial of Capasso. The
former justice, 75, Miss Myerson, 64, and Capasso, 43, are charged
with a scheme to cut Capasso's support payments to his estranged
wife, Nancy. In exchange, prosecutors claim, Ms. Gabel was given a
$19,000-a-year city job by Miss Myerson, who was then the city's
cultural affairs commissioner.
   On Tuesday, Hafetz asked Ms. Gabel whether discrepancies in her
grand jury testimony meant she had committed perjury. She shot
back, ``I would request a copy of Black's law dictionary before I
am required to answer that question.''
   The reply of the highly educated witness prompted chuckles from
spectators, and even the judge, who defined perjury for her.
   Later, Hafetz _ his voice rising _ stated, ``You taped your own
mother purposefully.'' He added, ``Did you record your own mother
with a recorder supplied by courtesy of the U.S. government in June
of 1987? Yes or no, ma'am? Yes or no?''
   ``I recorded a conversation with my mother,'' she said, balking
at a ``yes'' or ``no'' answer.
   Judge John F. Keenan asked the question again.
   ``Yes,'' she replied.
   ``That wasn't hard, was it, Ms. Gabel?'' asked Hafetz, prompting
a smile from the witness and the comment, ``It wasn't painless.''
   Under questioning by prosecutors last week, Ms. Gabel testified
that when she learned her mother was presiding over Capasso's
divorce, she confronted her father over the telephone and was told,
``Let your mother handle this. She knows all about it.''
   But under questioning by Hafetz, Ms. Gabel conceded she did not
mention the conversation in three appearances before the grand jury
and several depositions to prosecutors.
   ``I knew I wasn't telling the truth, I was fully cognizant of
it,'' she said.
   ``You deliberately and consciously and intentionally omitted
information when you testified before the grand jury, isn't that
correct?'' asked Hafetz.
   ``Entirely correct,'' the witness replied.
   Hafetz is trying to prove that Ms. Gabel is an unreliable
witness, and yet is intelligent and capable enough to have deserved
the city job on her own merits. Otherwise, it might appear Miss
Myerson gave her the post to curry favor with her mother.
   On Monday, Ms. Gabel, admitted to being treated for clinical
depression and did not disagree when Hafetz suggested that
electro-shock treatments she had received ``made your memory
selective, like a swiss cheese with holes in it.''
   After Tuesday's session ended, Mrs. Gabel came up to the witness
stand and spoke with her daughter, who leaned forward. Before
leaving, Mrs. Gabel blew her daughter a kiss.
   The trial resumes Tuesday. Keenan ordered the delay so he could
attend a judicial conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
