<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-YugoslavGlance     10-19 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslav Glance,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are facts and figures on Yugoslavia's six republics and two
autonomous provinces:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia has 23 million people. It has three official
languages _ Serbo-Croat, Slovenian and Macedonian _ and at least 20
different ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Slovenia: A northern republic bordering Austria and Italy, is
home to most of Yugoslavia's 1.7 million Slovenes. It has the most
prosperous economy of Yugoslavia's six republics, with 8 percent of
the national population accounting for 24 percent of national
exports.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Croatia: The second most developed Yugoslav republic, has
resisted any attempt by Serbs to dominate Yugoslavia. It is home to
4.4 million Croats, and with Slovenia has most of country's Roman
Catholics. It was the birthplace of Communist Yugoslavia's founding
father, the late Josip Broz Tito.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bosnia-Herzegovina: The central Yugoslav republic, has most of
the country's 1.9 million Moslims, who became Moslim during five
centures of Turkish domination. Serbs and Croats are other major
ethnic groups in the republic.
   The capital is Sarajevo, where World War I was was started with
the assassination of Archduke Ferdinand of Austria, in June 1914.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Serbia: The country's largest republic, is home to most of the
8.1 million Serbs. The Serbian kingdom dominated Yugoslavia prior
to World War II, but has since been divided into the Serbian
republic proper and the two autonomous provinces of Vojvodina and
Kosovo.
   Serbia is a largely agricultural republic and its capital,
Belgrade, is also the federal capital and the country's largest
city, with a population of 1.5 million.
   The autonomous provinces of Serbia are:
   Vojvodina: Northeast of Belgrade, borders Hungary and Romania
and is home to a half million Hungarians and some 170,000 Romanians
in addition to the Serb majority. It is known as the breadbasket of
Yugoslavia because of its fertile plains.
   Kosovo: The province bordering Communist Albania is Yugoslavia's
most ethnically troubled region. It was the heart of Serbia's
medieval empire and is the site of some of the oldest monasteries
of the Serbian Orthodox church.
   It is dominated today by ethnic Albanians, who make up 90
percent of Kosovo's 2 million population, and are Moslims as a
result of Turkish domination. Thousands of Serbs and Montenegrins
from the Christian Slav majority have left Kosovo since ethnic
riots there in 1981 killed at least nine people.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Macedonia: Yugoslavia's southernmost and poorest republic is
home to most of the country's 1.3 million Macedonians. Most of its
meager earnings come from agriculture and its state-run industrial
enteprises are largely unprofitable.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Montenegro: A mountainous republic bordered by Albania at its
southernmost tip, has some earnings from tourism along the Adriatic
coast. It is home to some 600,000 Montenegrins, who in medieval
times had their own independent state but later adopted the Serbian
Orthodox religion. Yugoslavia's second poorest republic, it was
part of Serbia before World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhalesScience     10-19 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whales Science,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biologists Use Opportunity to Study Trapped Whales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELSON LAGOON, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunched over a workbench in a tiny
shack, biologist Geoff Carroll meticulously records the
surrealistic sounds of whales surfacing and breathing less than 100
yards away.
   Hooked to the portable tape deck next to him is a hydrophone
submerged in a pool surrounded by ice. With astonishing clarity
come the sounds of splashes, the whales' whooshing exhalations, and
occasional grinding static when the barnacle-covered skin of one of
the whales grates against the hydrophone.
   With public and media attention focused on the plight of three
California gray whales stranded in unusually early ice in the
Beaufort Sea, Carroll and his colleagues at the North Slope Borough
are trying to take advantage of an almost unprecedented scientific
opportunity.
   ``Seldom do you get the chance to study whales in the wild under
such ideal conditions,'' says Carroll as he logs the times the
whales surface and their rates of respiration.
   The closeup and relatively long-term study of the whales is
being made possible by their failure to leave their summer feeding
grounds promptly. For nearly two weeks, the whales have been
alternating between two small breathing holes about 75 yards apart.
   The whales, one of them more than 30 feet long, haven't been
inclined to use their bulk to break through the ice. When they were
first trapped, it was only a few inches thick. Now it is more than
one foot.
   ``They could do it if they just would,'' Carroll said of their
icebreaking potential.
   Larger bowhead whales, which arrive in the ice-choked Arctic
Ocean earlier and leave later, regularly break through several feet
of ice to breath.
   Outside, a few fingers of northern lights streak the
star-studded sky. A bonechilling wind persists against the
foam-insulated plywood walls of the ``sled shed,'' which was
dragged into position by a snowmobile.
   The primitive structure is warmed by a small space heater to
keep the equipment from freezing.
   A shotgun loaded with slugs hangs on a nearby hook. Before
stepping outside, the biologists scan the vicinity with a
flashlight, looking for the telltale green eyes of a polar bear.
The great white bears regularly hunt open water like this to nab
unwary seals or sticken whales.
   In the darkness, the sudden surfacing of a whale is startling,
its warm, moist breath palpable to anyone standing along the edge
of the ice.
   In the shed, the splashes and breath sounds are interrupted by
occasional moans and grunts _ vocalizations, the biologists call
them.
   ``Sometimes, they'll make a noise like a drum roll, like someone
beating on a bongo drum or a steel drum,'' he said, tapping his
fingers on the workbench to illustrate.
   But Carroll is surprised at how quiet the gray whales are
compared to the more loquacious bowheads.
   ``It is sort of fortunate that bowheads vocalize as much as they
do, or we could never count them acoustically. If they were as
quiet as these guys, it (acoustical counting) would be of no use at
all.''
   The bowheads are what the borough biologists are most familiar
with and interested in. The bowheads, up to 60 feet long, are the
staple of the traditional subsistence diet of the Eskimos.
   When international pressure threatened to end all whaling, the
borough and the Alaska Eskimo Whaling Commission began intensive
census studies to demonstrate there was an adequate bowhead
population to sustain limited subsistence whaling.
   But the biologists are more than willing to study the smaller
gray whales, an endangered species.
   ``It's interesting. It's a freak occurrence,'' says biologist
Craig George. ``I'm not sure how much it's going to add to gray
whale biology. And I'm not sure how much it's going to help us down
the road. But we're interested all the same.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
