<DOCNO> AP881019-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoForSale     10-19 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago For Sale,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0488 to fix heading.</HEAD>
<HEAD>City Wares For Sale: Ballot Boxes, Parking Meters, Manhole Covers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 21 years, the ballot boxes here were
controlled by Mayor Richard J. Daley. Now the city is selling them
_ for $75 each.
   Traffic lights, street signs and even parking meters are being
sold, along with the wooden boxes that held the votes which kept
late mayor and his Democratic machine in office.
   They're all prized wares at The City of Chicago Store, a place
where a buyer can tote home a manhole cover and turn it into a
coffee table.
   ``We started talking about this during the city's
sesquicentennial last year,'' said Lorraine Nadis, who proposed the
idea to the Chicago Tourism Council and the city's Department of
Cultural Affairs.
   ``Other cities have stores,'' she said. ``There's the San
Francisco bridge store. New York has a store and St. Louis has one,
too.
   ``Here, we'll try to have something from every city department
and every museum around. We have art from all over. It's not common
to find any of this stuff.''
   Ms. Nadis was talking and tending the counter at the same time.
The city-owned store, across the street from the Bismarck Hotel and
half a block from City Hall, had been open for a week but afternoon
business was undeniably slow Tuesday.
   No takers yet for $100 manhole covers, crusted with genuine
Chicago grime.
   Ballot boxes, gouged from years of being bounced from ward to
ward or tucked in a precinct captain's truck, have a small plastic
window to imagine the paper ballots once inside.
   ``An end table if someone wants to put glass on top of it,'' Ms.
Nadis suggested. ``Or as a collector's item; there's not too many
of these left.
   ``They all want to know if there are any ballots inside,'' she
added. ``I've only opened one. People are absolutely enthralled
with them.''
   The store also features banners that have waved from city light
posts to honor a symphony conductor, a presidential yacht, music
festivals and visits by foreign leaders.
   Book shelves hold Chicago's very own, such as Nelson Algren's
``Chicago, City On The Make,'' a book of love-hate prose for his
hometown, and analytical works on how Harold Washington, the city's
first black mayor, busted the Democratic machine and rose to power.
   There are pictures and pins, mugs and men's ties. Even city
rodents get their due. A city sanitation poster titled ``Public
Enemy'' has a rat crossed with a red line.
   Unfortunately, Ms. Nadis said, the store won't be able to get
every piece of city history.
   ``We wanted to get the aldermen's old chairs,'' she said,
referring to recent renovations in the City Council. ``But of
course the aldermen get first shot at things like that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-19 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after ``Black Monday,'' the day of the
world-wide stock market crash, share prices today rebounded
moderately on the Tokyo Stock Exchange and the dollar fell against
the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 126.76-point loser
Tuesday, regained 151.69 points, or 0.56 percent, finishing at
27,293.67. The index gained 81.18 points shortly after the market
opened and kept rising.
   ``Buying increased mainly toward the end of the afternoon
session,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage house.
   ``Although trading was not very active, participants traded a
variety of issues, which we consider was a good sign,'' he said,
speaking anonymously. He added that Emperor Hirohito's worsening
condition has held down trading. Volume traded on the first section
was estimated at 550 million shares.
   Hirohito, 87, has been bedridden for a month.
   But the analyst said the market was not effected by the
anniversary of ``Black Monday,'' which led the Tokyo market to
plunge 3,836.48 points when it opened the next day.
   Meanwhile, Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, referring
to the anniversary, noted Tuesday that the crash made Japan realize
``its responsibility in the world economy that it had not been
aware of,'' news reports said.
   Miyazawa told reporters after a Cabinet meeting that following
the crash, he ``felt strongly that if the Tokyo stock market was
not reliable, the world economy would face serious consequences.''
   Among issues attracting attention today were Nippon Telegraph
and Telephone Corp. The government will sell 1.5 million NTT shares
Thursday and Friday at about $15,000 per share, a 3.5 percent
discount from today's closing price of about $15,600.
   It will be the third government sale of NTT stock since the
company was privatized in 1985.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 126.85 yen,
down 0.85 yen from Tuesday. Opening at 127.15 yen, it moved lower
and ranged between 126.85 and 127.60 yen.
   Today's closing rate was the lowest since Jun. 21, when the
dollar ended trading at 126.33.
   ``There was no market-affecting news to lead the trading in a
certain direction,'' said Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank.
   Investors were uncertain whether to sell or buy the dollar at
the current level, but a few more sold than bought because of less
concern about the U.S. economic growth, he said.
   ``There was no hint of intervention by the Bank of Japan today,
but I believe it won't intervene until the dollar hits the 125-yen
level,'' Yamasaki said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
