<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito's Condition Worsen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's condition worsened today as he
coughed up blood for the first time since his health suddenly
declined exactly one month ago.
   The emperor's daughter, Atsuko Ikeda, said Hirohito was awake
but hardly responded to her when she visited him today, news
reports said.
   Mrs. Ikeda told reporters her father coughed repeatedly during
the five-minute visit to his bedside in the Imperial Palace, Kyodo
News Service said.
   Imperial Household Agency officials said the 87-year-old emperor
was resting and his condition had stabiized.
   The officials said Hirohito coughed up a small amount of blood
around midnight Tuesday, and later discharged more blood from his
bowels. In response, doctors gave him a 0.42-pint blood
transfusion, they said.
   In the past month, he has received 20.2 pints in transfusions,
more than twice the normal amount circulating in his body.
   Imperial officials have declined to confirm or deny news reports
that Hirohito has cancer in the area of his upper intestine.
   Court physicians have unsuccessfully tried to combat Hirohito's
anemia and hemorrhaging with blood transfusions. In recent days
they have allowed the world's oldest living monarch to eat a few
spoonfuls of weak porridge, and acknowledged he is losing strength
because his intravenous feedings cannot supply enough nutrients.
