<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0514EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     10-19 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Members Arrested As Central Committee Meets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissenting members of Afghanistan's
dominant, Soviet-style party were arrested prior to a meeting of
the party's leadership, an official source said today.
   Other Afghan sources said the Central Committee of the People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan began its session this morning,
although no official announcement was made.
   The session follows reports of disagreements among party leaders
as the Afghan government seeks to reach a settlement with Moslem
guerrillas who have been fighting Afghan and Soviet forces for
nearly a decade.
   President Najib, the party's general secretary, and senior
government officials have spoken repeatedly of broadening the base
of the government in hopes of ending the war.
   The arrests of an undisclosed number of party members was
announced Tuesday night on government television. The broadcast
provided no further details.
   The official source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the arrests were ``due to some opposition activity that they were
launching against the policy of national reconciliation.''
   National reconciliation is the term given to efforts to
negotiate an end to the war with the guerrillas.
   These efforts have accelerated with the withdrawal of Soviet
troops, scheduled to be completed Feb. 15. But the guerrillas, who
are supported by Pakistan and the United States, have refused to
negotiate with any government headed by Najib.
   The official source said he did not know whether those arrested
belonged to the 140-member Central Committee. He said most of the
arrests were made in Kabul, where committee members have converged
the past week and were thought to be meeting in separate groups
before joining for a full meeting.
   He said he did not know the number of arrests, but deduced
``from the way it was announced'' that it was more than three.
   Najib has already made several shows of broadening his
government, but these efforts have failed to bring the Mujahedeen
to negotiations.
   Najib in May named a new prime minister, Mohammad Hasan Sharq,
who is not a party member but has had close ties with the Kremlin.
   Although the party is officially portrayed as unified, it has
two wings _ the more hawkish Khalq and Parcham _ that have had a
history of periodically violent rivalry since the party's founding
in 1965.
   Najib belongs to the Parcham faction and took power in 1986.
   The party first achieved power in 1978 when Noor Mohammad Taraki
ousted the government of Mohammad Daoud, who had overthrown King
Zahir Shah in 1973.
   Taraki was ousted by another coup in 1979 and replaced by
Hafizullah Amin, who was deposed three months later when the
Soviets entered Afghanistan. Amin was succeeded by Babrak Karmal,
who was moved aside by Najib.
   Under an accord signed April 14 in Geneva, the Soviet Union
began withdrawing troops May 15. An estimated 50,000 to 60,000
remain.
</TEXT>
