<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BurnedChurch     10-19 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burned Church,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Suspected In Second Fire At Black Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK FORK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black congregation whose 125-year-old
church was destroyed by arson in April has been hit by a suspicious
blaze that left only a wall standing two weeks before the
dedication of the reconstructed building.
   ``You try not to get discouraged,'' said Wesley Matlock, whose
great-grandparents founded The New Bethel African Methodist
Episcopal Church of Rock Fork. ``We want to have a church, but this
hurts a lot.''
   The cause of the early morning blaze has not been determined,
but Lt. Dennis Fischer, chief of detectives for the Madison County
sheriff's department said it was being investigated as arson.
   ``We have invitations to the church reopening sitting in boxes,
and we were waiting to put them in the mail,'' said Donna Jackson,
wife of the pastor, the Rev. Steven Jackson.
   ``We even had hats made for the construction workers saying, `I
helped rebuild Rock Fork.' It's so sad,'' she said. ``Nobody really
knows what to do. We're just in such a state of shock.''
   The small church, whose 25 members are black, has been sitting
on an isolated site in this southern Illinois community since 1863.
But in recent years, it has been the target of a bombing and
vandalism. Last year, it was defaced with racial epithets.
   The neighborhood around the church is predominantly white, but
church members say they know of no organized group causing the
damage. They said they have not received any threats.
   Each time, church members joined with volunteers from nearby
Alton and Godfrey, north of St. Louis, to clean up the damage. This
time, they aren't sure what to do.
   ``We don't know right now,'' said the pastor.
   Residents reported the blaze early Tuesday and the church was
``pretty well engulfed'' in flames by the time firefighters from
nearby Godfrey arrived, Fischer said. No injuries were reported.
   The fire left only one wall of the church standing _ just two
weeks before it was scheduled to reopen after the April 16 fire
that authorities also said was the work of arsonists. The repair
work had been nearly complete, and the congregation was to
rededicate the church Nov. 6.
   Instead, they gathered Tuesday to inspect more damage. Jackson
estimated the damage at about $50,000. He said the building was
insured.
   No arrests have been made in either fire.
   ``I just think it's a few sick vandals, young adults,'' Matlock
said.
   Virginia DeBruce, another church member, said, ``We've been here
for years, and all of this just started lately. I guess it's just
the world changing.''
</TEXT>
