<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IndiaCrash-Plane     10-19 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India Crash-Plane,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Look At The Boeing 737</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-India-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing 737 has been a success as the world's
most popular commercial aircraft, but the workhorse jetliner has
had its share of tragedy since its introduction 20 years ago.
   The latest disaster involving a 737 occurred in India this
morning, when an Indian Airlines 737 crashed on final approach to
Ahmadabad airport about 300 miles southwest of New Delhi, killing
130 of the 135 people aboard, officials said.
   The plane was trying to land in heavy fog, but the cause of the
crash was not known, said G.K. Rawal, police inspector at the
airport.
   A Boeing Commercial Airplanes investigator headed to the crash
scene from Bombay, company spokesman Tom Cole said here.
   On Monday, National Transportation and Safety Board officials
revealed that a foot-long crack had been discovered on a
Continental Airlines 737 as it was stripped for repainting Oct. 5.
   The aircraft came under increased scrutiny after April 28, when
part of the fuselage of an Aloha Airlines 737 peeled off at 24,000
feet over Hawaii. A flight attendant was swept to her death and 61
passengers were hurt, but the pilot managed to land the plane
safely.
   That accident triggered inspections of older 737s, and increased
pressure to update U.S. commercial jets.
   A little more than a month ago, on Sept. 16, a 737 crashed and
burst into flames after running into a flock of birds in northwest
Ethiopia. Thirty-one people were killed.
   On Aug. 31, 1987, a Thai Airways 737 fell into the sea off the
southern island of Phuket, killing all 83 people aboard.
   One of the best-known air disasters involving the aircraft
occurred in January 1982, when an Air Florida 737 crashed into a
bridge after taking off from National Airport in Washington, D.C.,
killing 78 people.
   In August 1981, a Far Eastern Air Transport 737 exploded 22,000
feet over Taiwan, killing all 110 people aboard.
   The 737 entered service in 1968, and is the world's most popular
commercial aircraft with more than 2,000 ordered in five different
models.
   The Indian Airlines plane was the 271st off the Boeing assembly
line and company records indicate it was delivered in December
1970, Cole said.
   The plane in the Aloha accident was No. 152, the Far Eastern Air
Transport was No. 151 and the Continental plane was No. 170. All
three were built in 1969.
   Indian Airlines, the domestic carrier, has come under criticism
recently for its poor management and maintenance record and
frequent delays. Today's crash was the 16th by an Indian Airlines
carrier during the past 25 years.
   An Indian Airlines 737 carrying 123 passengers crash-landed on
its belly June 19 after its landing gear failed, and an engine
caught fire as it slid along the runway, but no one was injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0068 </DOCNO>
