<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-US 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-US, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0522,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Defends U.S. Bases Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf, ``I knew...' to UPDATE with
protest; picks up 5th pvs: The United...
^By ROBERT H. REID</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino today
dismissed criticism of the new U.S. bases agreement and the largest
political party in Congress pledged to support the controversial
accord.
   The agreement, signed Monday in Washington by Secretary of State
George Shultz and Philippine Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus,
allows the United States to maintain six bases here until 1991 in
return for $962 million in aid over the final two years of the pact.
   But critics charged that the government settled for too little
compensation. Filipino negotiators had demanded $1.2 billion
annually.
   ``I knew that it would not get total acceptance,'' Mrs. Aquino
said of the agreement. ``But I still believe Secretary Manglapus
did a very commendable job and that certainly, it is a big
improvement from the previous bases agreement.''
   About 150 members of the leftist May First Movement shouted
anti-American slogans and burned a U.S. flag near the U.S. Embassy
today to protest the agreement. Riot police prevented them from
marching to the embassy grounds and they dispersed without violence.
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile said the agreement showed that
Mrs. Aquino had secretly decided to work for extending the bases
even after their lease expires in September 1991.
   ``The terms contained in the just-concluded agreement strongly
indicate to us that the Aquino regime will continue to foist upon
our people this onerous burden of a military presence on Philippine
soil,'' he said.
   The United States had been paying $180 million a year for use of
Clark Air Base, Subic Bay naval base and four smaller installations.
   Despite the increase, there has been strong criticism of the
agreement because the government raised public expectations that it
would hold out for $1.2 billion a year as well as other concessions
that Manglapus failed to win.
   The pro-Aquino ``Struggle of the Democratic Filipino'' party
said today that the agreement provided nearly three times as much
aid as the United States granted to now-ousted President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   ``Our party is satisfied with the agreement and will support it,
although we realize that more hard work is needed to resolve other
issues related to the American base facilities in our country,'' it
said.
   The party claims membership of 145 of the 202 House members and
six of the 23 senators.
   On Tuesday, the Senate debated whether Monday's agreement
required its approval in accordance with a constitutional provision
on international agreements, but was unable to resolve the issue
and postponed discussion to a later date.
   Mrs. Aquino said today she would discuss the ratification issue
with lawmakers but ``my legal advisers tell me that there is no
need for that.''
   Critics said the accord could prompt even stronger opposition to
the bases and raise doubts over whether the Philippines would
extend the lease on the facilities, which expires in September 1991.
   Under the Constitution, any extension must be approved by
two-thirds of the Senate, where anti-bases sentiment is strong.
   The agreement allows the United States to maintain its policy of
neither confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear weapons on
aircraft and ships visiting the bases.
   The constitution mandates that the Philippines adopt a policy of
freedom from nuclear weapons ``consistent with the national
interest.'' Legal experts say the phrase falls short of an outright
ban.
   Communist guerrillas, whose demand for the removal of the bases
has fanned a 20-year-old rebellion, accused the goverment of
``shamelessly selling out'' Philippine sovereignty.
</TEXT>
