<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficersShot     10-19 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officers Shot,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Policemen Killed in One Night in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers, one of them working
undercover in an alleged crack den, were killed within hours of
each other in separate shootings in upper Manhattan, authorities
said.
   Police arrested two suspects, including at least one of the
alleged gunmen, in what Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said was
the first case he knew of two police officers being killed in one
night in different incidents.
   Undercover Officer Christopher Hoban, 26, of Brooklyn, was shot
early Tuesday night during a drug raid when one of three cocaine
dealers guessed that he and his partner were policemen, Ward said.
One of the alleged dealers was also killed.
   Less than three hours later, Officer Michael J. Buczek, 24, of
Suffern was killed when he and his partner responded to a routine
medical emergency call in Harlem and ended up chasing two
``suspicious'' men, Ward said.
   The deaths raise to seven the number of officers killed on duty
this year.
   After each of Tuesday's killings, Ward and Mayor Edward I. Koch
met with the officers' families, then relayed the grim facts of
each case at hospital news conferences.
   ``It's an enormous tragedy. ... It's really overwhelming,'' Koch
said.
   Hoban, a four-year veteran, was shot twice as he and his
partner, Officer Michael Jermyn, 25, prepared to buy a gram of
cocaine prior to a raid at what residents said was a crack den. One
of three drug dealers believed the undercover policemen were
officers and one dealer began firing a .357-caliber Magnum,
striking Hoban in the chest and head, the commissioner said.
   A dealer, Manuel DeLarosa, 23, of Puerto Rico, was killed by the
officers during the struggle. The second suspect, Flavio Prophete,
49, was caught fleeing the building and the third suspect was being
sought, Ward said.
   The second shooting occurred as Buczek and his partner prepared
to leave a building and noticed two men ``acting suspicious'' in
the lobby, said Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell, a police spokesman.
   The officers asked them to stop, Ward said, but they fled. The
officers pursued them less than a block before each officer caught
up with one suspect, Ward said.
   However, one of the suspects spun around and killed Buczek with
two blasts to the chest and abdomen from a semiautomatic weapon,
Ward said.
   The second man apparently escaped in the commotion as the
surviving officer fired four shots.
   Alice McGillion, a police spokeswoman, said the suspected gunman
``made a comment as he was going down the block that he had just
shot a cop.'' With the help of descriptions from residents who
heard the comment, police apprehended the man almost immediately,
she said.
   His identity was being withheld early today pending arraignment,
O'Donnell said.
</TEXT>
