<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--NameCalling     10-19 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Name Calling,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foul-Mouthed Students Will Be Punished in LA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foul-mouthed students will be punished for
unsavory utterances or offending epithets scrawled on lockers under
a policy designed to stifle an outbreak of schoolyard name-calling.
   The measure, proposed by board member Jackie Goldberg, requires
schools to develop discipline plans for those who utter slurs
against any person on the basis of race, religion, sex, sexual
orientation, disabilities, immigration status or political belief.
   A companion measure also approved unanimously Monday by the
Board of Education requires each school to decide how to discipline
students for acts of physical violence that stem from hatred or
bigotry.
   Ms. Goldberg said she hopes the measures will help reverse a
noticeable increase in the use of slurs on playgrounds and locker
graffiti. She attributed the increase to a lapse in sensitivity
since the 1960s.
