<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FordFight     10-19 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford Fight,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement Proposed In Ford Trust Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Henry Ford II will
receive $10.5 million a year for life under a proposed settlement
intended to end the family's legal squabble over the auto magnate's
$350 million trust.
   Attorneys for Ford's third wife, Kathleen Duross Ford, are
expected to petition Palm Beach Circuit Judge Vaughn Rudnick today
for approval of the plan, which would give Mrs. Ford seven times
the minimum annual payment bequeathed by her husband.
   In addition, the settlement would grant Mrs. Ford, 48, ownership
of the couple's homes in Palm Beach, Grosse Pointe, Mich., and
London, and rights to purchase three additional Ford residences.
   ``I hope this puts an end to the litigation, but we'll just have
to see what happens,'' said Robert Montgomery, Mrs. Ford's attorney.
   ``The real benefit is that now the trust can get on with the
administration and not be bogged down in the sniping,'' said
attorney Arthur England, also representing Mrs. Ford.
   Meanwhile, a guardian representing the financial interests of
minor and unborn heirs to Ford's estate said they are protected in
the proposed settlement.
   Retired Palm Beach County Circuit Judge Robert Hewitt, appointed
to represent four minor grandchildren, unborn grandchildren and any
offspring, recommended Rudnick approve the settlement.
   In some versions of the Ford story transmitted Tuesday, The
Associated Press inadvertently reported an outdated development
that had once threatened the settlement.
   Rudnick's ruling on the proposed settlement was delayed Sept. 26
when an attorney representing the grandchildren suggested
appointment of a form of guardian. Attorneys at the time had argued
over calling in such a guardian, but all attorneys involved were
pleased at Hewitt's recommendation, the Fort Lauderdale News and
Sun-Sentinel reported Tuesday.
   Rudnick's ruling, expected in the next few days, should settle
the widow's lawsuit challenging the administration of the trust.
   She and Edsel Ford II, Henry Ford's son by a previous marriage,
had disagreed over how the money should be invested, which attorney
would be counsel for the trust and whether the trust should pay
family friend William Donaldson $1 million a year to manage the
money as a third trustee.
   Specific terms of the settlement agreement have not been
disclosed, but Mrs. Ford's attorneys said she withdrew her
objection to Donaldson. His payments under the settlement haven't
been disclosed.
   Mrs. Ford is entitled to receive a minimum of $1.5 million a
year from the trust.
   Ford died at age 70 in September 1987. The family had hoped to
avoid public airing of their dispute, but it erupted when Mrs. Ford
objected to the selection of Donaldson, a former undersecretary of
state.
</TEXT>
