<DOCNO> AP881019-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-People-CookeDivorce 1stLd-Writethru a0459 10-19 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Cooke Divorce, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Divorced Wife of Washington Redskins' Owner Promises Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WARRENTON, Va.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with Suzanne Cooke comments today; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The just-divorced wife of billionaire
Washington Redskins owner Jack Kent Cooke said today she will wage
a ``long, hard battle'' to win generous support for her infant
daughter.
   ``The battle has just begun, because I have my daughter to
protect,'' said Suzanne Martin Cooke, 32.
   Cooke, 75, was granted a divorce from his third wife last week,
but child support and a financial disposition of the prenuptial
agreement signed by both parties are still at issue.
   Fauquier County, Va., Circuit Court Judge W. Shore Robinson has
scheduled a hearing Dec. 12 to rule on matters pertaining to the
divorce, including paternity of the child. Mrs. Cooke said she
asked for blood tests to determine paternity of 9-month-old
Jacqueline Kent Cooke to put to rest ``the vicious rumors going
around Washington.''
   Cooke's lawyer, Burke McCahill of Leesburg, Va., said today, ``I
can't really offer any comment right now'' when asked for reaction
to Mrs. Cooke's statements. He also would not comment on whether
Cooke had denied paternity of the child, or on whether Cooke has
agreed to submit to blood tests.
   Mrs. Cooke, in a telephone call to The Associated Press, said,
``I want to make sure my daughter is taken care of as well as his
two sons were taken care of, as far as education, housing. ...No
amount of money could ever pay for the damage he's done ... to hurt
his poor, innocent daughter. You can't put a figure on it.''
   ``There is no financial settlement. It's going to be a long,
hard battle ... '' she said. ``His problem is getting bigger and
bigger every day.''
   According to court documents, Cooke had agreed to marry Suzanne
Martin on July 24, 1987, on condition that she terminate a
pregnancy that began in early June.
   After the marriage, she backed down on the promise and the
couple separated about four weeks later, court papers said. Cooke
filed for divorce in October.
   Jacqueline Kent Cooke was born on Jan. 25, 1988, six days before
the Redskins won the National Football League's Super Bowl
championship.
   Under terms of a prenuptial agreeement, Mrs. Cooke would be
entitled to $50,000 a year for three years after the divorce, plus
use of a Watergate apartment for five years and a new Jaguar. In
contesting the divorce, she sought a $15 million lump-sum
settlement, spousal support of $10,000 a month, custody of the baby
and $8,000 a month in child support.
   Cooke is one of the richest men in the country, according to the
current issue of Forbes magazine. He owns the Redskins, the
Chrysler Building in New York, the Los Angeles Daily News, a $44
million horse-racing stable in Lexington, Ky., and a cable
television system.
   His first wife was awarded a $41 million divorce settlement in
1979 _ which made the Guinness Book of World Records as the largest
such settlement _ and his second marriage lasted 10 months.
</TEXT>
