<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSRuling     10-19 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Ruling,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bars Doctors From Telling About Positive AIDS Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLATHE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge permanently barred a man's doctors
from telling his ex-wife that he had tested positive for the AIDS
virus.
   A lawyer for the man, identified in court documents only as John
Doe, said the ruling Tuesday could have nationwide implications.
   Johnson County District Judge Marion Chipman said in his order
issuing a permanent injunction that the man would be substantially
and irreparably injured by the release of his test results to his
ex-wife by Prime Health, a Kansas City health maintenance
organization.
   Court documents said the man does not have AIDS but has tested
positive for the virus.
   Chipman's opinion noted that the man signed an affidavit saying
he has no intention of engaging in sexual relations with his
ex-wife any more and that the woman has tested negative twice for
AIDS exposure, the second time after her last sexual contact with
the man two years ago. The document did not indicate why the
unidentified woman had decided to have AIDS tests previously.
   Prime Health said it provided health care for both the man and
the woman. The company had said the woman should be advised of the
test results ``even if she has not had sex with him recently, to
alert her to the potential danger she may face.''
   Frank Saunders, a lawyer for Prime Health, said after the ruling
that the health organization would abide by the ruling. Asked about
an appeal, he said, ``I doubt it. They're divorced now. ... The
threat isn't there anymore.''
   David Waxse, an American Civil Liberties Union lawyer for the
man, said the ruling could be the first nationwide where a person
has had to get an injunction to prevent his health care provider
from releasing the information that he has tested positive for AIDS.
   ``For other court cases with similar issues, it could have
nationwide implications,'' Waxse said. ``We think (the judge's)
legal reasons may have application to a wide range of cases.''
   Chipman ruled the man's right to privacy would be violated if
Prime Health were allowed to reveal the results to anyone,
including the man's ex-wife.
   ``We are very pleased that Judge Chipman could rationally look
at the issues and decide it based on legal principles involved and
not based on the hysteria often accompanying the AIDS issue,''
Waxse said.
</TEXT>
