<DOCNO> AP881019-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Nobel-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0569 10-19 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nobel-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0569,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winner Calls Nobel `Icing on the Cake'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `He said...', with 6 grafs to add reax from
chemistry winner who resides in U.S., add background on two physics
winners, picking up 12th graf, `Science is...'. SUBS last graf to
give full name of CERN.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the Americans who shared a Nobel Prize in physics said
today that being a scientist is enjoyable and winning a Nobel is
``icing on the cake.''
   ``I will recommend it to anybody,'' said Leon Lederman, 66, in a
telephone interview from his home in Batavia, Ill., where he is
director of the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory. ``It's
really very pleasant. It's a nice way to be awakened.''
   The official calling him with the news from Stockholm at 6 a.m.
CDT ``apologized for waking me up, but I said, `That's quite all
right, anytime.'''
   Lederman shared the prize, announced today in Stockholm, Sweden,
with Melvin Schwartz, 55, a former professor at Stanford University
and now president of Digital Pathways, in Mountain View, Calif.;
and Jack Steinberger, an American citizen who lives in Switzerland.
   The three did their prize-winning work together in the early
1960s at Brookhaven National Laboratory on New York's Long Island
while they were all associated with Columbia University in New York
City.
   Schwartz said he also was asleep when he got the news by phone
at 4 a.m. PDT at his home in San Francisco.
   ``Obviously, I'm very excited about it,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``It's been a long time since we did this piece of
work.''
   ``The work was the first pioneering effort to essentially put
together an experiment in which neutrinos ... which very rarely
interact in matter at all ... interact,'' Schwartz said.
   Lederman said the prize ``was very, very pleasing. Actually,
doing science is a great deal of pleasure even if you don't win the
prize, but winning it is icing on the cake.''
   ``This is an experiment that was completed and published in
1961. Those poor guys in Stockholm have been puzzling over it ever
since and finally decided it was good stuff.''
   No Americans were among the three winners of the Nobel prize in
chemistry, also announced today in Sweden, but one of the three
West Germans getting the honor currently resides in the United
States. Johann Deisenhofer, 45, works at the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute in Dallas.
   ``I can't believe it yet,'' Deisenhofer said today. ``I'm still
in a state of shock.'' As for what plans he had now that he had
won, he said: ``I haven't made up my mind yet, as you can imagine.
What I plan now is to have breakfast.''
   The chemists were honored for research into proteins involved in
photosynthesis.
   Physics winner Lederman got his bachelor's at City College of
New York before getting his master's and doctorate from Columbia.
He taught physics at the university for more than two decades.
   Schwartz received both his bachelor's degree and doctorate from
Columbia, where he taught physics for eight years before going to
Stanford University in the mid-1960s. He became president of
Digital Pathways in 1983.
   Lederman said he had no plans yet regarding the prize money and
joked, ``I haven't decided whether to buy a castle in Spain or a
string of race horses.''
   ``Science is a tremendous career to follow. You have fun all the
time, some blood, sweat and tears too, but it is ultimately
rewarding.
   ``Some day, some kid who is now in high school will find out how
to use this information (about the neutrino) to bring benefits to
all of society.''
   He said it was the first Nobel prize for a staff member at
Fermilab, where he has been director since 1979.
   ``I hope it might encourage them (federal budget makers) to send
us more money and the supercollider,'' he said, referring to the
proposed research facility for which several sites in the country
are competing.
   Fermilab, already home of one of the world's most powerful atom
smashers, is operated by a consortium of 54 research-oriented
universities in the United States and Canada under contact with the
U.S. Energy Department.
   Steinberger, 67, was born in Bad Kissingen, West Germany, and is
an American citizen. However, the Swedish Royal Academy of Sciences
officially lists his nationality as Swiss. He has been a physicist
at the European Organization for Nuclear Research, or CERN, in
Geneva, since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
