<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Explosion 3rdLd-Writethru   10-19 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Explosion, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0608,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Five Israelis Near Lebanon Border</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with claim of responsibility,
details, background. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded today near a border
crossing with Israel, killing at least five Israelis and wounding
11 others in an army convoy, security sources said.
   The Islamic Resistance, a coalition of Shiite Moslem factions
linked to both the Palestine Liberation Organization and Iran,
claimed responsibility for the attack and said it was a suicide
operation.
   But the security sources said on condition of anonymity that the
bomb-laden vehicle was detonated by remote control while parked
about 650 feet from the ``Good Fence'' border point about 20 miles
east of Tyre.
   United Nations sources in south Lebanon said an explosion at
1:30 p.m. destroyed four Israeli jeeps.
   ``There apparently are some casualties since there are
ambulances in the area,'' one U.N. source said on condition of
anonymity. It was not known if the victims were soldiers.
   The security sources said two Israeli helicopter gunships later
began airlifting casualties from the border village of Kfar Kela.
   Other gunships were seen strafing the fields around the scene of
the blast, apparently to protect the rescue mission from possible
guerrilla attacks.
   A witness told reporters in Tyre that he saw a civilian van
driving behind the Israeli convoy when the blast occurred. That
suggested a suicide attack, rather than a remote-controlled bomb as
reported by the security sources.
   The Islamic Resistance said in a statement relesed in Beirut,
``One of our mujahedeen (holy warriors) carried out a suicide
operation against an Israeli convoy in Kfar Kela, inflicting heavy
casualties among Israeli soldiers.''
   The explosion appeared to be the most devastating attack on
Israeli soldiers since a lone Palestinian commando flew across the
Lebanese border in a hang glider on Nov. 26, killed six soldiers
and was slain.
   Israel carved out a six-to-10-mile-wide security zone along its
border with Lebanon when it withdrew the bulk of its troops from
Lebanon in 1985 after a three-year occupation. The purpose of the
buffer was to prevent guerrilla infiltrations into Israel.
   But the estimated 1,000 Israelis who patrol the enclave along
with allied militiamen of the estimated 2,000-strong South Lebanon
Army have been regular targets of guerrilla attacks.
   Israel usually retaliates for attacks against its troops by
sending warplanes to bomb Palestinian and Lebanese Moslem guerrilla
bases in south Lebanon.
   The last anti-Israeli attack was Aug. 19 when a Lebanese car
blew up near an Israeli army jeep in the buffer zone, slightly
injuring three Israeli soldiers.
</TEXT>
