<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PhysicsWinners     10-19 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Physics Winners,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Nobel Physics Laureates Are U.S. Citizens</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the winners of the 1988 Nobel
Prize in physics are natives of New York state, and the third is a
naturalized U.S. citizen from West Germany.
   Leon M. Lederman was born in Buffalo July 15, 1922. He earned a
doctorate in physics in 1951, and became a professor at Columbia
University seven years later. He is now director of the Fermi
National Accelerator Laboratory in Batavia, Ill., where he is
continuing work on particle research.
   Melvin Schwartz, who was born on Nov. 2, 1932 in New York and
earned his doctorate in physics in 1958. After working on the
prize-winning project, he took a professorship at Stanford
University in 1966. He has now left academia to start a private
company, Digital Pathways, Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., which
specializes in computer communications.
   Jack Steinberger was born May 25, 1921, in Bad Kissingen, now in
West Germany. He earned his doctorate in 1948. Two years later he
became a professor at Columbia, where he retained a post until
1971. In 1968 he moved to Geneva, Switzerland to join the CERN
research laboratory.
   The Royal Academy of Sciences listed him as Swiss in its
citation for the prize, but mentioned his American citizenship in
its background paper on his achievements.
</TEXT>
