<DOCNO> AP881019-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BarricadedNuns     10-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barricaded Nuns,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Superior Of Barricaded Nuns Goes To Media To Present Her Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five nuns who have locked
themselves in their monastery protesting liberalizing changes in
their way of life are forgetting their vow of obedience, says their
mother superior.
   As the dispute has escalated among the Carmelite nuns over how
to live a cloistered life of prayer, both sides have turned to the
media to plead their cases.
   Mother Teresa Hewitt, prioress of the Monastery of the Most
Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel, called in reporters Tuesday
and in front of bright lights and cameras called the rebellion
``attempted anarchy.''
   She said she has received hate mail from around the country
since the five nuns moved into the monastery's infirmary Oct. 4 and
demanded their religious order return to a more conservative
lifestyle.
   The five nuns say they are protesting the innovations of
allowing them some use of radio, television, candy and newspapers.
But the real issue, said Mother Teresa, is their refusal to obey
her.
   ``I will not give in to attempted anarchy, of a total disregard
for the rules of the order,'' she said. ``What if the governor of
Massachusetts was voted president and all the people who supported
Mr. Bush rebelled?''
   ``The nuns have an obligation, because of their vows, to respect
their prioress whether they like the person or don't like the
person.''
   Mother Teresa defended the changes she has made since becoming
prioress 14 months ago, saying the Roman Catholic Church is
constantly evolving and that the changes were well within the
constitution of the order.
   Sister John of the Cross, one of the barricaded nuns who has
acted as a spokeswoman, said their allegiance to the order's rules
supersedes allegiance to their superior.
   ``We're saying she has deviated from the rules,'' Sister John
said in a telephone interview. ``We vow obedience to the ruling
constitution, and it's the reponsibility of the prioress to uphold
the constitution.''
   It is up to the Vatican to issue a final report and
recommendations for settling the matter, according to the Rev.
Kevin Culligan, who tried unsuccesfully to resolve the dispute last
week.
</TEXT>
