<DOCNO> AP881019-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   10-19 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0874</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   Oct. 13
   The Register-Guard, Eugene, Ore., on protecting whistle-blowers:
   Headed for the president's desk is a bill imposing major new
protections for federal workers who expose bureaucratic fraud,
abuse, corruption and waste. ...
   Information revealed by a whistle-blower can certainly embarrass
an entrenched bureaucracy and ... the administration. But, if
corrective action is taken, the embarrassment can be ... quickly
replaced with pride in a better-run agency. ...
   The government will now have to provide ``clear and convincing
evidence'' ... that whistle-blowing was not a factor in a personnel
decision. ...
   It's taken four years of often bitter struggle to forge a
compromise whistle-blower protection bill that both Congress and
the White House could accept. ...
   President Reagan should now take the next step and sign this
important and badly needed legislation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 13
   Huntington (W.Va.) Herald-Dispatch on what students don't know:
   Almost all 200 of the 17-year-old high school students
interviewed for a recent ABC-TV documentary could identify Michael
Jackson and Madonna, but fewer than half recognized the names of
Daniel Ortega and the Ayatollah Khomeini.
   One student thought the Ayatollah was a Russian gymnast.
   Two-thirds of the students didn't know about Chernobyl. One
guessed that it was Cher's full name. More forgivably, perhaps,
only a third knew the names of this year's vice presidential
candidates.
   Asked to identify the Holocaust, one student guessed it was a
``Jewish holiday.''
   Mind you, the youngsters interviewed, while perhaps not the
brightest or the best, were not inner-city dropouts, but seniors at
respected, middle-class high schools.
   Little wonder that ABC, in titling its documentary based on the
survey, decided to call it ``America's Kids: Why They Flunk.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 17
   The Honolulu Star-Bulletin on the Philippine bases accord:
   Agreement on terms for the next two years of operation of U.S.
military bases in the Philippines is an encouraging sign that the
two long-time allies can continue to work together.
   It offers hope that the government of President Corazon Aquino
will agree to let the bases remain when the current agreement
governing their use expires in 1991.
   Although Clark Air Force Base and Subic Bay Naval Base, the
principal U.S. installations, may not be irreplaceable, they are
certainly very important in meeting U.S. strategic needs in the
Western Pacific and Indian Ocean.
   Moving those facilities elsewhere would be difficult at best.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 17
   Times Record, Brunswick, Maine, on the ACLU and the presidential
campaign:
   The American Civil Liberties Union has taken a shellacking at
the hands of Vice President George Bush during the presidential
campgain.
   As the ACLU is a nonpartisan organization devoted to protecting
the basic rights set forth in the Constitution, one could
reasonably infer that Bush also takes a dim view of civil liberties.
   That's probably not the case, but the fact that Bush has gotten
such mileage out of criticizing Gov. Michael Dukakis' ACLU
membership suggests many Americans have little appreciation of the
civil liberties they enjoy. ...
   In the waning days of the Bush-Dukakis campaign, voters should
think twice about candidates who cast aspersions on those who
cherish and defend American civil liberties.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 14
   The Evening Times, Pawtucket, R.I., on the presidential debates:
   The most unfortunate aspect of the presidential debates is not
that they are not true debates, but that they serve so little
purpose.
   As media-managed personality profiles _ meeting the candidates
up-close-and-personal in a highly structured format with little
room for serious discussion _ they are marvelous conveniences.
   They give every voter in the nation the opportunity to see the
two candidates side-by-side, to view their mannerisms, hear their
voices, check out their apparel.
   Of course, if that's what presidential elections are all about,
we could just as easily play out the race in the pages of
Gentleman's Quarterly.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 17
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on presidential news conferences:
   The presidential debates are over, but the larger question of
how often sitting presidents should face questioning from reporters
remains.
   A new report from the Harvard Commission on the Presidential
News Conference says such meetings don't come (often) enough, and
the delays hurt both the president and the press. ...
   Made up of a panel of journalists and scholars, the commission
said the presidential news conference has fallen into a ``serious
state of disarray'' during the Reagan White House.
   As a result, its report said, what should be a steady flow of
meaningful information becomes a stream that is first dammed up,
then released in a torrent to shouting reporters who are just as
eager to pounce on a gaffe as on a significant news story. ...
   The commission's recommendation _ twice monthly conferences
during the daytime, to ``encourage more substantive and useful
exchanges,'' and six meetings a year on prime-time television _
would be more fair to everyone involved.
   The next president should take it seriously.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
