<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   10-19 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0932</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: it seriously.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 17
   Mccomb (Miss.) Enterprise-Journal on America's return to space
flights:
   The recent, successful flight of the spaceship Discovery is a
cause for reflection on the United State space program. ....
   The only other country in the world which can even challegne the
U.S. record in space is the Soviet Union, which undertook 1,733
successful space launches from 1957 through 1985 _ compared to 844
for the United States.
   Only three other nations _ Japan, India and China _ and the
European Space Agency together undertook a total of 53 space
launches during the same period. ...
   So despite a year and a half of re-evaluation and retrenching in
the wake of the Challenger disaster, the American space program
remains the pace-setter, the ``team to beat'' in establishing new
frontiers in the far reaches of space.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 16
   The Peninsula Daily News, Port Angeles, Wash., on families:
   A few weeks ago, when it became apparent that the so-called
family issues were generating more talk than action in Congress,
Sen. Christopher Dodd observed, ``Never in the history of American
politics has there been a constituency so popular but with so
little political clout as the American family.''
   The Connecticut Democrat was proven right a few days ago. Major
bills designed to help American families died when the Senate could
not find the votes to end a filibuster by conservative Republicans.
   The lost legislation dealt with child care, unpaid leaves for
workers having babies or serious family illnesses, and tougher
penalties in child pornography cases.
   The package did not offer families all that much, but it was too
much for conservative opponents. It would be interesting to know
what they are willing to offer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 18
   Marietta (Ga.) Daily Journal on the National Service Act:
   Last year, Sen. (Sam) Nunn, (D-Ga.), as chairman of the
Democratic Leadership Council, put forward a radical and
deceptively simple idea: The National Service Act, a program
similar to the G.I. Bill.
   Under the plan, the nation's youth would be able to volunteer
for either military or civilian service.
   In return, they would be given a $10,000 voucher at the end of
their tour of duty to be used for education, vocational training or
as a down payment on a first home.
   The plan's cost in real dollars will be much less than the $15
billion price tag Nunn has placed on it.
   By allowing citizens to earn their college education, the need
for many federal loans and grants would disappear. ... The high
cost of the current all-volunteer military would be reduced. ...
   In an age where brilliance and innovative leadership have given
way to petty politics and demagoguery, Nunn's plan shines out like
a beacon.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 14:
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on the presidential debates:
   Pit bull personalities licking their chops in anticipation of a
major gaffe in (the Oct. 13) presidential debate were disappointed.
   So too were those cursed with an annoying passion for equating
the debates with sporting events. There were no home runs, no
knockouts, no major blunders.
   Measured in terms of poise, confidence and image projection,
Michael Dukakis won the first contest Sept. 25. George Bush won the
second. ...
   But measured in terms of substance and in terms of stands on
issues and the ability to express them within the restricted
confines of these two so-called debates, score it a draw for both
men, both times. ...
   These debates have been far more useful than the meaningless
clips on the evening news and the sludge-slinging campaign ads
hurled upon us.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 16
   Press-Telegram, Long Beach, Calif., on the prison furlough issue:
   Since the beginning of the campaign, Vice President Bush has
been bashing Michael Dukakis with the accusation that Massachusetts
releases hardened criminals who use their prison furloughs to
commit more crimes.
   Dukakis, rather than discuss furlough programs, shoots back that
the federal government's own furlough program releases people who
commit crimes in the short time they are outside, and that Bush, as
an administration official, has to accept responsibility for those
failures as well. ...
   A survey conducted by Contact Center, a non-profit criminal
justice information clearinghouse, found that federal and state
furlough programs gave some 53,000 prisoners more than 200,000
furloughs and encountered relatively few problems. ...
   Nearly half of the states reported to the Contact Center that
their programs are 98 percent successful. Six said they were 100
percent successful. ...
   Just one state _ Indiana _ reported problems so serious they
forced suspension of the program.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 12
   Daily Record, Morristown, N.J., on the barricaded Carmelite nuns:
   The media circus that has sprung up since a group of nuns
barricaded themselves inside a Morris Township, N.J., monastery is
an ironic commentary on the nuns' complaint that a withdrawn,
spiritual life is nearly impossible in today's world.
   The nuns, who are among the monastery's youngest members, oppose
the prioress' decision to impose modern intrusions, such as
television and snack foods, on their quest for a quiet
contemplative life.
   They feel such moves will pull them away from the spiritual
goals they had upon joining the church. ...
   Despite their desire for avoidance of today's world, much of
their quest for a contemplative, cloisterd existence is being
fought through the media.
</TEXT>
