<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   10-19 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0826</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the media.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 16
   Farmington (N.M.) Daily Times on the welfare reform bill:
   President Reagan signed a major welfare reform bill into law
last week that should free many Americans from government
dependency.
   The major provisions of the new law require states for the first
time to offer people on welfare a variety of education, training
and work programs.
   It features mandatory work provisions for some welfare
recipients and provides child care assistance to help them keep
jobs.
   At long last the government appears ready to break the welfare
cycle that in many cases has shackled generation after generation
to the welfare rolls.
   We commend Congress for passing the new law and the president
for signing it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 13
   The Commercial Appeal, Memphis, Tenn., on federal auto mileage
standards:
   Building big cars is what Detroit does best. But federal auto
mileage standards have threatened to put a crimp in the operation.
   In 1975 Congress established progressively higher
miles-per-gallon fleet requirements in order to conserve gasoline,
peaking at 27.5 miles per gallon by 1985.
   The government's action set off a scramble in the industry to
make smaller cars, a race in which American manufacturers, with the
exception of Chrysler, came out second-best to foreign companies.
   General Motors and Ford faced deep trouble. They weren't making
enough high-mileage small autos to keep their overall fleet average
at 27.5 mpg. So the U.S. Transportation Department relaxed the
standard, as it was allowed to do under law.
   Despite demands from some quarters that Detroit be required to
comply with the 27.5 mpg standard, U.S. Transportation Secretary
James Burnley decided to set it at 26.5, a slight increase over
1988 but a figure that GM and Ford apparently can live with.
   Burnley made a sensible decision.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 12
   Las Vegas Review-Journal on the vice presidential debate:
   The inquisitors at the vice presidential debate kept hammering
on Dan Quayle ... about what exactly he would do should something
happen to George Bush and Quayle ascend to the presidency.
   Quayle said he would pray and then call in the president's
advisers. That wasn't a good enough answer for Tom Brokaw, et al.,
who kept nagging the nominee.
   In the interest of fairness, the panel should have fired the
same question at Lloyd Bentsen.
   Watching Quayle squirm was entertaining but watching his
opponent explain the policy ramifications of a Bentsen presidency
would have been fascinating.
   That's because Bentsen differs with his running mate, Michael
Dukakis, on just about everything.
   Should Dukakis become president and some evil befall him, we can
imagine Lloyd Bentsen working mightily to undo just about every
major Dukakis policy. How come Brokaw and the gang didn't ask
Bentsen about that?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 14
   Daily Journal, Fergus Falls, Minn., on the media and
presidential campaigns:
   In a campaign that's been described as inane, among other
things, it was fitting that George Bush was asked during (the Oct.
13) debate about the negative tone of this year's presidential
campaign. ...
   Bush ... pointed out, rightly, that the media (had) to take some
of the blame.
   Instead of focusing on detailed policies and complicated
positions, the national television networks look instead for the
snappy one-liners that fit neatly into their newscasts.
   Pity the poor candidates this year and in future years who can't
condense their positions to five words or less.
   It is no doubt easier for candidates to repeat slogans than to
explain their positions; why should they take the difficult course
when that results only in their being ignored?
   Candidates have a responsibility to talk about issues. The news
media has a responsibility to ask questions about the issues and
not allow candidates to so easily take the low road.
   Both the candidates and the media have taken the easy way out in
this campaign; the American public should demand more the next time
around.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 17
   San Antonio Express-News on getting qualified federal workers:
   The federal government is losing its ability to hire employees
qualified to perform increasingly complicated and technical work
because of low salaries, declining prestige and needless
frustration, the Reagan administration recently told Congress.
   The result, according to a new report prepared for the federal
Office of Personnel Management, or OPM, is a ``slowly emerging
crisis of competence'' because skilled workers are leaving federal
service.
   Obviously, the next administration should try to mend fences
with the federal work force. Obviously, federal employees should be
granted raises as frequently as members of Congress, the Cabinet
and other top appointive posts.
   Contrary to what some politicians think, the government is only
as competent and united as those who work for it _ not those who
are elected or appointed to it.
</TEXT>
