<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0545 10-19 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls For Bipartisan Foreign Policy, Raps Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 11 grafs new with speech; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng: In
a pair</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today called
for an end to partisan conflict in U.S. foreign policy, even as he
renewed criticism of his Democratic rival's foreign policy views.
   Campaigning in Michigan, which campaign manager Lee Atwater
labeled one of five ``key states'' in the Nov. 8 election, Bush
said the president and Congress should ``extend to each other the
hand of partnership, not the finger of blame.''
   In a speech at the University of Michigan, Bush said the
president's leadership ``involves the national interest beyond our
shores, an interest important to all Americans of whatever
political persuasion. That's why I want to revive bipartisanship. I
want to make it once more the vibrant heart of a foreign policy
that is decided by a debate which ends at the water's edge.''
   But he disparaged the qualifications of Democratic opponent
Michael Dukakis in this field.
   ``Lacking experience in foreign affairs, he has a rather
unrealistic view of American's role and the way in which we lead,''
Bush said of Dukakis.
   He also said Dukakis ``apparently believes that the Soviet
economic problems have left them too weak to make trouble. The
liberal Massachusetts governor seems to think that all we need to
do is offer Moscow economic inducements and a less agressive, less
threatening Soviet Union will be the result. He's wrong.''
   Bush called on Dukakis ``to join me in a bipartisan
reaffirmation that we are not going to reduce our troops in Europe
unilaterally.''
   Contending that the United States and Europe must forge closer
ties, Bush promised if elected to propose an early NATO summit
meeting to adopt a strategy for conventional arms control in
Europe, to discuss effective deployment of Allied forces, to agree
on common diplomacy toward East Europe and the Soviet Union, and to
influence public opinion on the need for the alliance.
   Atwater said that in addition to Michigan, the key states are
Illinois, California, New Jersey and Ohio.
   In addition, Atwater said, there are a range of states, like New
York, that are still competitive.
   Despite Bush's growing and substantial lead in opinion polls,
Atwater claimed the campaign is not changing its strategy, and Bush
will continue to campaign as if he is behind.
   In a pair of campus campaign appearances Tuesday, Bush began his
speeches by telling supporters the race for the White House is not
over, and won't be until Nov. 8.
   ``The election is still close and there are many undecided
voters,'' said Bush, who holds a 17-point lead in the latest
nationwide survey.
   The vice president predicted a ``tough battle'' for the rest of
the campaign and told a rally of about 7,000 people at Southwest
Missouri State University in Springfield that he would ``campaign
like an underdog.''
   ``The worst thing to do would be to show a complacency I don't
feel or an overconfidence that I do not feel,'' Bush insisisted to
reporters Tuesday morning before a speech on foreign affairs at
Westminster College in Fulton, Mo.
   Bush was making a series of appearances today in Michigan, where
he was expected to focus on his defense and foreign policy themes
of this week. Former President Gerald Ford, a Michigan native, was
joining Bush on the campaign trail.
   Despite the Republican candidate's repeated cautionary comments,
Bush supporters at Southwest Missouri clearly had victory in their
sights. Around the gymansium were banners reading ``On the Road to
the White House,'' ``The legend begins, the legacy continues,''
``Victory '88 for Our Man,'' and ``George is awesome.''
   The crowd cheered wildly and booed on cue for Bush's standard
Dukakis-bashing lines.
   Earlier at Westminster College, Bush did not mention Dukakis in
his speech on U.S.-Soviet relations. The vice president called for
a cautionary attitude toward the Soviets and a ``peace through
strength'' policy.
   Bush recalled that the campus was the site of former British
Prime Minister Winston Churchill's famous 1946 ``Iron Curtain''
speech. Churchill said a post-war Iron Curtain of secrecy and
self-imposed isolation had surrounded the Soviet Union and the
communist Eastern bloc.
   Bush said that curtain is rusting today but that ``in Europe and
other parts of the world, we have yet to see the full promise of
Soviet change turn into change itself.''
   If elected president, Bush said he would remain wary of Soviet
intentions, despite more promising signals from Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policies.
   ``Now is not the time to abandon realism about what moves the
Soviet Union,'' he said.
   Bush, asked why he talked about being an underdog when polls
show him handily ahead, said the campaign will not ``lighten up.
We're going to stay right down to the wire. ... If I find anybody
letting up in my campaign, they're history.''
</TEXT>
