<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0450 10-19 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barnstorming Quayle Pledges Republican Ticket `Like Tigers'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP seven grafs new with meeting with Jewish leaders; EDITS
elsewhere to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle met behind closed doors
with Jewish backers today, conceding Republicans have done too
little to convey their message to the Jewish community, but vowing
to step up that effort.
   ``Evidently we haven't done as good a job as we should have in
communicating where the Republican Party stands vis-a-vis Israel,
where the Republican Party stands vis-a-vis the Jewish community,''
Quayle said as he emerged from the meeting in a Chicago hotel.
   The early meeting followed a day of barnstorming rural Illinois.
Quayle toured the state Tuesday pledging a vigorous fight to win
his native Midwest from a Democratic ticket that he said is out of
touch with the region, and he told displaced workers there that
unemployment is a consequence of ``the way our dynamic economy
operates.''
   Quayle was continuing his tour of small-town middle America in
Missouri, but he started focusing on a Jewish vote he considered is
heavily Democratic.
   ``If you look at the numbers they're not where they should be,''
he said. ``We're not going to be satisfied until we get a clear
majority, and we don't have that right now.''
   He dismissed suggestions that members of an ethnic support group
for Bush who were fired for reported anti-Semitic connections would
damage the ticket among Jewish voters.
   He said that incident was handled ``with dispatch'' and hasn't
harmed the ticket.
   Quayle spoke to students and toured farms Tuesday as his bus
caravan snaked through downstate Illinois before arriving in
Chicago. The Republican vice presidential candidate planned to make
stops in Kansas City and across Missouri today.
   ``George Bush and I are going to be like tigers between now and
Nov. 8,'' Quayle said. ``We have an election to win.''
   During his tour, Quayle lashed out at presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis as a ``conceited liberal'' and contended the
Massachusetts Democrat ``looks down'' on the region.
   ``They think they're better than we are,'' Quayle told cheering
college supporters in Kankakee. ``We say `good night Mike' because
he never said good morning to America.
   ``We are the ones who are talking about the future. We are the
ones talking about moving this country forward.''
   With many parts of the Midwest industrial sector suffering from
decline, Quayle spent time touting his role in job training
legislation, meeting with displaced workers to give them a pep talk.
   ``If you lost a job, it's not your fault,'' Quayle said. ``It's
not that you didn't work hard.
   ``It happens to be the way our dynamic economy operates. That
power of positive thinking, there's no substitute for it.
   ``You've come to the right place. This is where you can get some
help as far as redirection.''
   Aides had scheduled a folksy _ and photogenic _ series of
small-town stops throughout the day. Quayle met with hundreds of
denim-clad youngsters on a farm with hay bales and a giant flag in
the background. He also stopped to buy a Halloween pumpkin he said
would be turned into ``monster Dukakis.''
   As the bus caravan snaked northward, Quayle occasionally spoke
through a loudspeaker mounted on top to groups of schoolchildren
gathered along the roadside.
   ``This campaign is full of controlled spontaneity,'' said
spokesman David Prosperi.
   But at the same time, Quayle and his aides promised an
aggressive final three weeks of the campaign.
   And while Quayle continued to warn against overconfidence, he
was upbeat after meeting cheering college students in Kankakee.
   ``I'm beginning to feel what it's going to be like on election
night,'' Quayle said.
   Most polls have shown the Republican ticket with a persistent
lead, and some have shown it widening in recent days.
</TEXT>
