<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0456 10-19 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says GOP Has Turned Campaign Into `Mud-Wrestling Festival'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SAN JOSE</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Bentsen speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Bentsen had; DELETES last 3 graf to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen accused Republicans
today of turning the presidential campaign into a ``mud-wrestling
festival'' with attacks on Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis that
have no regard for the truth.
   ``They have force-fed sound bites to the evening news and
laughed behind the backs of voters demanding some honesty about
America's future,'' said the Democratic vice presidential candidate.
   ``They have viciously slandered the patriotism and record of
Michael Dukakis and then turned around and whistled sweetness and
light when they are called to account,'' Bentsen said in a speech
prepared for delivery at Stanford University.
   Bentsen is seeking to bolster the Democrats' sagging fortunes in
the presidential race with a hard-hitting assault on what he terms
the GOP ticket's campaign of distortion and cynicism.
   The Texas senator said the attacks by Republican nominee George
Bush and running mate Dan Quayle were ``reducing the caliber of a
national campaign to the level of a mud-wrestling festival out at
the Cow Palace,'' a sports arena near San Francisco about 30 miles
north of Palo Alto.
   ``They have said things about Mike Dukakis that in Texas we
wouldn't say about a rattlesnake on a lawn at a church picnic,'' he
said.
   Bentsen was winding up two days of campaigning for California's
47 electoral votes before flying to Kentucky.
   Bentsen had been hinting at some dissatisfication with Dukakis'
failure to respond strongly to the Republican attacks. He uncorked
his own criticisms on Tuesday in a speech at the University of
California at Los Angeles and then at a rally in San Jose.
   ``They don't seem to mind if it's untrue. Doesn't seem to worry
them if it's misleading. Can't seem to care if it's downright
mean,'' he said. ``It's just the same kind of half-baked proposals
they throw up in debate.
   ``If it sounds good say it, if it sells, package it, if it looks
good nominate it,'' he said.
   Bentsen and Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis, he said, have
``been a little incredulous sometimes and haven't answered back as
we should.'' But he said those pointing to the ``open casket'' were
listening to Republicans.
   ``Well, they haven't heard the last from Mike Dukakis and Lloyd
Bentsen,'' he said.
   ``This election is too important ... to sit back and accept the
cynical view of politics that guides the campaign of the
opposition,'' he said.
   In his UCLA address to about 2,000 students, Bentsen traced the
Republican tactics back to July, when the Democrats held a big lead
in the polls and the Republicans were worried.
   ``And the image makers came in and said, `Don't you worry about
that. Wait `till we get through with Michael Dukakis and spend
millions of dollars on television cutting him up ... And then we'll
turn to a campaign of a sweetness and light and take it on home,'
'' he said.
   Bentsen's campaign was bolstered Tuesday by the presence of Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the conservative chairman of the Senate Armes
Services Committee. Nunn hosted Bentsen at UCLA and later
introduced him at a McDonnell Douglas aerospace plant in Orange
County.
   Nunn said the Democratic candidates want to spend more of the
total defense spending on conventional weapons such as planes and
tanks while the Republicans want to spend more on nuclear missiles.
   Attempts by the Republicans to scare people into thinking the
Democrats would disarm America were ``gross distortions,'' the
Georgia Democrat said.
   ``The Democratic ticket has got to hit back,'' Nunn said. But,
he added that it was Dukakis, not Bentsen, who had to head that
effort.
</TEXT>
