<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Comair-Charges     10-19 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Comair-Charges,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Filed Accyse Comair Airline Managers of Coercing Drug
Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Comair Airline executives, accused of
holding employees against their will in a hotel room to get them to
undergo drug tests, have been charged with misdemeanor criminal
charges.
   Boone County Attorney Larry Crigler said Tuesday he filed a
total of 25 charges of unlawful imprisonment against six Comair
managerial-level officials at the request of five employees.
   The unlawful imprisonment charges are second-degree misdemeanors
that carry a possible sentence of up to a year in prison and a $500
fine on each count, Crigler said.
   Although the employees were not physically restrained in the
hotel, they were detained against their will by the authority of
their company superiors, Crigler said. ``They were told they
couldn't leave.''
   The incident allegedly took place Sept. 15 in a room at the
Radisson Hotel at Greater Cincinnati International Airport. The
airport is in Kentucky, near the border with Ohio.
   The five employees say airline officials illegally held them and
coerced them into taking surprise drug tests. The employees say the
tests showed no evidence of drug use.
   Comair attorney Richard Creighton said that the company denies
that there had been any criminal behavior. When asked Tuesday if
the employees had been free to leave the hotel room, Creighton
replied: ``Of course.''
   Also Tuesday, Comair filed a libel lawsuit against the attorney
for the five crew members, Garry L. Edmondson. The lawsuit said
Edmondson told reporters at a news conference that Comair managers
``shanghaied'' the pilot and four flight attendants and used
``Gestapo-like tactics'' to obtain urine samples.
   The lawsuit, which seeks unspecified damages, contends the
statements damaged the reputation of Comair, a regional airline
based at Greater Cincinnati International Airport. The lawsuit was
filed Tuesday in Hamilton County (Ohio) Common Pleas Court.
   Edmondson said he had not seen the lawsuit and declined to
comment on it except to say, ``sounds desperate to me.''
   Lastl month, Comair fired five other employees, including three
pilots, reportedly because the five either failed drug tests or
admitted that they used drugs while off duty. The three pilots have
filed grievances against the company.
</TEXT>
