<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru; a0430 10-19 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru;, a0430,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Uncaring About Farmers' Plight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede DETROIT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 15 grafs new with Dukakis campaigning; picks up pvs 4th
graf bgng, The campaign swing; DELETES last 4 grafs pvs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HULL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, targeting a rural
bastion of Republican strength in presidential elections, said
today he cares about the future of rural America while Republican
rival George Bush ``has never expressed any particular concern.''
   En route to a rally at a southern Illinois farm, Dukakis said,
``I don't remember any time in this campaign he's expressed any
concern about family farmers. They (the Republicans) like corporate
operators.''
   The farm owned by Jim and Mabel Reed was the Democratic
nominee's first stop on a bus tour of southern Illinois and
Missouri.
   Dukakis' meeting with farmers at the Reeds' home was being
broadcast on a hookup to 20 states via satellite cable television.
   The states were Arkansas, Colorado, Georgia, Illinois, Iowa,
Kansas, Kentucky, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, New Mexico, North
Carolina, North Dakota, Ohio, Oregon, South Dakota, Tennessee,
Washington, Wisconsin and Wyoming.
   The Massachusetts governor's aides said he has requested a
half-hour of air time on each broadcast network the night before
the Nov. 8 election.
   Dukakis said he was making the bus tour to show ``how much I
care about family farms and how little George Bush cares about
family farms.''
   He said Bush's philosophy was ``the fewer farms the better.''
   Dukakis said he also was concerned about the decline of other
facilities in rural areas, particularly hospitals.
   He was asked to comment on an interview with Willie Horton Jr.,
the Massachusetts prisoner who escaped from a furlough in 1986 and
slashed a Maryland man and raped his fiancee last year.
   Horton, now imprisoned in Maryland, was asked whom he'd support
for president.
   ``Obviously I'm for Gov. Dukakis,'' Horton was quoted as saying.
   ``He can't vote,'' commented Dukakis.
   Before arriving at the Reed farm, Dukakis' bus went through the
tiny town of Plainville, where people stood by the side of the road
holding up ``Dukakis for President'' signs.
   The candidate opened the bus window, leaned out, waved and said,
``Thank you all very much, thank you.''
   The campaign swing through rural areas marked a shift from the
previous two days when Dukakis visited factories, schools and a
bowling alley in Ohio and Michigan.
   ``George Bush was against the minimum wage; he was against the
plant closing law,'' Dukakis told workers Tuesday at McLouth Steel
Products, an employee-owned firm on the outskirts of Detroit.
   The firm's motto is ``The Future Is in Our Hands,'' a fact
Dukakis noted when he told the workers ``that's exactly what the
election is about.''
   For two days, in urban areas, Dukakis drew a distinction between
himself and Bush that he summed up this way:
   ``George Bush cares about the people on Easy Street. I care
about the people on Main Street. He's on their side. I'm on your
side.''
   He said his GOP rival has ``no convictions, no ideas, no plans.''
   The Massachusetts governor blamed the Republican administration
for the economic problems of the Midwest and for the nation's trade
deficit which he pledged to end within his first four years in
office.
   During the race for the Republican presidential nomination, Bush
was beaten badly in Iowa, South Dakota and Minnesota.
   But the man who defeated Bush in the those contests was Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole, whose Midwest roots and involvement in agricultural
policy in the Senate made him a formidable candidate in the region.
   Iowa remains a state in which the Democrats have high hopes. The
same is true of Minnesota.
   The states Dukakis was visiting today were key battlegrounds in
the battle for an electoral majority.
   Illinois is one of the big prizes with 24 electoral votes.
Democrats normally depend on huge majorities from the Chicago area
to overcome Republican majorities from the state's rural areas.
   Dukakis hopes to cut into that Republican bloc with his pledge
to create a presidential council on rural development and to target
$100 million to finance projects to help rural businesses.
   With 11 electoral votes, Missouri is one of the largest of the
border states.
</TEXT>
