<1ST_LINE>u w PM-LobbyingBill 1stLd-Writethru a0487 10-19 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lobbying Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 4 grafs new to UPDATE; pickup 3rd graf pvs, House
Judiciary.
^By LARRY MARGASAK</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said today he favors
passage of legislation this session that would apply the first-ever
lobbying restrictions to former members of Congress and
ex-congressional staffers.
   Both houses have approved different versions of the legislation,
which also would strengthen current lobbying restrictions against
those who leave the executive branch of government.
   The Senate took the latest action Tuesday night with voice vote
passage of lobbying legislation that modified an earlier Senate
bill.
   Wright told reporters he has asked House Judiciary Committee
members to work with senators to fashion a final compromise, and
approve the legislation before congressional adjournment.
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Peter W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J.,
and other influential House members have been skeptical about the
legislation, arguing there was no evidence of unethical lobbying by
ex-members of Congress.
   But despite such reservations, the House passed its own version
of the bill by a vote of 374-19 on Oct. 12. The House bill was a
somewhat watered-down version of a bill the Senate passed earlier
this session.
   The bill passed Tuesday was the Senate's effort to meet the
House halfway, and House members would have to accept the modified
version for the bill to go to President Reagan.
   Major provisions of the Senate bill would:
   _Bar members of Congress from lobbying either chamber of
Congress for one year and restrict high-level executive branch
officials from lobbying their branch for one year.
   _Prohibit top congressional staffers from lobbying their own
member or the member's personal staff for one year, and prevent,
for the same period, top committee staff from lobbying the
committee's members or staff.
   _Provide a one-year moratorium during which Cabinet members,
their principal deputies, members of Congress, and top White House
aides could not lobby or work for a foreign entity after leaving
government service.
   The legislation would maintain the lifetime ban in current law
that prevents executive branch employees from lobbying on any issue
in which they had a ``personal and substantial'' involvement while
in government service.
   Maximum criminal penalties in the measure include $250,000 in
fines and four-year prison terms. The measure also provides for
recovery of civil fines of up to $50,000 or the amount of proceeds
obtained by an individual who violates restrictions in the measure.
   The legislation would become effective nine months after
becoming law.
   The House bill's restrictions on former members of Congress and
their staff would apply only to the chamber where they served. The
Senate restriction would apply to contacts in either house.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the chief sponsor, said the bill
would ``prevent those who are employed by the federal government
from leaving public service and marketing their access and
influence for financial gain.
   ``In addition, the legislation prevents federal employees from
vending sensitive information vital to national interests to
foreign entities for profit,'' he said.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said Americans are tired of
influence-peddling and of Congress exempting itself from lobbying
restrictions.
</TEXT>
