<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Firewalking Bjt   10-19 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firewalking, Bjt,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priests Lead 200 Barefoot Devotees Over the Coals</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drums pounded a trance-like beat
Wednesday night, the smell of incense filled the air, and temple
priest Gan Chai Heng cleared his mind of worldly thoughts.
   Then, he and eight other priests led 200 barefoot Chinese
devotees in a calm walk over a 30-foot bed of burning coals so hot
that the 10,000 spectators had to watch from 50 feet away.
   The firewalking ceremony in front of the Temple of the Southern
Heaven capped the nine-day Festival of the Nine Emperor Gods.
   Temple worker Wong Choong Bun, 49, one of those who walked
unflinchingly over the red-hot coals, said he felt no pain and it
was an act of faith in the gods to ensure good luck.
   ``I walk to ensure a good life and for the well-being of my
family and friends,'' Wong said.
   Some carried a statue of the gods with them as they walked over
the 4{-foot-wide and 1{-foot-thick bed of coals on wooden platforms
mounted on horizontal poles. Others carried images of gods and
incense sticks in their hands.
   ``We have used several thousand pounds of charcoal for the fire
and we began making the fire four hours before the firewalking to
ensure that it was really hot,'' said Yap Kok Chan, deputy
secretary of the temple.
   The firewalkers, all men, wore loose-fitting white trousers and
long-sleeved shirts, and scarves on their heads. ``We never allow
women to walk on the fire,'' Gan said, although they may join in on
the fasting.
   Gan, who has walked on the coals for more than 10 years, said
it's not difficult and added: ``All I have to do is to adhere to a
vegetarian diet and clear my mind of worldy thoughts.''
   The firewalkers usually eat one vegetarian meal a day during the
nine-day fasting period, although there are some who take only
liquid nourishment. Mostly, they pray and meditate, and must
abstain from sex.
   According to legend, a Manchu emperor many centuries ago
beheaded nine gods who helped the people to rebel against his
oppression. The emperor later regretted his actions and prayed.
   After an epidemic swept through the region in 1940, residents
prayed to the statue of the Nine Emperor Gods, practiced
vegetarianism for nine days, and started walking on the coals.
   Now the Chinese here, especially those who practice Taoism, come
for the annual festival, walk on the coals, and pray and give alms
to atone for their sins. Buddhists, Confucionists and other Chinese
also participate.
   Western scientists say that firewalkers usually avoid injury by
walking across the coals with moist feet so that a thin layer of
steam protects the flesh.
   ``It could be faith and some hypnosis,'' said physician
Ampikaipahan Kandiah. ``But there have been some cases reported
where people's feet have been burned during firewalking. We have
treated them. They put it dwn to lack of proper fasting.''
   Gan said that over the years, he has seen a few people with
slight burns on their feet. Yap said those with burned feet never
admit it or show it because they are ashamed that people might
think they were impure or had not fasted properly. No one
complained Wednesday night.
</TEXT>
