<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Alaska     10-19 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Alaska,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans, Soviets To Study Harsh Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists from Alaska and the Soviet frontier
town of Magadan will examine how people adapt to harsh conditions
in the far north, one of the participants said Wednesday.
   Alaska medical students, nurses, biologists and environmental
scientists will work with their counterparts in Magadan and
surrounding villages for three weeks next May, said Dr. Ted Mala,
director of the Institute for Circumpolar Health Studies at the
University of Alaska-Anchorage.
   ``We plan to bring in sleeping bags and work side by side,''
with local physician's assistants and scientists from the Institute
for Biological Problems of the North in Magadan, Mala said.
   The group will examine disease patterns, psychological problems
and medical anthropology, including the drug and alcohol abuse,
Mala said.
   Two groups of 10 Soviets specialists will travel to Alaska for
similar studies next September and October, Mala said.
   ``It will be interesting to see what has happened on both sides
with the difference in diets,'' Mala said, especially since the
natives of Alaska are related to the indigenous population of the
Soviet Union just across the Bering Strait.
   The agreement was signed Aug. 15, but Mala noted that none of
the group had been anywhere near a telephone since then.
</TEXT>
