<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-IRA 2ndLd-Writethru   10-19 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-IRA, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0625,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans Broadcast Interviews With IRA Members, Militant
Protestants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th pvs, `Roy Hattersley...' to CORRECT quote.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today banned broadcast interviews
with members of the outlawed Irish Republican Army, its legal
political wing, Sinn Fein, and Northern Ireland's militant
Protestant groups.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd announced the immediate ban in the
House of Commons and said the Conservative government aimed to deny
terrorists publicity.
   The ban, which also applies to any statements supporting the
organizations, provoked immediate outcry from opposition parties
and civil liberty groups that denounced it as futile and a
violation of free speech.
   Hurd, who is responsible for broadcasting, told Parliament:
``This is not a restriction on reporting. It is a restriction on
direct appearances by those who use or support violence.''
   He said it brought radio and TV into line with print media,
which are not affected by the ban, in that broadcasters remain free
to report the content of statements by pro-violence groups.
   The broadcast ban was done by decree. Such a restriction on the
press would require legislation.
   The ban forbids broadcasting interviews with members of the
legal Ulster Defense Association, the umbrella group for militant
Protestant organizations, as well as the mainly Roman Catholic IRA
and Sinn Fein and all other outlawed groups.
   The ban on supporters prompted questions in Parliament, since it
could apply to other legal organizations sympathetic to the IRA's
goal of driving Britain out of Northern Ireland by force.
   Roy Hattersley, Labor Party deputy leader, called the measure
``trivial, worthless and almost certainly counterproductive'' and
said it made ``the government look simultaneously repressive and
ridiculous.''
   ``Have you considered the damaging ways in which this will be
used both at home and abroad, particularly in the United States, to
portray this government as the enemy of free expression?''
Hattersley said.
   Hugh Dykes of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
Party said the ban would be ``a very great mistake'' because ``it
would look as if the government fears the IRA can persuade people
of their sick cause.''
   The ban applies to the publicly funded British Broadcasting
Corp. and the commercial Independent Broadcasting Authority, but
not to foreign broadcasting organizations.
   It also will not apply to proceedings in Parliament and will be
eased during election campaigns when all parties are supposed to
get equal coverage from the broadcast media, said Hurd.
   The ban, imposed under existing broadcasting laws, closely
follows a 15-year ban in the Irish Republic on interviews with the
IRA, Sinn Fein and Protestant groups that espouse violent tactics.
   A government source said Mrs. Thatcher decided on the ban as
part of a package of security measures after an upsurge in IRA
activity, including a bomb that killed eight British soldiers in
Northern Ireland two months ago.
   It was the first time such actions have been taken since the
mid-1950s, when similar powers were used against splinter Welsh and
Scottish nationalist groups.
   The BBC and Independent Broadcasting Authority refused comment
on the ban.
   Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams, a member of Parliament, called
the ban ``nonsense'' and said: ``This draconian measure is not an
attack on the IRA or the ability of the IRA to operate. It is a
direct attack on Sinn Fein because our views are unacceptable to
the British government.''
   Sarah Spencer, general secretary of the National Council for
Civil Liberties, said the ban would ``serve only to prevent the
public understanding the motives which lie behind the violence and
thereby hinder the search for a political solution to the
conflict.''
   A Sinn Fein statement said:
   ``If we were in eastern Europe the British government would be
crying foul at the banning from TV and radio of a legal political
party that has parliamentary representation and a mandate from its
community.''
   Sinn Fein commands about one-third of the minority Catholic vote
in Northern Ireland and has about 60 representatives on local
councils who stand to lose access to radio and TV.
</TEXT>
