<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORRIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's only October but author Alex Haley and
producer David Wolper have Christmas on their mind.
   The two, who teamed up to produce the television miniseries
``Roots'' and a sequel, have collaborated again for ``A Roots
Christmas _ Kunta Kinte's Gift.''
   Haley said he expects Wolper and about 170 other guests for a
picnic at his Norris farm this weekend to relax and discuss the
project, scheduled to air Dec. 4.
   ``David is a good friend,'' Haley said. ``I wanted to get him to
East Tennessee. He's never been here. The farm is pretty much
developed so that if you bring in people from the film and
publishing industry you expose them to East Tennessee.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenor Luciano Pavarotti, who has lost 85 pounds
in recent months on a strict diet, confesses, ``You cannot be
romantic on stage without some sugar.''
   The 53-year-old operatic heavyweight shared some of his diet
secrets in a New York Times interview, although one he kept to
himself was his current poundage. He said he adheres to an 1,800
calories-a-day regimen that is high in salads and lean protein like
chicken and veal.
   Asked to describe a typical day before a performance, he said:
``At 11:45 I make a little veal with vegetables. Then at 3:45 I
have a piece of prosciutto. Then at 4:45 a second prosciutto with
bread; you need some sugar when you sing. You need the energy.''
   Pavarotti, who is currently performing at the Metropolitan
Opera, said one of his favorite dishes is pasta with butter and
melted blue cheese. ``You know that it has two million five hundred
calories a spoonful,'' he said wistfully.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Joanne Woodward, who with her
husband, Paul Newman, helped set up a short-lived recycling center
here in the 1970s, has been named to a committee to launch another
recycling program in Westport.
   The couple are longtime residents of the community. Woodward
asked First Selectman Martha Hauhuth to put her on the committee,
said Eleanor Solovay, an assistant for Hauhuth, said Wednesday.
   The state has ordered all municipalities to initiate recycling
programs by Jan. 1, 1991, to reduce the volume of solid waste by 25
percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PINOLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bob Hope, actress Marlee Matlin,
Oakland A's pitcher Dave Stewart and a host of other celebrities
are scheduled to attend a fund-raiser for an 8-year-old who
vanished June 3.
   Kim and Al Garcia, the parents of Amber Swartz-Garcia, are
planning to hold the $250-a-plate black-tie event at millionaire
Ken Behring's new Antique Car Museum on Dec. 8 in Blackhawk, an
exclusive community in Contra Costa County.
   Proceeds will go to the non-profit Amber Swartz Garcia
Foundation for Missing Children, which the Garcias created to help
search for Amber.
   Investigators have pursued hundreds of tips and sightings since
the youngster disappeared from her front yard but have come up
empty-handed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sukhreet Gabel, the key witness in the bribery
trial of former Miss America Bess Myerson, predicted Wednesday
she'd enjoy 15 minutes of fame _ during a 25-minute appearance on a
local talk show.
   ``I'm very conscious of the fact that I'm not really a
celebrity, I'm just a 15-minute sensation. I'm aware that this is
going to end,'' Gabel said on the WWOR-TV show ``People Are
Talking.''
   It was the latest bit of exposure for Ms. Gabel, whose hiring by
Miss Myerson is at the center of the highly publicized trial, since
she took the witness stand last week.
   A local radio personality has offered Ms. Gabel a job as a
weather announcer; her telephone has been ringing off the hook with
calls from strangers, and a man in panty hose asked her for a date.
   ``I found the guy in the panty hose pretty funny,'' she said.
   Despite the rash of attention, Ms. Gabel described herself as
just an average person: ``I'm a human being, I'm just a person like
anybody else. I'm your next-door neighbor, I'm the person you meet
in a grocery store. ... I'm not a real celebrity.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although country music singer Roy Clark
blew out the candles and cut the cake while others sang ``Happy
Birthday,'' it wasn't Clark's _ it was the 21st anniversary of
``Hee Haw.''
   Clark, host of the syndicated television show since it went on
the air, limited himself to just one bite of the chocolate cake
with white icing. He has been on a doctor-prescribed diet since
June to adjust his metabolism and slimmed down from 257 pounds to
195.
   ``It tasted strange,'' he said about the cake, which is
forbidden on his sugar-free diet. ``But that (one bite) is all I'm
going to have.''
   Grandpa Jones, Minnie Pearl and Lulu Roman were among the
regular cast members on the hourlong country music-comedy show that
attended the 10-minute ceremony Tuesday.
