<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0479 10-19 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Proposes New Nation of `Koryo'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with North Korea proposing new nation. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Korea-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea today proposed creating a new
nation out of North and South Korea, with a shared military command
and a national assembly comprised of an equal number of
representatives from each side.
   The North's deputy foreign minister, Kang Sok Ju, suggested the
new nation would be called the Democratic Confederal Republic of
Koryo.
   Kang told the General Assembly that ``there is no hidden attempt
to insinuate `unification through communization' and no intention
to impose our ideas and system on the other side.''
   He said peaceful reunification is possible if each side respects
the other's ideology and that the new state would retain the
separate social systems of the communist North and pro-Western
South.
   South Korea's U.N. Mission said in a statement, ``We think the
North Korean delegation's speech this morning appears to be a
compilation of their past proposals. Our president yesterday
(Tuesday) suggested all those proposals of North and South Korea be
discussed at the sumit talks between the two parts of Korea.''
   South Korea's president, Roh Tae-woo, addressed the Assembly on
Tuesday.
   The authorities of ``Koryo'' would found and run joint companies
and common markets and encourage the formation of a new national
economy for the entire peninsula, said Kang.
   A unified Korea would ``not only leave intact the capital
invested by other nations in South Korea prior to reunification and
continue to ensure their concessions, but also promote new
investments of foreign capital,'' said Kang.
   ``Koryo'' would have a unified military command, abolish former
military alliances and treaties, and dissolve the demarcation line
dividing North and South, he said.
   The new nation would be the sole representative of the peninsula
in diplomatic relations with other nations and would hold one seat
in the United Nations, he added.
   Both Koreas currently hold non-voting observer status in the
General Assembly.
   ``Koryo'' would be a neutral, non-aligned nation, and the
peninsula would become a nuclear-weapon-free zone and ban the
presence of foreign troops, Kang said.
   About 42,000 American troops are stationed in South Korea.
   Vernon Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
called it a ``thoughtful speech and interesting speech.''
   ``I don't think there were any new elements except the tone; the
tone was considerably more conciliatory,'' said Walters.
   On Tuesday, Roh proposed a summit between the leaders of North
and South and the signing of a non-aggression pact by the bitter
rivals.
   Roh said a summit with North Korea's President Kim Il-sung would
``resolve all the problems raised by either or both sides with
regard to disarmament, arms control and other military matters.''
   Roh also pledged that ``the Republic of Korea will never use
force first against the North.''
   Kang agreed with Roh that a summit would have to adopt a
non-aggression pact, but he said the summit also would have to
cover the issue of reunification.
   If the South is not ready to discuss reunificaton, said Kang,
senior officials could at least meet to hold talks aimed at easing
military tensions as a step toward eventual ``top level talks.''
   He also said the United States and North Korea should sign a
peace agreement that would result in the withdrawal of U.S. troops
from the South, a phased demilitarization of the peninsula, and the
estabishment of a nuclear-free zone.
   Roh also proposed the two Koreas meet with United States, Soviet
Union, China and Japan to prepare the groundwork for peace and
security measures throughout northeast Asia. He did not offer
specifics.
   Allies of the United States and South Korea should ``contribute
to the progress and opening of North Korea by engaging Pyongyang in
expanding relations,'' the president told the 159-member world body.
   Relations between North Korea and the United States never have
gone beyond the symbolic since 1945, when the Korean peninsula was
divided between North and South Korea.
   The Koreas hold U.N. non-voting observer status because they
still technically are at war. The 1950-1953 Korean War ended in an
armistice and no peace treaty was signed.
   On Thursday, Roh meets President Reagan in Washington. The South
Korean leader is expected to ask Washington to improve its
relations with North Korea.
</TEXT>
