<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WifeAmbush     10-19 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wife Ambush,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced For Shooting At Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of shooting at his
estranged wife from ambush was sentenced to 8 to 16 years in prison.
   Sentence was imposed Tuesday on Timothy Garland, 40, of Bolivar
by Westmoreland County Common Pleas Court Judge Donetta Ambrose.
   Authorities said in March 1987, Garland took a handful of
shells, a high-powered rifle with a telescopic sight, a pistol, his
last unemployment check, and a Bible to a rural road and waited for
his wife, Cynthia, 33, to drive by on her way to work.
   After he opened fire with the hunting rifle, the woman's car
stalled and she flagged down another motorist, Robert Barnhart,
authorities said.
   During the trial, she testified Garland continued to fire while
she tried to hide underneath the dashboard of Barnhart's truck. She
was unhurt, but Barnhart's dog was killed.
   A jury last November found Garland guilty of attempted homicide,
two counts of aggravated assault and two counts of recklessly
endangering another person.
   Garland's wife has since divorced him and goes by another name.
