<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Idaho-Waste     10-19 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Idaho-Waste,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov. Andrus Bans Further Shipments Of Radioactive Waste Into Idaho</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Cecil Andrus today banned further
shipments of low-level radioactive waste into Idaho until the
federal government opens a permanent repository for that waste.
   ``Any of this waste will be stopped at the border,'' Andrus
declared, accusing the government of welching on two promises to
begin moving millions of cubic feet of temporarily stored waste out
of the state.
   Andrus notified Energy Secretary John Herrington of the ban
after returning from a one-day tour of the government's proposed
Waste Isolation Pilot Project repository in New Mexico.
   That facility in the desert near Carlsbad was to open this month
as the permanent repository for more then 2 million cubic feet of
radioactive waste, brought into Idaho and now stored above ground
at the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory, a research and
training facility run by the Energy Department.
   The opening, however, has been postponed until at least early
next year because of questions raised about its long-range safety.
After his tour, the governor said Energy Department officials could
give him no firm date on when the site might open.
   ``It's an outstanding facility,'' Andrus said. ``It appears to
be well engineered. ... If radioactive waste can be stored safely
any place in the world, this is it.
   ``No more radioactive waste will be accepted in Idaho from any
location outside this state until they have a location where this
waste will be stored,'' he said.
   The temporarily stored waste at INEL has built up over the past
several decades, but the bulk of it has been shipped in recent
years from the federal facility at Rocky Flats, Colo.
   The government delayed opening the $800 million repository in
salt corridors some 2,000 feet below ground in New Mexico because
of safety concerns raised by some Energy Department engineers and
because of a congressional dispute over putting the site under
Energy Department control.
   Andrus discounted the questions of safety and called on
Herrington to begin proceedings to gain control of the land so the
repository can be opened.
   ``Promises have come and promises have gone,'' he said.
``Promises from DOE are no longer good. ... We're tired, and we're
not going to do it.''
   Andrus acknowledged that he could be legally challenged in
closing the borders to radioactive waste imports. But, he added,
``I'm confident that DOE is not going to bring material into the
state when we have said we don't want it.''
   The state already requires truckers of hazardous wastes to stop
at border checkpoints for safety and paperwork checks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
