<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0591,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Stage General Strike, Three Wounded In Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT that Gaza captured from Egypt,
sted Jordan. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Arab reports...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shops were closed and transportation came to a
standstill today during a general strike in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Hospital officials said three Palestinians were wounded in
clashes with soldiers.
   About 50 buses filled with supporters of the right-wing Likud
bloc headed into the Gaza Strip to show support for Israeli
occupation of the area seized from Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   Arab reports said the army imposed curfews in refugee camps,
towns and neighborhoods throughout Gaza, confining about 210,000
Palestinians to their homes.
   The fundamentalist Moslem Hamas movement, a main force in Gaza,
distributed leaflets Tuesday night urging Arabs in the seaside
strip to obey calls to strike today, the Israeli Itim news agency
reported.
   The strike call followed a violent clash Tuesday in the West
Bank city of Nablus, where Israeli soldiers shot and killed a
5-year-old boy and a teen-ager. Six other people were wounded,
including an American news photographer.
   Violence erupted today in the West Bank town of Jenin, where a
24-year-old man was shot in the stomach and a 50-year-old man was
hit in the neck when troops opened fire at stone-throwers,
officials at Al-Ittihad hospital in Nablus said. Both men were in
critical condition, the officials said.
   In Gaza City, a 16-year-old Palestinian was shot and seriously
wounded during another stone-throwing protest, officials at Ahli
Arab Hospital said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In response to the strike call, shops and schools were closed
throughout the Gaza Strip. Buses were not operating and horse-drawn
carts were the main mode of transportation.
   Palestinian flags flew from electricity poles and the tops of
mosques. Newly painted slogans were seen on walls, including one
declaring ``Yes to the liberation of Palestine, all Palestine.''
   In the West Bank, dozens of Jewish motorists were pelted with
stones on the main road to Jerusalem outside refugee camps near
Bethlehem. At the entrance to Bethlehem, troops stopped and
searched cars with Arab drivers.
   Pictures of PLO leader Yasser Arafat were stuck on traffic signs
in Bethlehem. Dozens of roads were blocked by barricades of stones
and burning tires.
   Among the six wounded on Tuesday was 37-year-old photographer
Neal Cassidy of Oakland, Calif., who was taking pictures of the
riot. Cassidy, who was on assignment for Frontline, an Oakland
biweekly, was the first foreign reporter shot in the 10-month-old
uprising.
   The two deaths Tuesday raised to 301 the number of Palestinians
killed since 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip began their uprising Dec. 8. Six Israelis have died.
   The Hadashot newspaper reported today that Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres renewed direct contacts with Jordan's King Hussein to
try to arrange talks on returning parts of the West Bank and Gaza
in exchange for peace.
   The Jerusalem Post daily, quoting the French television network
Antenne 2, also reported that contacts were made. It said the
contacts were between representatives of Hussein and aides to Peres.
   The reports did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
