<DOCNO> AP881019-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NastySenateAds 1stLd-Writethru a0662 10-19 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nasty Senate Ads, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Purveyors Of Ugliness' Find Customers This Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, The ad, to show Dawkins-Lautenberg race in New
Jersey.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In probably the most slashing attack so far
among the 33 Senate races across the country, a political spot for
Sen. Frank Lautenberg calls opponent Pete Dawkins ``a hypocrite''
and concludes: ``He'll move anywhere, say anything to get elected.''
   The ad is not alone _ indeed, there are many political spots
with almost as nasty a tone being aired around the nation. But that
it would be the product of an incumbent senator from New Jersey who
by all accounts enjoys a double-digit lead in the polls defies
traditional campaign wisdom.
   Normally, so-called ``attack videos'' are the tools of the
desperate. They have well-known political risks, so traditionally
have been used only in the closing stages of a campaign, and only
when a candidate is holding onto a slim and narrowing lead or needs
to close a wide gap quickly.
   This year the campaign book is being rewritten, and University
of Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato has a name for the new
strain of negative advertising.
   ``They're infectious ads,'' Sabato says. ``They try to infect
the opposition with a deadly germ. They come from incumbents
attacking challengers before they have a chance to define
themselves.''
   In addition, he says, there no longer is a well-defined
progression from biographical ads early in a campaign, to positive
issue-oriented ads, to negative spots in the late stages.
   Attack ads have sprouted all over the political map:
   _ In North Dakota, state Rep. Earl Strinden is openly going
after incumbent Democrat Quentin Burdick's age. ``This isn't the
old Quentin Burdick we used to know,'' his ads say of the
80-year-old Burdick. ``It's time to come home, Quentin. You owe it
to all of us.''
   _ Rep. Connie Mack, the GOP front-runner in the Florida Senate
race, is styling his opponent, Rep. Buddy Mackay, as an
old-fashioned tax-and-spend Democrat. His ads conclude, in a voice
dripping with accusation: ``Hey, Buddy: You're liberal.''
   _ In Nevada, Gov. Richard Bryan's attack on incumbent GOP Sen.
Chic Hecht criticizes Hecht's voting record, then notes that he was
``voted the least respected senator in Washington'' by a group of
top Senate aides.
   _ In Minnesota, incumbent Sen. David Durenberger suggested that
his opponent, Democratic state attorney general Skip Humphrey,
shames the memory of his late father, Hubert Humphrey. ``Skip's
mudslinging doesn't fit in Minnesota,'' the ad said. ``Skip's great
late father never would have started a campaign this way. Skip's
father knew Minnesota.''
   ``I don't know how you get much more brutal than some of the
stuff that's out there now,'' said Tom Mason, spokesman for the
National Republican Senatorial Committee.
   ``Negatives are employed now as standard equipment,'' says
Sabato, noting that Lautenberg went straight to slashing attacks
when he went on the air after Labor Day, bypassing any positive
advertising.
   That first spot was a segment from Dawkins' own announcement
speech, with the sarcastic tagline, ``C'mon Pete. Be real.''
   Lautenberg insists he wanted to run on his record, primarily on
environmental issues, but was forced into negative attacks by
Dawkins' distortions of his record.
   The latest Dawkins spot accuses Lautenberg of personally
profiting from his Senate position through investments in companies
that do business with the government. The closing line, delivered
over sinister background music, is: ``Frank Lautenberg. He'll deny
anything to get elected, as long as he can make some money on the
side.''
   That triggered the latest Lautenberg blitz, which seeks to
capitalize on reports that Dawkins, who as a career military
officer moved around the country frequently, is a carpetbagger who
was shopping for a state to run in.
   Asked why he would take such a blunt approach while holding a
substantial lead in the polls, Lautenberg responded:
   ``If the question is, will you stand there and take the abuse
and turn the other cheek, the answer is no, I won't.'' And he
added, ``The audience likes the show. You hear negative campaigns
bemoaned, the hand-wringing ... Unfortunately, there are some
purveyors of ugliness who've found that it pays.''
</TEXT>
