<1ST_LINE>r w AM-YoungEntrepreneurs     10-19 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Young Entrepreneurs,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SBA Slates Seminar For Young Entrepreneurs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The under-30 crowd will get a chance Saturday
to learn how to become entrepreneurs, complete with pep talks from
some young millionaires.
   The seminars are being sponsored by the Small Business
Administration, which hopes to attract 15,000 participants to the
sessions on college campuses at 123 different sites across the
country.
   For a $15 registration fee, the Young Entrepreneur Seminars will
offer lectures on marketing, bookkeeping, business regulations and
developing a business plan. Local attorneys and accountants are
donating their services to conduct the seminars.
   Three out of four small businesses fail within the first year
with 90 percent of those failures attributable to bad management,
SBA officials said.
   ``Having a great idea is only one element of going into
business. You have to be prepared. We want to give them some
tools,'' said SBA official George Solomon.
   SBA officials said the seminars, which are aimed at persons 30
or younger, will feature talks by young entrepreneurs who have
successfully started their own businesses.
   Sophia Collier, 32, founder of the company which makes SoHO
Natural Soda, will be the keynote speaker at the New York City
seminar.
   SBA Administrator James Abdnor said he was encouraged by the
level of interest shown in advance registrations.
   He said at least 100 participants were expected at every one of
the locations and some colleges were expecting more than 400
participants.
   For persons interested in finding out information on the seminar
in their area, the SBA has this toll-free number: 1-800-368-5855.
</TEXT>
