<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dancer'sMom     10-19 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dancer's Mom,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State: Mother Of Nude Teen Dancer To Comply With `Son-Of-Sam' Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida law to keep felons from
profiting on stories about their crimes will get its first use in
the case of a woman convicted in the suicide of her daughter who
was a nude dancer, the state said Wednesday.
   Theresa Jackson, found guilty of mental child abuse almost a
year ago in Fort Lauderdale, has agreed to abide by the
10-year-old, so-called ``Son of Sam'' law, Attorney General Bob
Butterworth said.
   Ms. Jackson, 41, thought to be the first parent criminally
convicted in a child's suicide, has agreed to set aside certain
amounts from any film, television or book income she receives
related to the death of her 17-year-old daughter, Butterworth said.
   So far, no one has paid for the story of Tina Mancini, who shot
herself in March 1986, two months after she began working as a nude
dancer. Seven months later her mother was convicted of forgery,
child abuse and procuring a sexual performance by a child.
   Ms. Jackson, who was sentenced to a year in jail, is currently
free on bond appealing her conviction and sentence. Of the funds
that would be set aside, at least $35,000 would go to the state for
trial costs.
   The commitment by Ms. Jackson to comply with the statute is
contained in a proposed settlement to be presented to Broward
County Circuit Judge Arthur Franza, who presided over Ms. Jackson's
month-long trial.
   ``The defendant has agreed that all such income will go into a
state trust fund until her obligations under the statute have been
met,'' Butterworth said in a press release issued by his office.
   The Florida statute is based on a New York law that restricted
serial killer David ``Son of Sam'' Berkowitz from profiting from
books about his crimes.
</TEXT>
