<DOCNO> AP881019-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BombingProbe     10-19 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bombing Probe,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Probe Patient's Claim of Knowledge About Church
Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are looking into a dying
man's claim that he had information about the 1963 church bombing
that killed four black girls, even though the man's family and
friends say he has been having hallucinations.
   Gary Tucker, 54, a cancer patient at the Veterans Administration
hospital in Tuscaloosa, told the FBI on Friday that he had
knowledge of the 16th Street Baptist Church bombing. Authorities
refused to disclose details of what Tucker told them.
   One man was convicted in the well-known case, but reports about
Tucker raised the specter that others also knew in advance about
the racially motivated bombing.
   Ku Klux Klansman Robert Chambliss was convicted of the murder in
1977 and sentenced to life in prison, where he died in 1985.
   FBI spokesman Charles Steinmetz said the agency had not
developed a case based on Tucker's information, but turned it over
to the state prosecutor in Birmingham.
   Jefferson County District Attorney David Barber said Wednesday
he had discussed the information with Bob Eddy, who was an attorney
general's investigator on the bombing case. Barber would not
comment on whether Tucker was a credible informant.
   ``I don't have any comment I can make on it at this point. We're
not through doing what we're going to do,'' the district attorney
said. ``We're not going to make comments on half-knowledge.''
   Tucker has refused to talk with reporters. But his pastor and
relatives in Walker County, near Birmingham, dismissed his claim.
   ``Cancer is just eating him up. He's had a drug problem in the
past that crippled him up. He had a car wreck that crippled him.
They're just going to have to take him at face value,'' Tucker's
minister, the Rev. Dale Olmstead, said.
   Someone in Tucker's serious medical condition may make such
statements to get attention, he said.
   Tucker would have been 29 years old at the time of the Sept. 15,
1963, bombing. During Chambliss' trial in Birmingham, witnesses
talked about seeing other men in a car near the church the night
before the blast that killed 11-year-old Denise McNair, and Addie
Mae Collins, Cynthia Dianne Wesley and Carole Robertson, all 14.
   Two of Tucker's uncles also cast doubt on their nephew's ability
to give authorities reliable information.
   Theo Tucker of Sumiton said his nephew worked for him about five
years driving a truck. ``He drank so much alcohol and took so many
pills that the doctors told me it ate up his brain,'' his uncle
said.
   Another uncle, C.W. Tucker of Sumiton, said he didn't know of
any involvement of Gary Tucker with the Ku Klux Klan.
   And in Marietta, Ga., E.R. Fields, publisher of the
segregationist newspaper The Thunderbolt, said he was not familiar
with Tucker. ``At one time I knew most of the boys in the
Birmingham area. But the name `Gary Tucker' doesn't ring a bell
with me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
