<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-ShirleyTemple     10-19 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Shirley Temple,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shirley Temple Black Named Grand Marshal of Tournament of Roses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shirley Temple Black, who as a child
movie star was grand marshal of the 50th Rose Parade in 1939, will
lead the 100th parade this January, the Tournament of Roses
announced Wednesday.
   ``It's an awesome, wonderful job and I'm looking forward to it
with great anticipation,'' said Mrs. Black, who was 10 when she
first led the annual floral spectacle down Colorado Boulevard.
   Mrs. Black, whose credits as a child actress included ``Little
Miss Marker,'' ``Bright Eyes,'' ``The Littlest Rebel'' and ``Wee
Willie Winkie,'' was the youngest grand marshal in the parade's
history.
   Only three others, Bob Hope, Richard Nixon and Earl Warren, have
been grand marshal of the parade twice.
   Mrs. Black left acting at a young age and in 1969 began a
government career that has included a term as U.S. ambassador to
Ghana.
   Just as it did in 1939, Jan. 1, 1989, falls on a Sunday so the
parade, watched annually by television audiences worldwide, and the
Rose Bowl football game will be held Jan. 2.
</TEXT>
