<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JetCrash-Hotel     10-19 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet Crash-Hotel,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blackened Hotel Stands As Grim Reminder Of Fiery Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The blackened facade of a hotel stands as a
grim reminder of the cloudy morning a year ago when a crippled Air
Force fighter slammed into the lobby, killing 10 people in its
fireball.
   A small, white cross in front of the seven-story Ramada
Inn-Airport bears the words: ``In memory of the 10.'' The hotel
remains shut down.
   For the families of those who died in the crash on Oct. 20,
1987, the memories remain vivid and painful.
   ``All the families are just devastated,'' said Robert Goldberg,
whose 30-year-old daughter, Beth, was killed. ``We've had days this
week that were just as bad as the week after the accident.''
   Goldberg's daughter died when the powerless A-7D Corsair punched
through the clouds on an aborted emergency landing attempt and
slammed into the hotel. Moments earlier, the pilot, Maj. Bruce L.
Teagarden, had ejected safely.
   Teagarden, who was enroute from Pittsburgh to his home base in
Nevada, had lost his engine and was attempting a second run at the
Indianapolis International Airport. The pilotless jet slammed into
the hotel, a mile and a half from the runway.
   Teagarden, who was not seriously injured, was cleared of any
wrongdoing and resumed flying eight months after the crash. He is
in advanced training in Montgomery, Ala.
   Many of the victims' families will attend a memorial service
Thursday arranged by the Marion County Sheriff's Department at St.
Christopher's Catholic Church.
   Three of the dead were found behind the reception counter, two
were in an office behind the desk, two in a nearby laundry room and
two in the center of the lobby. The 10th victim, a salesman who had
stopped by to use a phone, died several days later.
   Charlotte Henry had talked to her daughter, Brenda, a hotel
maid, about 8 a.m., begging her to stay home with her 9-month-old
son, who was sick.
   ``By 10 after nine it was all over with. One of the girls (at
Mrs. Henry's office) told me something had happened at the
Ramada,'' she recalled.
   Mrs. Henry's grandson, Travis, now nearly 2 years old, is a
daily reminder of her 26-year-old daughter.
   ``I love him even more because he's a piece of her for me to
hold onto,'' Mrs. Henry said.
   Goldberg, whose daughter was the hotel's assistant sales
director, remembers the confusion and terror that he and his wife,
Harriet, felt after the 22-ton jet crashed.
   ``It was a day you never forget. You remember the flames, the
smoke, chasing around, the fear,'' he said. ``We were looking for
Beth and hoping she was going to appear and it never happened. You
ask yourself, `Did she suffer, did she try to get out?'''
   Larry Martin recently submitted a preliminary claim with the Air
Force for the death of his daughter Dawn Shelly Martin, 19, who was
a front desk clerk.
   Martin is a 28-year Air Force veteran who works at a bombing
range at Camp Atterbury near his rural Edinburgh home.
   ``I've never seen an A-7 since October 20th that I don't think
of my little girl lying there burning,'' he said.
   While his co-workers expressed sympathy on his daughter's death,
Martin says Air Force officials have ignored his loss.
   ``There is no justice in a society that would allow these things
to happen and not treat people with dignity and respect,'' he said.
``If I still feel this way in a few months, I'll probably seek
employment elsewhere.
   ``It hasn't gotten easier this first year,'' said Martin,
echoing the feelings of many of the families. ``I hope by next
spring my attention could get off of this.''
</TEXT>
