<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1504EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TrappedWhales 3rdLd-Writethru a0664 10-19 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trapped Whales, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0664,0918</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eskimos To The Rescue; More Help On The Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8-12th grafs, bgng `The trip...', with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with barge still in Prudhoe Bay, CORRECT that noon local time is 4
p.m. EDT. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `Officials hoped...'. Lead
prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BAR2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eskimo whalers wielding chain saws donated
by an oil company cut new breathing holes for three beleaguered
whales trapped two weeks in thick ice near the top of the world.
   The Eskimos on Tuesday cut three holes 75 yards apart in a line
leading away from the larger of two small breathing pools the
California gray whales have used since being stranded in the
Beaufort Sea while migrating south.
   The rescuers, who received a telephone pep talk Tuesday from
President Reagan, hope the new holes will influence the endangered
mammals to move in the direction they must travel if they are ever
to escape their icy corral.
   ``It'll be interesting to see if it works,'' North Slope Borough
biologist Craig George said as he dodged the slushy spray from
chain saws chewing through foot-deep ice 18 miles northeast of this
Inupiat Eskimo community. By Tuesday night, the whales hadn't moved
to the new holes, officials said.
   Standard Oil of Alaska donated three chain saws, and planned to
send a digging machine by helicopter to speed the work.
   Meanwhile, a long-shot attempt to free the whales with an
icebreaking barge was delayed until today.
   Two Alaska Army National Guard Skycrane helicopters have been
rigged to tow the 185-ton hovercraft barge from Prudhoe Bay, an oil
field about 200 miles southeast, in a tricky trip across Arctic
Ocean ice.
   The trip, which is expected to take 25 to 40 hours, was to have
started Monday or Tuesday, but was delayed when the barge got stuck
and was slowed again by refueling. Plans to get under way shortly
after daylight today were also put off, but rescuers were still
working through the morning and hoped to leave at about noon.
   Overnight, workers labored to decrease the amount of fuel on the
barge to reduce its weight by 70 tons.
   Army National Guard Chief Warrant Officer Tom Williams, a
helicopter copilot, said they hoped the barge, now that it's so
much lighter, wouldn't get bogged down in ``a goopy mess'' of mud
underneath ice close to shore, as it had Tuesday.
   ``The barge doesn't operate well unless it's over water or ice.
It started blowing mud out the sides and bogged down,'' he said
today as workers began getting ready for another try.
   By midmorning Alaska time, the National Guard office in Prudhoe
Bay said the much-delayed rescue mission was now scheduled to get
under way about noon (4 p.m. EDT), but few details of the morning's
efforts at the site were available. National Guard spokesman Mike
Haller had said earlier that if the barge could not be moved by
about noon today, officials would consider alternatives.
   Officials hoped to use the barge to carve a 40-foot path to open
water and freedom for the whales. The barge pulverizes ice with its
bulk and the fans that provide lift.
   Leads in the ice that were as close as five miles last weekend
have been plugged by shifting winds, record low temperatures and
drifting ice. By Tuesday night the nearest open water was believed
to be 100 miles away, officials said.
   The rescue effort, complicated by the harsh arctic conditions,
has become a race against time.
   The young whales are tired, and at least one has pneumonia.
Their barnacle-encrusted snouts have been worn raw from grating on
the jagged ice surrounding the breathing holes. The animals were in
shallow water only a few hundred feet from shore.
   Last week, ice around the holes was so thin biologists did not
dare walk on it. By Tuesday, with a record low temperature of minus
13 degrees, the ice was 18 to 24 inches thick.
   The whales are 24 to 30 feet long, but have shown no inclination
to smash their way to freedom.
   Their plight has drawn international attention.
   On Tuesday, Reagan telephoned Army National Guard Col. Tom
Carroll, commander of the rescue, to wish him well.
   ``I just wanted to tell you that everybody down here, their
hearts are with you and our prayers are also with you,'' Reagan
told Carroll, who was at the helicopter staging area at Prudhoe
Bay. ``Anything that we can say or do to help you along with the
success of the operation, we'd be pleased to do it.'' Biologists
said they were overwhelmed by the interest shown in the whale
drama. Scores of people have called with ideas to free the mammals,
such as using explosives, dropping bowling balls to break the ice,
or netting the whales for transport elsewhere.
   ``Every year, probably dozens of grays drown or are crushed by
the ice, but nobody ever knows about it,'' said George.
   But Ron Morris of the National Marine Fisheries said this case
is different. The whales are a little more than 100 yards from
shore and are easily viewed.
   ``It's simple. It happens every time with whales ... with any
marine mammals,'' Morris said. ``They're portrayed as gentle
creatures and the situation out there (on the ice) is sad; it's
really sad.''
</TEXT>
