<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FaultyPacemakers     10-19 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Faulty Pacemakers,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Wants Tougher Penalty, Rejects Cordis Plea in Pacemaker Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $123,000 fine does not compensate for thousands
of defective heart pacemakers and corrosion-prone batteries sold by
the Cordis Corp., a federal judge said Wednesday in rejecting the
company's plea bargain.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus pointed to a federal Food and
Drug Administration pre-sentencing report saying the company
knowingly continued to distribute the defective equipment between
December 1983 and October 1985.
   ``I am troubled by this report,'' Marcus said. ``It was my duty
to decide whether this plea agreement and guilty plea served the
interests of justice. ... I find that they do not.''
   Cordis is accused of 23 counts of selling defective pacemakers
between 1980 and 1985. The FDA said the devices, implanted under
the skin to regulate the heartbeat, could stop without warning.
   On Aug. 31 the company had agreed to plead guilty to the
charges, and faced the fine plus $141,000 in court costs under a
deal worked out with federal prosecutors.
   In rejecting that deal, Marcus criticized the government for
failing to file charges under a 1985 change in the law that would
have allowed fines of up to $500,000 per count, instead of the
maximum $10,000 under the older law. He set a new hearing on the
case for Oct. 26.
   The ruling does not affect a separate indictment of four former
Cordis officers, who have all pleaded innocent in that case.
   After Marcus' ruling, attorneys for both Miami-based Cordis and
the government defended the plea agreement.
   Cordis ``is no longer in this business and has a new
management,'' said U.S. Justice Department prosecutor Raymond
Philipps. ``We don't want to put the company out of business.''
   Cordis attorney Sherwin Markman said the fine is not the only
penalty that Cordis has suffered, noting it was required to sell
off the pacemaker division and has lost tens of millions of dollars.
   The company reported net losses of $56.1 million in 1987, but
underwent a major restructuring since selling the pacemaker
operation to Telectronics of Australia. Net earnings for 1988
totaled $2.4 million on sales of $132 million.
   The FDA report said that betweeen December 1983 and October
1985, Cordis shipped 2,200 pacemakers that were subject to
potential failure and 6,000 batteries they knew were subject to
corrosion.
   But company spokesman Chick McDowell denied that, saying Cordis
had never been charged with that offense.
   Cordis' main operations now include making catheters for
diagnosing and treating heart problems and gauges for monitoring
pressure on the brain.
   When the pacemaker case was announced, federal officials called
it the most significant felony prosecution to date under the 1976
Medical Device Amendments to the FDA law.
</TEXT>
