<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Ballet     10-19 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Ballet,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baryshnikov Brings Cancan to French Audience</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city paid tribute Wednesday to Mikhail
Baryshnikov and his American Ballet Theater after they wowed a high
society audience with an effervescent cancan at the European
premiere of ``Gaiete Parisienne.''
   At a party in City Hall, Mayor Jacques Chirac praised the
troupe, which is on its first trip to Europe in more than a decade.
   Its return to the French stage Tuesday night was a high point in
the city's cultural season, now in full swing with plays, concerts
and exhibitions filling theaters and exhibition spaces. The
company, which performs through Sunday, is part of Paris' 26th
International Festival of Dance.
   The troupe romped through opening night with a wicked joie de
vivre in a fluorescent flash of costumes by Christian Lecroix, the
rage of French haute couture.
   Turquoise-ruffled tulle, dotted chartreuse, zebra-striped gloves
and orange ostrich-plumed hats stretching toward the sky, the
splendid costumes were icing on Baryshnikov's delectable pastry
served up at the elegant Theater Champs Elysees.
   Among the first-night audience who paid $500 a seat were actor
Jack Nicholson, director Roman Polansky, the Baroness Guy de
Rothschild, Rudolf Nureyev, Prince Mubarak Al Sabah and U.S.
Ambassador Joe Rodgers.
   Lecroix's costumes were inspired by the Belle Epoch and
Toulouse-Lautrec rather than by the more staid Second Empire, which
was the basis for the costumes in the original production of
``Gaiete Parisienne.''
   The ballet was created in 1938 by Leonide Massine, the world's
best-known ballet choreographer between the wars, for the Ballet
Russe de Monte Carlo. It was performed continuously each season
from the time it was created until about 1960, but has fallen out
of fashion and is rarely performed these days.
   Set to the bubbling music of Jacques Offenbach, the ballet is a
series of frothy divertissements that tell of the flirtations and
romantic adventures of the demimonde in the 19th century. A flower
girl and a glove vendor compete for the attention of aristocrats,
soldiers, dandies and a naughty, mysterious Peruvian.
   The action takes place in a fantasy cafe, where the characters
enter down a sweeping, red-carpeted staircase framed by a pair of
pink French windows through which glows the Eiffel Tower.
   The centerpiece of the production, restaged for the American
Ballet Theater by Lorca Massine, the choreographer's son, is a
dazzling cancan.
   Eugenia Delarova Doll, the original flower girl and Massine's
wife at the time of the first production, once said that the cast
had so much fun performing the ballet they made ``the audience want
to come up on stage and dance with us.''
   The effect was the same Tuesday night, with the audience
breaking into spontaneous clapping as long-legged girls in polka
dot tights and ruffles kicked high to the familiar cancan melody.
   ``I'm very pleased,'' said Baryshnikov, artistic director for
the company, in an interview after the ballet. ``Gala audiences are
known for being very conservative and we were very enthusiastically
received.''
   The first half of the program was less successful, opening with
the lackadaisical ``Fandango,'' a mock Spanish dance performed by
five ballerinas. ``Le Jardin de Villandry,'' performed by a trio of
two men and a woman was reminiscent of the Francois Truffaut film
``Jules et Jim.''
   After the ballet, dancers mixed with the beau monde, at a dinner
in the Petit Palais museum. Many of those walking past the museum's
collection were works of art themselves, dressed in gowns by Yves
St. Laurent, Givenchy and, of course, Lecroix.
   A string orchestra played at the top of the spiral staircase
down which ballerinas glided toward candlelit tables and champagne.
</TEXT>
