<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ExecutionStayed     10-19 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Execution Stayed,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Rapist-Murderer Wins Stay of Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Wednesday
stayed the execution of a onetime motorcycle gang leader less than
12 hours before he was scheduled to die for the rape and murder of
a tavern waitress.
   The execution of George ``Tiny'' Mercer would have been the
first in Missouri since 1965. The action by a three-judge panel of
the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals was the second time this
month the court has blocked an execution in the state the same day
it was to occur.
   Missouri Attorney General William Webster's office planned to
immediately file a motion to vacate the stay with the entire
10-member court.
   ``We're filing this motion because we believe the issues are
easily resolved in favor of the state,'' said Mary Jenkins, a
spokesman for Webster. ``We feel like nine years has been an
adequate length of time for the appeals process.''
   Mercer, 44, was to have been put to death by lethal injection at
12:01 a.m. Thursday at the Missouri State Penitentiary.
   In its unanimous decision to grant a stay, the three-judge
panel, meeting in St. Paul, Minn., said it needed more time to
review Mercer's case.
   If the entire Appeals Court were to vacate the stay, Mercer's
court-appointed lawyer, Douglas S. Laird, could appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   U.S. District Judge Scott Wright of Kansas City had refused to
stay Mercer's execution Tuesday, citing the ``incredibily heinous
nature'' of the crime.
   Mercer was sentenced to death in 1979 for the rape and
strangulation of 22-year-old Karen Keeton at his home in Belton,
south of Kansas City.
   Records show friends brought Ms. Keeton to Mercer, who was free
on bond in the rape of a 17-year-old girl, as a ``birthday
present.'' During the assault in which Mercer forced Ms. Keeton to
have sex with him at gunpoint before killing her, Mercer's
11-year-old daughter was in the house.
   At the time of his conviction, Mercer was reported to be a
leader of two morotocycle gangs in the Kansas City area _ the
Rancid Riders and the Missing Links. He has contended that
prejudice against motorcycle gangs is the reason he was convicted
of killing Ms. Keeton.
   Mercer's execution would mark the state's first in 23 years, the
first time the death penalty has been carried out under the state's
11-year-old reinstated capital punishment law and the first use in
Missouri of lethal injection.
   Prison authorities began preparations for execution last month
after convicted killer Gerald Smith demanded that further appeals
be dropped so his execution could be carried out.
   Smith's scheduled execution Oct. 4 was blocked by the 8th
Circuit just hours before it was to occur. The federal judges
wanted more time to review Smith's competency.
</TEXT>
