<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-People-Tyson 1stLd-Writethru a0576 10-19 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Tyson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0576,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Givens To Tyson: Here's Your Divorce, Keep The Money</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Givens' statement that she will seek
no money settlement in divorce. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Robin Givens said today she would give
heavyweight boxing champion Michael Tyson a divorce without taking
any money from him for herself.
   ``I never wanted anything but what was best for Michael,''
Givens said in a statement read by her lawyer, Raoul Felder. ``I
never wanted anything for myself and I never sought anything for
myself.''
   The statement was issued by Felder at a news conference in his
office. Givens was not present.
   The actress, who appears on ABC's situation comedy ``Head of the
Class,'' decried the publicity surrounding the divorce action she
initiated earlier this month and said she wanted Tyson and herself
to go forward with their lives in dignity.
   ``Therefore, although I understand my lawyers are waiting for an
offer in money, the exact amount of which is not ascertained at
this time, but presumably it will be considerable, before it is
forthcoming, I unequivocally and irrevocably state as follows:
   ``1. Michael can have his divorce.
   ``2. I will not seek nor accept any money for myself.''
   Tyson was in Venezuela and not immediately availalbe for
comment. Earlier today, the New York Post published a story quoting
him as saying his failed marriage has made him ``almost
anti-women,'' but conceded he still loves Givens.
   Givens filed for divorce Oct. 7 in California, citing
irreconcilable differences. If Givens had been able to prove that
the couple actually resided in California, the state's community
property divorce law would have provided that the couple split the
earnings received during the marriage.
   Tyson won a a multimillion-dollar purse in a heavyweight
championship bout this summer. The couple were married in February.
   Last Friday in Trenton, N.J., Tyson filed for divorce and
annulment of their marriage, claiming that Givens tricked him into
marrying her by falsely claiming she was pregnant.
   ``I'm learning so much from this, but I wouldn't wish a divorce
on my worst enemy,'' said Tyson, 22, in the Post interview.
   ``I'm still madly in love with Robin,'' he said, but added, ``I
can't go back with her. I couldn't do it. ... I think that she is
basically a good person, but now, after all this, who would want to
be with her?''
   ``I'm almost anti-women, after what I've been through,'' he said
with a laugh.
   The boxer confessed that ``the nicest girl I've ever met'' was
former Miss America Suzette Charles, 25, whom he dated briefly
before marrying Givens in February. ``I should've taken my chances
with Suzette, but I was too wild back then,'' he said.
   Charles, of Los Angeles, told the Newspaper she was flattered by
Tyson's comments, but said ``we were just friends.''
</TEXT>
