<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Crashes-Airline     10-19 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Crashes-Airline,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crash Was Worst in Airline's History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India-Crashes, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash Wednesday of an Indian
Airlines jetliner in the central city of Ahmedabad is the worst
disaster in the 26-year history of the carrier, which has been
accused of lax safety procedures.
   At least 130 people were killed in the airline's 16th major
accident since it was formed 26 years ago to handle domestic
traffic and short flights to neighboring countries.
   The worst previous accident for the airlines was in 1976, when a
Caravelle aircraft exploded at Bombay airport while landing.
Ninety-five people were killed in the crash, blamed on leaking fuel
pipes.
   In 1973, 49 people died when a Boeing 737 made a crash landing
short of the runway at New Delhi airport.
   Indian Airlines is owned by the government, as is Air-India,
which operates only on international routes.
   Wednesday's crash comes 12 years after the last fatal accident
on the airlines, but some recent reports have criticized safety
measures.
   In June, the pilot of an Indian Airlines plane forgot to lower
the landing gear before landing at New Delhi. The aircraft
slithered along the runway on its belly but no one was hurt.
   India Today newsmagazine said in its latest issue that safety
measures were ignored on Indian Airlines flights and that pilots
``exhibited a cavalier disregard for their own and passengers'
lives.''
   ``Mandatory safety-related procedures are often reduced to a
paper exercise,'' the magazine said. ``Doctors who conduct
pre-flight alcohol tests on pilots sign stacks of reports _ the
pilot just fills his name, date and flight number.''
   The airline refused comment.
   In September 1986, the pilot of an Indian Airlines Airbus
aborted takeoff at Madras airport after the nose of the aircraft
was already in the air. Newspaper reports said heavy concentrations
of alcohol were found in the blood of the pilot, the co-pilot and
the engineer of the plane.
   Indian Airlines is the largest regional airline in South Asia.
It operates flights to 73 airports in India and nine in neighboring
countries.
</TEXT>
