<HEAD>Biographies of Nobel Physics Laureates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brief sketches of the American winners
of the Nobel Prize in physics:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Leon M. Lederman was born in Buffalo, N.Y., on July 15, 1922. He
earned a doctorate in physics in 1951 and became a professor at
Columbia University seven years later. He is now director of the
Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory in Batavia, Ill., where he is
continuing work on particle research.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Melvin Schwartz was born Nov. 2, 1932 in New York and earned his
doctorate in physics in 1958. After working on the prize-winning
project, he became a professor at Stanford University in 1966. He
left academia to start a private company, Digital Pathways Inc. in
Mountain View, Calif., which specializes in computer communications.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jack Steinberger was born May 25, 1921, in Bad Kissingen, now
part of West Germany. He received his doctorate in 1948. Two years
later he became a professor at Columbia University. In 1968 he
moved to Geneva to join the CERN research laboratory. The Royal
Academy of Sciences listed him as Swiss in its citation for the
prize but mentioned his American citizenship in its background
paper on achievements.
</TEXT>
