<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CourthouseShooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0680 10-19 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Courthouse Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0680,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Killed By Estranged Husband, A Policeman, at Michigan
Courthouse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with account of incident,
including wounded judge trying to flee, other detail; CORRECTS
spelling of Ratliff sted Ratlif and CORRECTS ages of suspect,
victim, and length of time husband has been on police force. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, `Gunshots sailed...'. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-year veteran of the city police
department opened fire in the county courthouse today and killed
his estranged wife, the county's first female judge, authorities
said.
   Police said Clarence Ratliff, 53, was taken into custody and
that his wife, District Judge Carol S. Irons, 40, was killed in the
incident shortly after noon today. There were no other injuries
reported.
   Irons, elected in 1982, was the first woman judge in Kent County.
   After the initial shooting, the wounded judge ran from her
chambers into a nearby courtroom, while her husband chased her and
fired at least two or three more shots, police said.
   She died in the courtroom. Police Chief William Hegarty said it
was not immediately clear whether the judge was wounded a second
time during the chase.
   A witness, John Smith, said he was just leaving the building
when ``I heard three shots, rapid fire'' and saw ``people running
out of the building, falling on the floor. I ran because I didn't
want to be hit.''
   The police chief said Ratliff had no history of mental problems
and there was no reason to believe Irons feared him. Irons called
the police dispatcher on an intercom at 12:07 p.m. and said her
estranged husband had a weapon to her head, Hegarty said.
   Police said Ratliff was off duty at the time of the incident and
was wearing street clothes. It was not immediately determined if a
police gun was used in the shooting.
   Gunshot sailed over the heads of some employees who were in
chambers with the victim, said the senior judge in the county,
Chief Judge Donald Johnston.
   ``In addition to a lot of criminal suspects here, the people
here are undergoing severe strees involved in divorces, child
custody. ... There are a lot of wrought emotions here,'' Johnston
Johnston said. ``There's a potential threat continually.''
   The Hall of Justice, which houses courts and the Grand Rapids
Police Department, was cordoned off and surrounded by police cars
and ambulances.
   Court staff workers were crying and consoling one another
following the shooting, and officials said the courts would be
closed for the rest of the day.
</TEXT>
