<2ND_LINE>AM-Mosaic Controversy,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mosaic Portraying Freed Slave Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black man once shown in a City Hall
mosaic as a smiling freed slave now carries a hoe and has a
different smile, ending a dispute that started when critics said
the artwork was demeaning to blacks.
   The 10- by 40-foot mosaic, created in the mid-1960s, showed
white settlers in covered wagons and a smiling freed slave,
celebrating his freedom with a broken rope hanging from his wrists.
   Complaints about the mural started in 1986, but the City Council
did not approve the changes until a year ago. The $1,200 project
was financed by private donors.
   The new tile work was finished on the mosaic Tuesday.
   ``The black man now has a hoe in his hand and the smile that he
wore was changed a bit. It's a nice smile,'' said city Clerk Nina
Baird, whose first-floor office is only a few steps from the
mosaic. ``It's nice to have it over with.''
   The son of late designer Edward Kane filed a lawsuit in March in
an unsuccesful attempt to stop the revisions, claiming they would
infringe on the rights of artists.
</TEXT>
