<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Comair-Charges     10-19 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Comair-Charges,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libel Lawsuit Filed By Comair Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A regional airline has filed a libel suit
against the attorney for five crew members who contend they were
held against their will in a hotel room to undergo drug tests.
   The lawsuit says Covington lawyer Garry L. Edmondson told
reporters at a news conference in September that Comair Airline
managers ``shanghaied'' the pilot and four flight attendants and
used ``Gestapo-like tactics'' to obtain urine samples.
   The suit contends the statements damaged the reputation of
Comair, which is based at Greater Cincinnati International Airport
near Hebron, Ky.
   The lawsuit, which seeks unspecified compensatory and punitive
damages, was filed Tuesday in Ohio's Hamilton County Common Pleas
Court. The county includes the bulk of the Cincinnati area's
newspaper readers and television viewers, Comair attorney Richard
Creighton said.
   Edmondson said he had not seen the lawsuit and would not comment
on it except to say, ``sounds desperate to me.''
   Also Tuesday, six Comair executives were charged with
misdemeanor unlawful imprisonment. Boone County Attorney Larry
Crigler said he filed the charges at the request of the employees
who said they were held against their will.
   He said no physical restraint was involved, but that the company
figures used their managerial authority to order the employees not
to leave.
   The five employees say they were coerced into taking surprise
drug tests. The employees say the tests showed no evidence of drug
use.
   ``The company denies that any of the conduct that is complained
of was criminal in nature,'' Creighton said Tuesday. The airline
also has denied liability in civil lawsuits filed Sept. 22 by the
airlines' employees.
   Comair fired five other employees, including three pilots, last
month, reportedly because the five either failed drug tests or
admitted that they used drugs while off duty. The three pilots have
filed grievances against the company.
   The Federal Aviation Administration has proposed a regulation
that would require random drug screening of ten of thousands of
pilots, flight attendants and other airline employees. Airline
labor unions oppose the measure, arguing there is no evidence of a
problem in the industry to warrant it.
</TEXT>
