<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan     10-19 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Western Death Toll 20 Times Too High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi said Wednesday
the death toll from civil war and famine in his country was 20
times lower than Western estimates, and he rejected criticism of
his handling of the crisis.
   Mahdi said his government has taken ``great measures'' in trying
to help thousands of refugees witnesses describe as being ``no more
than skin over bone.''
   Western relief officials, who compare the situation in Sudan to
the Ethiopian famine of recent years, said Tuesday that about
260,000 people have died in 1988 because of lack of food and
medical care during long treks to escape the fighting in southern
Sudan.
   Mahdi said in an interview with The Associated Press that ``I
don't think the loss of life was more than 10 per 1,000.'' That
would be the equivalent of about 13,000.
   He acknowledged that the army, which represents the Moslems in
the north, has suffered setbacks in recent fighting against the
southern rebels, most of whom are Christians or animists fighting
for autonomy.
   But Mahdi, a Moslem, said the government has acted effectively
to help thousands of refugees whom witnesses have described as
being ``no more than skin over bone.''
   ``The United Nations representative has recognized the great
measures taken by the Sudanese government to bring relief to the
displaced. He generally approved the way the situation was
handled,'' said the prime minister, who was interviewed in his
office in Khartoum.
   ``Criticism of the government floated by some is misinformed,''
said Mahdi, dressed in a traditional Sudanese flowing white robe
and white turban.
   Some Western relief experts have charged that the government has
not been effective in easing the plight of the southerners fleeing
on foot hundreds of miles northward or east into Ethiopia.
   Bona Malwal, editor of the English language daily The Sudan
Times, this week criticized the government's relief effort as ``too
little, too late.''
   An estimated 2 million people have abandoned their homes since
the rebellion began in 1983. About 1.3 million of them set out this
year alone.
   Fritz Gilbert, who heads the U.S. aid program in Sudan, told the
AP Wednesday that the southern refugees are ``starving and dying in
terrible numbers.''
   He said he has no exact figure but believes there are hundreds
of thousands of victims. The magnitude of the Sudanese problem can
be compared to the famine in Ethiopia in recent years, Gilbert said.
   This year, about 700,000 southerners trekked to Khartoum,
150,000 to Juba in the province of Equatoria, 300,000 to Ethiopia
and 150,000 to Kordofan and Darfur provinces in southwestern Sudan,
according to UNICEF, the United Nation's child-welfare agency.
   A U.S.-funded operation to bring relief to the tiny town of
Abyei, 500 miles southwest of Khartoum, entered its seventh day
Wednesday.
   Gilbert said government and foreign supplies to Abyei can feed
only 15,000 until the end of the rainy season this month, while
there are up to 30,000 refugees in the town.
   ``The people arrived in terrible shape, having trekked hundreds
of miles,'' Gilbert said. ``Food was insufficient, and they started
to starve and die. Kids are in very poor condition.''
   Witnesses who traveled to Abyei on relief planes reported that
they saw thousands of people who were ``no more than skin over
bone.'' The witnesses said children seemed to be the worst off.
   Western relief officials, who asked not to be identified, say up
to 10 people are dying in Abyei every day.
   Mahdi said his government regularly reviews the activities of
more than 90 relief organizations in Sudan to check if they are
operating legally.
   ``Some non-governmental organizations, because of their own
motivations and ideals, may have other than humanitation activities
in mind,'' he said. The government has accused some agencies of
delivering supplies to the rebels and thus prolonging the war.
   Mahdi said that since taking office in April 1986, he has made
13 peace offers to renegade army Col. John Garang, the leader of
the guerrillas, but has received no firm response.
   The rebels have said they captured six army positions in recent
weeks, but the government has acknowledged the loss of only four.
</TEXT>
