<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0653 10-19 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Charges Against Former CIA Agent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds one graf of defense lawyer reax</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Wednesday permitted
Iran-Contra prosecutors to drop charges here against a former CIA
agent and seek a new indictment across the Potomac River in
Virginia.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. dismissed a
five-count indictment that charged Joseph F. Fernandez participated
in an illegal conspiracy to help arm Nicaraguan rebels and later
lied to cover up his role in the covert operation.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh sought dismissal in order
to bring the charges anew in federal court in Virginia, where
Fernandez is alleged to have lied to CIA superiors and the
presidential board that investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   The defense had sought to quash a new prosecution on the ground
that Walsh had improperly brought charges against Fernandez in
Washington that should have been filed in Virginia.
   But in dismissing the charges without prejudice, Robinson gave
Walsh the opportunity to bring the case before a new federal grand
jury in Alexandria, Va.
   Fernandez, 51, was indicted June 20 on a charge that he
conspired with former National Security Council aide Oliver L.
North and arms dealer Richard V. Secord to set up a clandestine
arms-supply network for the Contra rebels in defiance of a
congressional ban on such aid.
   The alleged conspiracy took place in Washington and elsewhere,
according to the indictment.
   Fernandez, who went by the pseudonym Tomas Castillo when he was
the CIA's station chief in Costa Rica, was also charged with four
counts of lying to his superiors at CIA headquarters in Langley,
Va., about his role in the operation and to the presidential
commission headed by former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas. The
questioning by the Tower Commission also occurred at Langley,
according to the indictment.
   Last month, the defense moved to dismiss the false-statements
and obstruction charges for lack of jurisdiction.
   Walsh countered with a motion to dismiss the entire indictment,
saying he wanted an opportunity to prosecute the entire case in
Virginia.
   Robinson, who had sharply questioned prosecutors about their
tactics at a hearing on Oct. 6, gave no reason for his decision in
the one-sentence order.
   Defense attorney Thomas E. Wilson said he was disappointed that
the judge did not bar further prosecution of Fernandez but added:
``The independent counsel had 18 months to get an indictment
returned and it's been dismssed in three months.''
</TEXT>
