<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Tisch,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Count CBS Boss Among `Roseanne' Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' has an unlikely fan _ CBS
President Laurence Tisch, who congratulated his rivals Wednesday
for creating a ``wonderful'' television show.
   Tisch, speaking to the International Radio & Television Society,
said he was ``heartened'' by the show's premiere Tuesday night
because it showed that the three major networks can compete with
cable channels.
   ``It shows you that if we deliver wonderful programs to the
American people, they want to watch network television,'' he said.
   ``Roseanne'' stars comedian Roseanne Barr as a blue collar
housewife who struggles to cope with a husband and three children.
   Tisch, who said he was ``being realistic about the weaknesses in
our prime-time schedule,'' also expressed envy over NBC's
much-scorned ratings for the Summer Olympics.
   ``With all the talk of the poor ratings, I'd love to have those
ratings on CBS,'' Tisch said. CBS recently paid $243 million for
rights to the 1992 Winter Olympics.
