<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ParisCafe     10-19 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paris Cafe,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famous Champs Elysees Watering Hole to Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Le Fouquet's, the famed cafe-restaurant threatened
with closure, on Wednesday was proposed for listing as a historic
monument, a move that should safeguard the high society haunt.
   The Regional Commission for Historic, Archaeological and
Ethnological Patrimony voted overwhelmingly to inscribe the
building housing Le Fouquet's on the Supplementary Inventory of
Historic Monuments and Edifices, the commission announced.
   The measure, which must be formalized within a month, obliges
the landlord to obtain authorization from the Ministry of Culture
for any changes in architecture or decor.
   ``The architecture of Le Fouquet's merits preservation because
it participates elegantly in the urban decor,'' said Culture
Minister Jack Lang.
   Le Fouquet's, located on a prime corner of the Champs Elysees,
is well-known as a gathering place for the rich and famous.
   In July, it announced it might have to close because of a rent
increase by the building's proprietor, a Kuwaiti holding company.
   A committee, fearing a fast-food chain in its place, was formed
to try to save the watering hole.
   The decision by the Regional Commission does not completely
safeguard Le Fouquet's from eventual closure, which can only be
done by ``classifying'' the building, a proposal the Commission
failed to make.
   However, the Culture minister himself can seek to classify the
building if he disagrees with proposed changes.
   Lang said the commission already marked a turning point because
it ruled favorably on a ``place of memories'' rather than a clearly
historic building.
   In other rulings Wednesday, the Commission did propose
classifying Julien, a restaurant in the center of Paris known for
its 1900s decor.
   It proposed inscribing a number of other eating establishments
on the Supplementary Inventory of Historic Monuments. Among them
were: Lipp, on the Boulevard St. Germain; Bofinger, near the
Bastille; and Pharamond, in Les Halles.
</TEXT>
