<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Korea     10-19 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korea,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Welcomes South Korean Peace Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department welcomed on Wednesday
peace initiatives set forth by South Korean President Roh Tae-woo
but said a cautious approach towards North Korea is required
because of that Marxist country's long record of ``state terror.''
   Department spokesman Charles Redman withheld comment on Roh's
specific proposal, which calls for a summit meeting with North
Korean President Kim Il-sung and for a general effort to secure
peace and prosperity in Northeast Asia. Roh spoke Tuesday to the
U.N. General Assembly.
   Overall, Redman said, ``we welcome the imaginative and
constructive policy of reconciliation and accommodation that
President Roh is putting forward.''
   He said the specifics of Roh's proposal will be discussed at a
meeting here Thursday between Roh and President Reagan.
   A proposal even more ambitious than Roh's was unveiled Wednesday
at the General Assembly by North Korean Deputy Foreign Minister
Kang Sok Ju, who called for the creation of a new nation out of the
two Koreas with a shared military command.
   Redman reaffirmed that the United States is reviewing its policy
toward North Korea following the resumption of talks between the
two Koreas at Panmunjom and the show of North Korean restraint
during the Seoul Olympics last month.
   There had been concern that North Korea would attempt to disrupt
the Olympic games.
   Redman noted that North Korea remains on the U.S. list of
countries that engage in state-sponsored terrorism and any policy
changes the administration undertakes will not include the removal
of the Pyongyang government from that list.
   ``I would emphasize that North Korea's well-established track
record of belligerence and state terror makes a very cautious
approach to this issue necessary,'' Redman said.
   Among the steps the administration might take, officials said,
is the relaxation of restrictions on diplomatic contact between
U.S. and North Korean officials.
   The Reagan administration reimposed strict limitations last
January following a terrorist incident 11 months ago in which a
South Korean passenger plane was blown up, killing all 115 aboard.
   The administration said evidence of North Korean involvement in
the incident was compelling.
   A State Department official who briefed reporters Tuesday on the
condition of anonymity said the administration ``will probably have
an announcement'' on policy changes toward North Korea a few days
after Thursday's White House meeting.
   ``We certainly want to be responsive to President Roh's policy
changes and what he wants to do,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
