<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BattleshipReturns     10-19 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Battleship Returns,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Modernized World War II Battleship Ready To Rejoin Fleet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Wisconsin, the last of four huge
battleships brought back to life by the Reagan administration to
strengthen the Navy, will be recommissioned this weekend during
ceremonies in Mississippi, the Pentagon said Wednesday.
   The return to active duty for the 887-foot warship will begin on
Saturday morning at the Ingalls Shipbuilding yards in Pascagoula,
Miss. Former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, will deliver the principal
address during the ceremonies, the Pentagon added.
   The Wisconsin will join three other World War II battleships
that were modernized and returned to service: the Iowa, New Jersey
and Missouri.
   Thanks to the modernization work, the four vessels are
considered among the most powerful surface warships in the world.
   Each of them features nine 16-inch guns, capable of firing
2,700-pound armor-piercing shells up to 23 miles. The battleships
also carry 12 five-inch guns and have been modernized with box
launchers for Tomahawk cruise missiles; canister launchers for
Harpoon missiles; and four Phalanx gatling guns to defend against
aerial attacks.
   The Wisconsin's reactivation began more than two years ago, when
the vessel was taken out of mothballs in Philadelphia in August
1986 and towed to Pascagoula. The ship is 887 feet long, 108 feet
wide and displaces 58,000 tons.
   Its four geared turbines are capable of driving the ship at
speeds in excess of 30 knots.
   The Wisconsin was launched on Dec. 7, 1943, and operated in the
Pacific during World War II with Adm. William F. Halsey's Third
Fleet, earning five battle stars. It was decommissioned in July
1948, but brought back to service again in March 1951 for the
Korean War.
   The ship earned another battle star during that conflict and was
decommissioned again in March 1958.
   It cost $448.8 million to modernize the Wisconsin and return it
to active duty, a figure the Navy describes as a fraction of the
cost of building such a ship from scratch today.
   The Wisconsin will call Norfolk, Va., its home port for now, but
it eventually is to be based at a new Navy base now being built in
Texas. The ship will be sailed by a crew of 1,600.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-19 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Dissenters Arrested, Guerrilla Rockets Kill 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Committee of the
Soviet-style party that has governed Afghanistan for the past
decade convened Wednesday after dissenters within the party were
arrested.
   Also on Thursday, anti-government guerrillas fired 21 rockets
into Kabul airport, killing nine people and wounding 17, security
officials said. The official Kabul radio confirmed the death toll
but said 18 were injured.
   Afghan security forces sealed off all streets leading to the
hall where the 140-member Central Committee of the People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan met.
   The meeting was expected to begin last week, but Afghan and
foreign sources said the session apparently was delayed by
high-level internal disputes.
   Official sources said on condition of anonymity that the chief
business at the meeting was ``national reconciliation,'' the
government's term for peaceful efforts to halt the fighting between
U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas and Afghan and Soviet troops.
   Afghanistan's state-run television said the Central Committee
dropped two men from the communist party's 13-man Politburo.
Neither was prominent.
   Few details of the arrests of party members were made public in
this country where party and government activities usually are
veiled by official secrecy.
   But one official source said on condition of anonymity that the
arrests were ``due to some opposition activity that they were
launching against the policy of national reconciliation.''
   He said he didn't know how many were arrested or whether they
were members of the Central Committee. Another Afghan source said
the arrests numbered in the dozens, and a Western diplomat said he
had unconfirmed reports that 10 to 15 people were detained.
   The party is divided into two factions: President Najib's
Parcham group and the more hawkish Khalq group headed by Interior
Minister Sayed Mohammad Gulabzhoi. It was not known which faction
those arrested belonged to.
   The Politburo members who dismissed Wednesday were Saleh
Mohammad Zarry, a longtime prominent party member, and Zalour
Razinjo, former Kabul party secretary. Razinjo is about 30 and was
the Politburo's youngest member.
   No replacements were announced.
   Afghan observers said Sarry was associated with the Khalq wing,
while Razinjo had ties with Parcham.
   As Soviet troops withdraw from Afghanistan, ending nine years of
military intervention to prop up the government, Najib increasingly
has tried to portray his government as separate from the party. But
virtually all its non-party members have belonged to
non-threatening loyal opposition groups or are technocrats who
worked with the party in the past.
   Under an accord signed in Geneva in April, all Soviet troops are
to leave Afghanistan by Feb. 15, 1989. The withdrawal started May
15 and is now half over, with an estimated 50,000 to 60,000 Red
Army soldiers still in Afghanistan.
   Some foreign diplomats say the Soviets may not want major
political upheaval until their withdrawal is over. They say any
change in leadership may be little more than cosmetic.
   The guerrillas' leaders, based in neighboring Pakistan, have
refused to deal with Najib or participate in a coalition government.
   The United States and most other Western countries have refused
to recognize the Kabul government since the Soviet intervention in
1979.
   The guerrillas have continued to rocket Kabul and besiege other
major cities such as Kandahar depite the the Soviet withdrawal.
   Wednesday's rocket attack on Kabul airport closed it to civilian
flights for the rest of the day and for Thursday, said an officer
of Sarandoy, a paramilitary force that guards airport entrances.
   Soviet and Afghan troops continued to operate helicopters and
airplanes from the airport.
   The Sarandoy officer said only one rocket caused casualties. He
said two Soviet women and a Soviet girl of about 2 were killed, and
one Soviet boy was wounded. The rest of the victims were Afghans,
he said.
   The victims were waiting in a tent outside the airport gate for
a flight to Tashkent and Moscow on Ariana, the Afghan airline.
</TEXT>
