<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-PLO     10-19 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Left-Wing Israeli Legislators Meet With PLO Delegation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two left-wing legislators defied Israeli
law and met with a high-ranking PLO delegation in Yugoslavia
earlier this week, the legislators said Wednesday.
   Matityahu Peled and Muhammad Miari, who represent the mixed
Arab-Jewsih Progressive List for Peace, issued a call for an
independent Palestinian state that woulc co-exist with Israel.
   A statement was being issued in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, by the two
legislators and the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Peled and Miari told reporters in Tel Aviv that they met in
Belgrade with a PLO delegation headed by top-ranking Mahmoud Abbas,
a member of the organization's executive committee.
   The two Israelis said they recognize the Palestinians
``unquestioned right to self-determination and the establishment of
a sovereign and independent state on the soil of its homeland,
alongside Israel.''
   The statement also accepted ``all United Nations decisions''
that recognize Israel's right to exist and called on Israel to
withdraw from the West Bank and Gaza, territories occupied in the
1967 Middle East war.
   An amendment to the anti-terrorist law passed in 1986 bars
Israelis from meeting with PLO representatives and gives violators
prison terms of up to three years.
   In June, four Israelis were sentended to six months in prison
each and fined $2,500 for meeting PLO representatives in Romania in
1986.
   Miari and Peled have parliamentary immunity from prosecution but
the Knesset, Israel's parliament, could vote to strip them of that
privilege.
   Israel radio reported that Avi Farhan, a leader of the
right-wing Tehiya Party, has lodged a complaint with police against
Peled and Miari.
   The two left-wing legislators are running for re-election as
candidates of the Progressive List for Peace, which calls on Israel
to negotiate with the PLO and supports the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state.
   Several other Israelis, including peace activist Abie Nathan,
face charges for meetings with PLO representatives. Nathan recently
held talks with PLO head Yasser Arafat in Tunisia.
</TEXT>
