<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     10-19 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Courts Urban Voters, Heads Back to Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIBERTY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle gave his backroads
campaign a brief urban twist Wednesday and said the GOP is seeking
a ``clear majority'' among traditionally Democratic Jewish voters.
   Quayle met privately with about 15 Jewish backers in Chicago,
emerging to concede ``we haven't done as good a job as we should
have'' among Jewish voters, but said the GOP will ``make inroads''
in that voting bloc.
   Aides said there was no discussion at the closed meeting of
earlier Quayle stumbles while answering questions about the murder
of Jews In World War II.
   In addition, Quayle rejected suggestions that an incident in
which GOP campaign workers were fired for alleged anti-Semitic
leanings had hurt the ticket.
   ``It came up, was brought to our attention and we handled it
with dispatch,'' Quayle told reporters who questioned him about the
dismissals. ``It's over and done with.''
   He insisted the campaign had cleared its name and ``we're not
going to stand for any attitudes like that.''
   The brief campaign stop in Chicago was a departure for Quayle,
who has spent most of his time in smaller towns.
   After meeting with Jewish backers, he briefly toured a job
training site in an ethnic neighborhood in Chicago, before heading
out for a day of stumping across rural Missouri.
   Motorcading across the state, Quayle toured factories and spoke
at schools attacking Democrat Michael Dukakis for a ``dangerous and
naive'' approach to foreign policy.
   Quayle said the GOP would make gains by focusing on pro-Israeli
policies.
   There have been suggestions that growing tensions between blacks
and Jews in the Democratic Party have left an opening for the GOP,
but Quayle wasn't asked to address that issue.
   ``If you look at the numbers, they're not where they should
be,'' Quayle said. ``We're not going to be satisfied until we get a
clear majority and we don't have that right now.''
   Republicans, Quayle said, haven't done their homework in telling
Jewish voters why they should switch from Democrats.
   ``There are a lot of things we have to offer the Jewish
community,'' Quayle said.
   ``Evidently, we haven't done as good a job as we should have in
communicating where the Republican Party is vis-a-vis Israel, where
the Republican Party is vis-a-vis the Jewish community,'' Quayle
said. ``I'll be the first to admit that we've got more work to do.''
   Quayle found himself in the middle of a controversy earlier in
the campaign when he fumbled answers to questions about the
Holocoust during World War II, but he was not questioned about that
incident after Wednesday's meeting.
   In addition, spokesman David Prosperi said ``it did not come
up'' during the meeting.
   ``We had a lot of good issues come forward,'' Quayle said.
   He insisted that it's realistic for Republicans to court Jewish
voters, because that's simply one more group the GOP can bring
under its broadening umbrella.
   ``The bottom line is we are committed to expanding our base and
one of those bases is the Jewish community,'' Quayle said.
   One of the staples of the Quayle campaign is a tour of a job
training site because of his role in crafting legislation which
created training programs.
   On Wednesday, however, he was questioned about the role his
wife, Marilyn, would play in a new administration.
   ``I don't believe she's crossed that bridge yet, or if she has
she hasn't told me,'' said Quayle.
   Mrs. Quayle is spending time this week campaigning in
California, while he stumps the Midwest.
   In Missouri, Quayle stumped in St. Joseph, Liberty, Blue Springs
before heading to Kansas City.
   He has been focusing on building regional ties in the Midwest,
and aides said they planned to continue that theme on Thursday with
yet another bus trip, this one in Ohio.
</TEXT>
