<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-American     10-19 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-American,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Describes Shooting Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American news photographer said Wednesday
that Israeli soldiers who shot him during a stone-throwing clash
Tuesday were not in physical danger when they opened fire.
   Neal Cassidy, a photographer for the Oakland, Calif.-based
Frontline newspaper, was the first journalist shot in the
10-month-old Palestinian uprising.
   Cassidy, who is in good condition at a hospital in Arab east
Jerusalem, was shot in the right knee with a plastic bullet during
a Palestinian demonstration in Nablus.
   He said soldiers opened fire after a group of five or six
Palestinian youths began shouting and throwing stones at them. He
said the demonstrators were about 150 yards from the soldiers.
   ``That's a pretty good distance,'' Cassidy said from his
hospital bed. ``They were throwing stones in the direction of the
soldiers, but they were too far to reach.
   ``I didn't have the sense that they (the soldiers) were in any
physical danger. There was no physical threat.''
   A photograph Cassidy said he took moments before he was shot
showed five soldiers, one with his gun raised, standing in the
street where the incident took place.
   The photo also showed a young man standing behind the soldiers
preparing to throw a stone.
   Army regulations allow soldiers to open real ammunition fire
only if their lives are in danger. However, trained troopers may
fire plastic bullets for riot dispersal, even if the soldiers are
not endangered.
   An army spokesman said Tuesday that troops fired in Nablus while
being stoned, adding that Cassidy ``endangered himself'' by being
close to the rioters in an area the military had ordered closed to
outsiders.
   A 5-year-old boy and a teen-ager were killed in West Bank
clashes Tuesday.
   Cassidy, 37, of Oakland, said he refused to go to a Jewish
hospital for treatment when Israeli authorities asked him to
transfer from an Arab clinic after the attack.
   ``I told them I had seen enough of their hospitality,'' he said.
``First they shoot me and then they want to take me to their
hospital. I said `No thanks.'''
   On Wednesday, Palestinian patients at the hospital, several of
whom said they were injured in the uprising, visited Cassidy and
exchanged words of support. One Arab patient said: ``This place is
not safe ... it is like Beruit.''
   Cassidy said he has been in the country for about three weeks
working on a story about Palestinians living under Israeli
occupation. He said he will check out of the hospital in a few days
and probably will stay in Israel for another two weeks.
</TEXT>
