<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BurnedChurch     10-19 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burned Church,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Hit by Arson Twice, Black Congregation Vows to Hold Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GODFREY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church serving a tiny black congregation
has been set afire twice this year, but its pastor vowed Wednesday,
``We're not gonna let anybody force us out.''
   ``Emotions are running a little too high right now,'' said the
Rev. Steven Jackson after a fire Tuesday left only one wall of the
church standing.
   The blaze came just two weeks before the church was scheduled to
reopen, following repairs of damage from an April 16 fire. Both
fires have been attributed to arson. Police have made no arrests.
   Congregation members in the town 30 miles north of St. Louis
probably will rebuild the church a second time on the same spot,
Jackson said, but a final decision will not be made until early
next week.
   ``Tempers could flare. We just need to cool off a little,''
Jackson said.
   ``We need to clear our minds,'' he said, adding there are
``10,000 rumors'' that the fire was racially motivated.
   Area residents reported the blaze shortly before 3 a.m. Tuesday
and the church was engulfed in flames by the time firefighters
arrived. No injuries were reported.
   An FBI agent at the agency's Alton office, who refused to give
her name, said that the agency had entered the investigation to
determine whether the congregation's civil rights had been violated.
   The neighborhood around the church is predominantly white, but
church members said they were unaware of any organized group that
might be behind the fires.
   Jackson said a pipe bomb destroyed the building in 1974.
   ``If it's racially motivated, then somebody is telling us to get
out, and we're not gonna let anybody force us out,'' he said. ``A
lot of the black people who live in the community are kind of hot.''
   Last year the church was defaced with racial epithets, said Lt.
Dennis Fischer of the Madison County Sheriff's Department.
   Police haven't ruled out racism as a factor in the fires, but
``it could be just a straight act of vandalism,'' Fischer said.
   ``I don't have any idea why they'd want to burn it down,'' said
Wesley Matlock, 71, whose great-grandparents founded The New Bethel
African Methodist Episcopal Church of Rock Fork in 1863.
   ``Just vandalism or meanness, that's all I can say,'' Matlock
said.
   The 25-member congregation had planned to rededicate the church
Nov. 6, Jackson said, adding worshippers had put about $65,000 into
rebuilding it.
   Rebuilding could start by November, Jackson said, noting the
church was insured.
   It was built ``so people could worship God free and clear. We
ought to have a right in 1988 to worship where we please,'' he said.
   ``Why would somebody want to run us out?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
