<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Middle Class Has Shrunk Through Prosperity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Cincinnati appearance and Baker remarks, SUB
three grafs for 7th pvs, Reagan was...; New grafs 7 and 8 EMBARGOED
till 6:20 p.m.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan crisscrossed Ohio on
Wednesday for George Bush, saying prosperity has caused the middle
class to shrink and ``America doesn't want to go'' where the
Democrats want to take the nation.
   Making several appearances in a state that strategists say
Michael Dukakis must carry to have a chance at the White House,
Reagan said the Democrats have greater problems than ``whether
their candidate is likable.''
   Fifteen times in a 15-minute speech prepared for a Republican
rally at Ohio State University, Reagan used what he calls the ``L''
word _ condemning both Dukakis and en. Howard Metzenbaum as
liberals. Metzenbaum, seeking a third term in the Senate, is
opposed by Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich.
   At the Wood County courthouse in Bowling Green, Reagan said the
Republicans would deal harshly with criminals and would continue
the kind of firm foreign policy that led to a U.S.-Soviet treaty
restricting medium-range nuclear weapons.
   ``Make a false move and the next sound you hear is the clang of
a jail cell slamming shut,'' the president said, boasting that his
administration has appointed judges who ``know the meaning of the
word punishment.''
   Praising the vice president, he said, ``George and I also
believe that a crack dealer with a machinegun who murders a police
officer in the line of duty should receive the death penalty.''
   Reagan said that Soviet Leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``did
business because he knew we meant business. And we still mean
business.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Following grafs EMBARGOED for 6:20 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan wound up his day of campaigning with an appearance at a
fund-raising affair for Voinovich in Cincinnati, where he linked
the Cleveland mayor to Bush and said both ``have the same goals
-keeping government off the backs of the American people, keeping
taxes down, and keeping this nation strong and at peace.''
   In his three speeches, Reagan used the word ``liberal'' more
than 50 times. In the original text of his Bowling Green speech,
Reagan was to say that he was opening ``a second front'' designed
to assure election of a Republican Congress ``with the liberal
presidential campaign starting to fall apart.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End EMBARGOED material</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In remarks to reporters aboard Air Force One, campaign chairman
James A. Baker III said ``it is entirely possible there will be''
joint appearances of Bush and Baker.
   In his Columbus speech, Reagan spoke of watching the
presidential candidates' debate.
   ``I don't often feel sorry for liberals, but I came close,'' he
said. ``I couldn't help thinking, the problem with those fellows on
the other side is not camera angles or lighting; it's not whether
their candidate is likable or not.''
   Many analyses of the debate have said that Bush came across as a
more warm, appealing personality than his opponent, the
Massachusetts governor.
   Reagan, however, said the problem the Democrats face is ``that
where they want to take America, America doesn't want to go; that
they're way over there in left field; that they're out of the
mainstream of American politics; and that their policies are
liberal, liberal, liberal.''
   ``You may have heard the liberals talk about a smaller middle
class, and it's true,'' the president said. ``The middle class is
getting proportionately smaller. But not because a greater
proportion of people are poor. That just isn't so. No, because more
people have moved up and become so well off that they're no longer
called middle class.''
   ``Here in Ohio,'' he said, ``we have a Senate race that draws
just the same lines between the liberals and the rest of us as are
drawn in the race for president.''
   The state has 23 electoral votes.
</TEXT>
