<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless     10-19 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Emergency Food, Housing, Health Care Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday approved legislation
authorizing $1.3 billion for emergency food and housing, health
care, education and other help to the nation's homeless people over
the next two years.
   The bill received a big boost when the Republican presidential
candidate, Vice President George Bush, called for full funding of
the measure during the first debate with the Democratic nominee,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who has called for even more
funding for the homeless.
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., a chief sponsor, said, ``This
is a noble start but it is only a start. It won't even address the
temporary needs of the vast majority of the homeless.
   ``There needs to be permanent housing for the homeless,'' he
said. ``The only way to alleviate the needs of the men, women and
children who are homeless is to build permanent housing and this
bills does not do it.
   ``This bill is a Band-Aid,'' Schumer said, ``A needed Band-Aid,
but not a cure.''
   The House approved the measure on a voice vote. The measure
still must win Senate approval before it is sent to the White House.
   The House-passed bill would authorize $633.8 million for fiscal
1989, which began Oct. 1, for which $378 million has been
appropriated. In fiscal 1990, $682.8 million would be authorized.
   Congress authorized $616 million for fiscal 1988, but a lesser
$360.5 million was appropriated.
   Advocates for the country's homeless population _ estimated at
between 250,000 and 3 million people _ have been angry because so
far, the government has not fully financed the legislation.
   The legislation, known as the McKinney bill, would extend for
two years a law passed early last year.
   The measure is named after the late Rep. Stewart B. McKinney,
R-Conn., one of the original sponsors of the bill. McKinney died on
May 7, 1987, less than three months after the legislation became
law.
   The bill would allow the government to provide money to states
and municipalities, and to private agencies, for rental assistance,
health care, mental health services, alcohol and drug abuse
programs, education and job training projects.
   Funds would be available for the purchase and rehabilitation of
group homes. In addition, unused space at Veterans Administration
hospitals would be set aside for the treatment of homeless veterans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
