<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CreditCards     10-19 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Credit Cards,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Sends Reagan Bill on Disclosure of Credit Card Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday approved and sent to
President Reagan a bill requiring issuers of credit and charge
cards to give consumers more and earlier details about the interest
rates and other costs.
   Approval came on a voice voice. The Senate also had passed the
measure by voice vote without discussion last week.
   The legislation requires card issuers, such as banks and
department stores, to disclose their interest rates, fees and grace
periods at the time on applications and solicitations. Supporters
said this will enable consumers to shop around for the least
expensive product.
   Under current law, creditors are not required to disclose the
information until the card is issued.
   Donald G. Oglivie, executive vice president of the American
Bankers Association, said in a statement after the House acted:
``The bill is a victory for both consumers and creditors who will
benefit from balanced disclosure information.''
   More than 100 million people in the United States hold more than
800 million credit cards and have outstanding balances approaching
$150 billion. Solicitations total more than 2.5 billion annually.
   The measure was endorsed by such consumer groups as Consumers
Union, Consumers Federation of America, Bankcard Holders of America
and a coalition of business and industry groups, in addition to the
ABA, Consumer Bankers Association, Coalition of Credit Card
Issuers, National Retail Merchants Association, American Express
Co. and Sears, Roebuck and Co.
   During House debate last Thursday, Rep. Fernand J. St Germain,
D-R.I., Banking Committee chairman, called the measure ``one of the
most important and strongest credit disclosure acts that we have
been able to move through the Congress since the first
truth-in-lending statute was passed 20 years ago.''
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., the measure's chief House
sponsor, said, ``The bill does pre-empt state laws, but that is
immaterial. It is tougher than any state law.''
   Under the legislation, individual states cannot enact laws more
strict than the federal statute.
   However, Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the Banking
Committee's consumer affairs subcommittee, was displeased with the
state pre-emption. He said the measure does not go far enough to
protect consumers.
   ``Let me suggest that what Americans want in their credit cards
is not more disclosure, but lower interest rates on their
charges,'' he said. ``There is nothing in this legislation that
will cause credit interests to fall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0177 </DOCNO>
