<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0709 10-19 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0709,0873</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suicide Car Bomb Kills Seven Israeli Soldiers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with army
announcement, details, Shamir quotes, Hezbollah claim, changes
figures, LaserPhoto numbers. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TLV3,6</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following story was submitted to the Israeli
military censor who ordered a deletion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>METULLA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suicide car bomb exploded Wednesday
near Israel's ``Good Fence'' border crossing in south Lebanon,
killing seven Israeli soldiers and wounding eight others and two
Lebanese civilians, the military command said.
   In Beirut, the Islamic Resistance claimed responsibility. The
same coalition of pro-Iranian fundamentalist groups claimed
responsibility for a car bomb that wounded three Israelis in August.
   The military wing of Hezbollah, the Party of God militia based
in Beirut, also claimed responsibility, according to Middle East
Television, a Christian-run station. Hezbollah belongs to Islamic
Resistance.
   The TV report, monitored in Metulla, said, ``The car bomb tore
apart a minibus full of soldiers.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and other Israeli leaders vowed to
retaliate.
   Maj. Gen. Yossi Peled, head of Israel's northern command, told a
news conference the bomb exploded 300 yards north of the border at
1:25 p.m. (7:25 a.m. EDT) as two groups of army vehicles passed
each other, one headed home and the other into Lebanon.
   Peled said the blast was so powerful ``nothing remained of the
car bomb.''
   An Israeli officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
white Toyota truck, driven by an Arab ``apparently from
Hezbollah,'' exploded amid two convoys totaling seven vehicles.
   ``The commanders got out to talk. The Toyota came in between the
two groups of vehicles and exploded,'' he said.
   The blast left a crater more than 15 feet wide. Witnesses said
they saw pools of blood. Trees were scorched.
   Witnesses said the attack vehicle was unrecognizable.
   Israel created the ``Good Fence'' in 1976 to provide medical and
other aid to refugees from Lebanon's civil war. It is used today
mostly by Lebanese workers who travel to Israel daily.
   Villagers in south Lebanon told reporters the suicide driver
stopped his vehicle and asked an Israeli soldier for a light.
``When he saw Israeli vehicles, he reached inside ... and set off
the bomb,'' one said.
   Some Israeli army officials noted that the driver's body was not
found and said there were indications a remote-control device
triggered the explosion.
   Peled told reporters, ``We must talk to the survivors to
ascertain what happened. What we know is that the car was
apparently not parked, and when the army vehicles arrived, the
vehicle also arrived and exploded.''
   Israel television said six army jeeps and a minibus were
involved. It showed pictures of charred and heavily damaged
vehicles. U.S.-made M-16 assault rifles lay in a heap, surrounded
by vehicle parts.
   Reporters arriving later were barred from entering Lebanon but
saw a soldier guarding a charred truck and jeep.
   The soldier and TV cameramen said the blast knocked down a
section of the electronic fence.
   Israel television quoted army experts as saying the bomb
contained up to 330 pounds of explosives and apparently was readied
in a south Lebanese village.
   The blast was heard four miles away and broke windows in the
small border town of Metulla.
   Scott MacDonald, an employe of the Christian-run Voice of Hope
radio station, said ``I felt the explosion as I was walking in the
house and a saw a blast of wind. The explosion was at least a mile
away so it was pretty powerful.''
   Tour groups visit the ``Good Fence'' site regularly, and
witnesses said Australian youths were at the fence shortly before
the blast. None was harmed.
   TV film showed medical teams performing emergency surgery in the
field and victims with arms and legs blown off.
   ``The soldiers who were slightly wounded began to rescue their
comrades. It was amazing, they did it under fire as ammunition and
grenades were exploding around,'' a civilian security officer from
Metulla said on Israel radio.
   Wounded soldiers were flown by helicopter to Israeli hospitals.
The army said one was in critical condition. Peled said two
Lebanese women were hurt.
   Shamir vowed that ``Israel's just and secure hand will reach the
killers,'' the television reported.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said: ``Those sending suicide
drivers in car bombs should know they will pay the bill till the
end.''
   Rabin and Peled said the incident proved nevertheless the value
of Israel's self-declared security zone, a buffer strip six to 10
miles deep in south Lebanon.
   ``That it happened so close to the border proves the importance
of the security zone,'' Peled said.
   The last major car bomb attack occurred yards from Metulla's
border fence on March 10, 1985, shortly before most Israeli troops
were withdrawn after three years of occupation. That attack,
claimed by the pro-Syrian Lebanese Syrian Socialist Nationalist
Party, killed 12 Israeli soldiers and wounded 14.
   Hezbollah has been demanding stepped up action to force Israel
to withdraw its remaining troops from south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
