<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Teamsters-Bush-Quayle     10-19 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Bush-Quayle,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Union Says Endorsement Includes Bush and Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters on
Wednesday clarified that it is endorsing Republican Sen. Dan Quayle
of Indiana for vice president along with its endorsement of George
Bush for president.
   ``We support Bush and Quayle like ham and eggs,'' said Teamster
President William J. McCarthy.
   McCarthy had announced Monday that the union was endorsing the
Republican ticket on the basis of a poll answered by 21,207 union
members showing they favored Bush over Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis 50.2 percent to 46.4 percent.
   In a news conference held during a meeting of the union's
18-member executive board at Grenelefe, Fla., he said that he
personally also favored Bush.
   But when pressed by reporters on whether he also favored Quayle
over Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen, McCarthy
responded, ``Look, I'm not going to talk about Quayle or
(President) Reagan or anybody else,'' according to Teamster
officials.
   That remark had been widely misinterpreted as an endorsement of
Bush but not Quayle.
   Tim O'Neill, a spokesman for the union, said a questionnaire on
presidential preferences sent to 1.6 million Teamster members last
month had boxes for checkmarks listing only Bush and Quayle
together and Dukakis and Bentsen together.
   The Teamsters had endorsed Reagan and Bush in both the 1980 and
1984 elections.
   But officials in the union had not expected a Teamster
Republican presidential endorsement this year because of the 1986
indictment of then-Teamsters President Jackie Presser and a Justice
Department suit in June seeking to place the union under a
court-appointed trustee.
   ``I was just as surprised as anybody,'' one top Teamster
official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said Wednesday.
``Before Monday's meeting, there was no indication that any board
members would vote that way.''
   Not all of them did, according to other sources close to the
union.
   One, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said the vote by
the 18-member executive board on endorsing Bush and Quayle was 11-7.
   At least five Teamster board members had actively worked on
behalf of Dukakis.
   Secretary-Treasurer Weldon Mathis, before he was upset by
McCarthy in a bid for the Teamsters' presidency upon Presser's
death last July, had spoken in favor of Dukakis on several
occasions.
   However, McCarthy, the Teamsters' top official in Boston for 20
years before taking over from Presser, had made no secret of a
dislike he had developed for Dukakis during his 10 years as
Massachusetts' governor.
   Teamster vice presidents and board members Daniel Ligurotis and
Donald Peters, both of Chicago, Don West of Birmingham, Ala., and
Michael Riley of Los Angeles had also supported Dukakis.
   Meanwhile, Federal Election Commission records show that the
Teamsters have given Bentsen $9,000 in campaign funds this year in
his simultaneous race for re-election to the Senate from Texas.
   But the union also gave Quayle $5,000 in campaign funds two
years ago when he was seeking re-election to the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
