<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JewishGroups     10-19 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jewish Groups,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics of Pro-Israel Lobby Deny They Plan Independent Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of three major Jewish
organizations, seeking to heal a public rift, pledged their support
Wednesday to the most prominent pro-Israel lobbying group and said
they were not planning a rival operation.
   The American Jewish Committee, the American Jewish Congress and
the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith had complained earlier
that the American Israel Public Affairs Committee (AIPAC) had taken
positions that were not in accord with ``the consensus of the
organized Jewish community.''
   The complaint, in a letter that appeared initially in a story in
The New York Times, said the three organizations had established
``a joint political committee'' for Israel in Washington.
   However, the joint statement Wednesday said ``the implication''
in the story that they ``are contemplating the establishment of a
lobbying operation in Washington that would operate independently
of AIPAC is entirely incorrect.''
   The statement was signed by Ira Silverman, executive vice
president of the American Jewish Committee; Harry Siegman,
executive director of the American Jewish Congress; and Abraham H.
Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League.
   ``Our three organizations, each of which has had offices in
Washington for many years, are founding members of AIPAC, have been
fully supportive of its work and will continue to support it,'' the
letter said.
   ``The new procedures we have established in Washington are
intended to improve coordination between our agencies and AIPAC in
developing policy'' that ``will be consistent with the consensus''
of American Jewish groups, it said.
   ``The purpose of this improved coordination is to enhance
AIPAC's effectiveness, not provide any alternative to it,'' the
letter said. ``We expect AIPAC to participate fully in that
coordinating process.''
   Foxman, in an Associated Press interview Tuesday, described as
``hogwash'' the idea that the hard-line stance of AIPAC was the
issue.
   ``We're united how we feel about the PLO,'' Foxman said.
   But the Jewish leader said AIPAC was mistaken to try to force
the closing of the Palestine Liberation Organization's U.N. office
in New York.
   And, Foxman said, while there was widespread opposition to a
U.S. missile sale to Kuwait, it was poor strategy for AIPAC to try
to persuade Congress to block the purchase.
   Meanwhile, Seymour Reich, the president of B'nai B'rith, who did
not sign the letter, expressed ``deep concern over the public
expression of disunity in the Jewish community with regard to
Washington-based lobbying activity.''
   He said disagreements among the organizations ``is best solved
by individuals _ not through a public airing in the media.''
   Reich criticized the Jewish leaders who called in the letter for
establishment of ``a joint political committee'' for Israel in
Washington.
   ``Efforts to create a competing lobbying bloc gives the mistaken
impression that the community has no consensus on peace in the
Middle East,'' he said.
   A senior official of AIPAC told The Associated Press in a
separate interview Tuesday that ``this whole episode is bound to
confuse members of Congress.''
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity from Los
Angeles, where the group held a board meeting, said ``more
consultation is always desirable'' among Jewish groups.
   He said AIPAC leaders would meet in Washington with the critics
on Nov. 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
