<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RollsFlap     10-19 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rolls Flap,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Declares Rolls-Royce a Public Nuisance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Beverly Hills succeeded Wednesday
in having a $200,000 Rolls-Royce auto declared a public nuisance
and barring its owner from parking it in the same Rodeo Drive spot
for more than an hour at a time.
   Five attorneys representing the city convinced Superior Court
Judge Edward Kakita to issue a preliminary injunction against art
gallery owner David Spellerberg and his 1954 Rolls.
   ``This is the first time a Rolls-Royce has been declared a
public nuisance,'' Spellerberg said after the 15-minute hearing.
``Only in Beverly Hills would this happen.''
   Spellerberg has parked the dark blue, chauffeur-driven car in
the one-hour spot in front of his National Heritage Gallery of Fine
Art for the past seven months. His driver stands by, pumping $15 in
quarters into the meter each day.
   ``I just wanted to put glitter and glamour back on the street.
We sure aren't getting that with a Pinto. But the city of Beverly
Hills could care less,'' said Spellerberg. ``Rodeo Drive just isn't
what it used to be.
   ``We're paying $20,000 a month in rent and I can't even park my
own car in front of my own gallery.''
   Spellerberg said he bought the Rolls after noticing that
tourists walking down Rodeo Drive, famous for its posh shops and
celebrity clientele, were frequently heard asking, ``Is that all
there is?''
   Since parking the car in front of the gallery, he said an
estimated 20,000 tourists have posed for snapshots in front of it.
He blames the city's action on jealous business owners nearby.
   The ruling which imposed the one-hour parking limit also compels
Spellerberg to move the car no less than 500 feet. In addition,
Spellergerg cannot block or use the sidewalk for commercial
advertisements or promotions.
   Spellerberg said he isn't giving up his fight, but he won't
disclose his next move.
   ``The city hasn't had any sense of humor in this,'' he said.
``They had five attorneys in there this morning. I want to know
what the taxpayers have to say about that.''
</TEXT>
