<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy-Clothes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0814,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Ducks Question About Wardrobe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 17th graf pvs, bgng: ``I won't ...'' to
UPDATE with additional Reagan comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan ducked questions on Wednesday
about her borrowed, high-fashion wardrobe, as her spokeswoman
refused to rule out the possibility that she might receive more
free fashions.
   Mrs. Reagan, appearing at a riding center for the handicapped,
refused to speak with reporters attempting to question her about
the latest flap over designer gowns lent her by leading fashion
houses.
   President Reagan denounced the reports, which first appeared in
Time Magazine over the weekend.
   ``I don't have anything to say about that ridiculous story,''
Reagan told reporters as he left the White House for a day of
campaigning in Ohio.
   Mrs. Reagan, queried as she left the National Center for
Therapeutic Riding, only smiled slightly and continued walking as
reporters asked to speak with her.
   White House counsel Fred Fielding informed the Office of
Government Ethics in 1982 that even though the Ethics in Government
Act of 1978 did not require Mrs. Reagan to report the borrowed
material, she would include the information on financial disclosure
forms.
   At that time, Mrs. Reagan also pledged to quit using borrowed
items.
   However, over the weekend, Time Magazine reported that several
fashion designers said they'd continued to lend Mrs. Reagan
expensive clothes since 1982. And neither the first lady nor the
president has since reported the items as gifts or loans on their
financial disclosure and tax forms.
   One Los Angeles designer, David Hayes, was quoted by Time as
saying he'd made some 60 to 80 made-to-order outfits available to
the first lady over the years. She returned more than half and kept
the others, he said.
   A spokeswoman for Hayes, who refused to identify herself, said
he was ``in conference'' on Wednesday and unable to take a phone
call.
   Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman disputed Hayes' account, contending
his number was ``extraordinarily high.''
   ``I haven't seen her wear a David Hayes in five years,'' said
Elaine Crispen.
   Mrs. Crispen also took issue with Hayes' assertion that she
hasn't returned some of the dresses made especially for her. ``All
the items that were borrowed have been returned,'' said Mrs.
Crispen.
   The spokeswoman said she did not know what led the first lady to
break the promise she made in 1982.
   ``I just don't know. She made her own rule ... she broke her own
rule. Perhaps because she was told it wasn't against the law. I
just don't know what her personal thinking was,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   The spokeswoman said she couldn't rule out a continuance of the
practice, however.
   ``I won't rule out that possibility _ that sometime, something
in the future might be borrowed,'' she added.
   Reagan, at the outset of his third and final speech on a
three-city Ohio campaign swing, came to his wife's defense.
   Speaking of the separations and absences caused by political
life, the president said that while he'd like to stay longer, ``I
want to get home to see Nancy.''
   Reagan went on to praise the first lady's ``Just Say No''
anti-drug abuse campaign, and added: ``The government's got quite
an employee there, with no salary.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday ``there is
no legal problem, there is no ethical problem'' for failing to
report the items.
   ``There is no consequence,'' Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater based his statements on statements made earlier in the
week by Donald Campbell, the No. 2 man at the Office of Government
Ethics, who said his agency sees no need at this time to reassess
the 1982 opinion on the matter.
</TEXT>
