<HEAD>President Gives Wife Good-Natured Praise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nancy-Clothes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan, in hot water again
over borrowed finery, got a good-natured pat on the back Wednesday
from her traveling husband.
   President Reagan, in Cincinnati to make a Republican
fund-raising speech, opened up by saying, ``You know some people
say that politics makes strange bedfellows. I'm going to let you in
on a little secret. Sometimes, politics doesn't make bedfellows at
all.''
   ``And sometimes it separates people that have been bedfellows
for a while.''
   ``Frankly, I have to say I'm a little anxious to get back to
Nancy myself,'' he said.
   ``The government's got quite an employee there in the first
lady, for no salary,'' Reagan added.
   ``I thought I'd like to tell you I'm very proud of her,'' the
president said, going on to speak of Mrs. Reagan's campaign against
drug abuse.
   He made no reference to the controversy over Mrs. Reagan's
admission that she has continued to accept loaned dresses from
designers although she had announced in 1982, after a similar
controversy arose, that she would not.
