<HEAD>Dukakis Accuses GOP Of Spreading `Garbage'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 8th pvs, Dukakis toughened..., with
aides' refutation of charges in brochures.
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis accused Republicans on
Wednesday of resorting to ``garbage'' and distortions in the race
for the White House, citing a Republican brochure that says a
convicted Illinois mass-murderer would be ``eligible for weekend
passes'' in Massachusetts.
   ``Friends, this is garbage,'' Dukakis said, holding aloft a GOP
mailing to Illinois voters that deals with a controversial
Massachusetts furlough program. ``This is political garbage.''
   Dukakis, facing widespread advice from Democrats to respond more
aggressively to Bush, decided to do so on a crisp autumn day of
campaigning in rural Illinois and Missouri in which he also accused
Republicans of lack of concern for rural issues.
   But his main text for the day was fighting back.
   ``This isn't worthy of a presidential campaign,''he said of the
brochure, which said Illinois mass murderer John Wayne Gacy would
``be eligible for weekend passes'' in the Massachusetts program.
   ``They shouldn't lower the level of a political debate,'' he
said of the Republicans, who have used the program to suggest that
Dukakis is soft on crime. ``They should inform the voters and not
mislead and frighten them.''
   Gacy was convicted and sentenced to death in 1980 for murdering
33 young men and boys, 29 of whose bodies were found in his home in
the Chicago suburb of Des Plaines.
   Dukakis also held up a second brochure sponsored by the Illinois
Republican Party that said, ``All the Murderers and Rapists and
Drug Pushers and Child Molesters in Massachusetts Vote for Michael
Dukakis.''
   Dukakis toughened his rhetoric during the day, telling a crowd
at a farm in Palmyra, Mo., ``I've never seen such a pack of lies in
my life.''
   Aides traveling wuith Dukakis specifically denied that Gacy
would be eligible for weekend passes under the Massachusetts
furlough program. They also disputed the allegation in one of the
pamphlets that Dukakis said he would commute every death penalty
given to murderers in the event that the people of Massachusetts
voted to reinstate in the death sentence.
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis told reporters: ``My positions are
being distorted on a number of these issues. That seems to be what
the Bush campaign is all about.''
   He declined to say precisely what he had in mind for the three
weeks remaining to Election Day.
   ``We're going to get the truth out to the American people,''
Dukakis told reporters after a call-in program beamed by satellite
from a pig farm, the first stop of his rural America bus tour.
   The Massachusetts governor wore a suede jacket over a checked
shirt and khaki pants for his day in the country. At his first
stop, Jim and Mabel Reed's 900-acre spread along Illinois Highway
57, the backdrop included farm tractors, pig pens and silos.
Dukakis sat on a bale of hay while he delivered his populist
rhetoric in terms specially scripted for farmers.
   ``I don't remember any time in this campaign he's expressed any
concern about family farmers,'' Dukakis said of Bush. He said
Republicans ``like corporate operators.''
   From there, the bus ride through rolling, rich farmland led to
Quincy, and an outdoor, flag-draped rally downtown.
   ``George Bush cares about the people who hold mortgages on
family farms. I care about people who pay them,'' he said.
   Near the end of his speech, he held up the GOP mailing and said
they ``shouldn't lower the level of a political debate.''
   The mailing says Dukakis ``supported a program in his home state
that let murderers, rapists and child molesters free on weekend
passes.'' It recounts the story of an escaped furloughed prisoner
who brutalized a Maryland couple and says if Illinois mass murderer
John Gacy had committed his crimes in Boston, he would be
``eligible for weekend passes'' under Dukakis program.
   Dukakis said he had accepted responsibility for the
Massachusetts incident, and noted that President Reagan had
accepted responsibility for similar incidents in a federal program.
   That program, he noted, ``is furloughing murderers and its
furloughing pushers and drug peddlers, the people he (Bush) now
tells us he wants to execute.''
   Dukakis declined to tell reporters whether he would purchase
time in 30-minute blocks on network television to carry his case
directly to the voters, and aides declined to discuss any
television commercials that might be in production.
   Dukakis acknowleges he is behind in the race for the White
House, although his aides say the race is far closer than the
17-point margin found in an NBC-Wall Street Journal survey
completed over the weekend. In the manner of all lagging
candidates, Dukakis insists at every stop that the victory can
still be won.
   Even so, with only three weeks left in the campaign and the
presidential debates behind him, Dukakis and aides have been
struggling to find a way to turn the tide in their favor.
</TEXT>
