<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0766 10-19 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Politburo Members Resign, Another Loses Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with quotes,
outcome of meeting, other. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Politburo members resigned
Wednesday rather than face a confidence vote in the Communist
Party's Central Committee, which ended its three-day meeting
without a crisis solution in sight.
   Another member, Dusan Ckrebic from the Serbian republic, offered
to quit after losing a confidence vote, the first time that has
happened since the Communists took power in 1945.
   The nation is torn by ethnic, political and economic problems,
but Stipe Suvar, the Communist Party chief, declared, ``Yugoslavia
will not fall apart.'' He told a news conference there was
``virtual consensus (among the leaders) for profound changes'' and
insisted the meeting had made ``a step forward'' in solving its
woes.
   The Central Committee accepted a proposal from Suvar to replace
one-third of its 165 members over the next six weeks. If this goes
ahead, it would be the single biggest sweep through the ruling
elite since 1948, when Stalinists were purged after Josip Broz Tito
broke with Moscow.
   But Yugoslav leaders remained deeply divided, and popular
criticism of the hierarchy seemed unlikely to abate.
   Ckrebic's defeat in the confidence vote was seen as a blow to
Serbian Communist Party leader Slobodan Milosevic, whose insistence
on more Serbian control over the autonomous provinces of Vojvodina
and Kosovo has deepened Yugoslavia's political and ethnic rifts.
   Crkebic, an oldtime Communist in his 60s, was seen as a
Milosevic ally.
   Ten of the 23 members of the Presidium, or Politburo, were up
for the vote and had been expected to resign. Nine obtained more
than the simple majority of 83 required from the full Central
Committee membership of 165, but Ckrebic mustered only 68 votes.
   The resignations of another four members _ Kolj Siroka, Bosko
Krunic, Milanko Renovica and Franc Setinc _ were unanimously
accepted by the Central Committee. Nine, including Milosevic, were
exempt because they hold seats as party chiefs of Yugoslavia's six
republics, two provinces and the armed forces.
   ``Please accept immediately my resignation,'' Ckrebic said after
losing the confidence vote in a secret ballot.
   Milosevic demanded that Ckrebic's offer not be considered
immediately and Suvar later told reporters the resignation will be
discussed at a regular meeting of the Presidium in 10 days.
   The confidence vote followed heavy public criticism that the
Communist chiefs failed to provide strong leadership, calm ethnic
tension and ease Yugoslavia's worst economic crisis since World War
II. Inflation is more than 200 percent, unemployment is 15 percent
and the foreign debt is $21 billion.
   The economic problems have led to increasing strikes and worker
unrest, adding to the ethnic tensions in a country of more than 20
ethnic groups.
   Wednesday's events may well increase ethnic divisions because
the Serbs, Yugoslavia's largest ethnic group, were likely to be
unhappy with the outcome.
   Serbs have been rallying by the hundreds of thousands to push
for more control over Kosovo, an ancient Serbian heartland
bordering Albania and now dominated by ethnic Albanians.
   Some of Kosovo's 200,000 Serbs called a rally Thursday in
Pristina, their capital.
   The four resigned Politburo members gave different reasons for
their actions. But all had come under fire in the state-run media
and at public rallies.
   The state-run Tanjug news agency said Suvar received 126 votes.
   Suvar, in proposing the Central Committee changes, said an
extensive list of candidates would be prepared in the next month
and then voting would start.
   In another implicit defeat for Milosevic, the Central Committee
agreed Wednesday only to set up a working committee to review
Serbian calls for the ouster from the Central Committee of three
Kosovo leaders _ two ethnic Albanians and one Serb.
   In a move that seemed designed to quell potential further
unrest, authorities indefinitely postponed a mass rally in Belgrade
called for Saturday.
   Up to 1 million Serbs had been expected to attend the rally to
express their solidarity with their Slav brothers in Kosovo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
