<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugBill     10-19 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bill,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House, Senate Negotiators Seek Compromise Drug Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators met Wednesday
night to fashion compromise anti-drug legislation, the major bill
that is keeping the 100th Congress in session.
   Members of the House and Senate judiciary committees, and other
lawmakers interested in law enforcement issues, met to resolve
differences in the anti-crime provisions of the bill.
   A separate group of lawmakers representing the House and Senate
leadership tried to resolve other issues, including provisions on
drug prevention, education, treatment, testing, loss of federal
benefits, obscenity and pornography.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said the working
groups have ``made progress,'' adding he hoped that compromise
language would be available by Thursday afternoon. If that
timetable is met, a vote would be expected Friday, when the
agreement could be written in the form of a bill.
   Many senators already have fled Washington to campaign, since
there were no roll calls Wednesday and none scheduled for Thursday.
   Both Byrd and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said it
will be difficult to get senators to return, and told reporters the
drug bill could be approved by voice vote.
   ``There's a determination by the joint leadership to get the
drug bill and get it done by Friday,'' Dole said.
   House members, off since last week, returned to Washington on
Wednesday for a full day of work, and they were expected to remain
in town for the drug legislation.
   The two houses have passed bills with different language on a
number of key issues.
   They include: the death penalty for those who kill during drug
crimes; civil penalties of up to $10,000 for possession of
marijuana, cocaine and other drugs; increased penalties for train
and bus operators found to operate their vehicles under the
influence of alcohol or drugs.
   Also, distribution of anabolic steroids without a prescription;
denial of some federal benefits for those convicted of drug crimes;
drug testing of transportation workers; standards for drug testing
laboratories; money laundering; plastic guns; law enforcement
funding; education and prevention programs; foreign aid to
drug-fighting countries; and creation of a Cabinet-level ``drug
czar'' to coordinate drug policy.
   The Senate bill includes anti-obscenity and anti-pornography
language not in the House measure.
   Only the House bill includes a grant program for states willing
to establish enforcement programs that require suspension or
revocation of drivers' licenses for drug convictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HugeDiamond     10-19 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Huge Diamond,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egg-Size Diamond Is Too Rich for Auction Bidders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flawless diamond the size of an egg proved too
much of a good thing Wednesday, when its owners rejected a record
$12 million bid as too low and pulled it off the auction block.
   It was the second time in two days that a precious stone
expected to bring a record price was removed from auction without a
sale.
   The polished diamond, which weighs 407.8 carats _ the world's
second largest _ was offered by Christie's on behalf of two New
York jewelry dealers and the Zale Corp., a Dallas-based chain of
jewelry stores.
   Although the $12 million bid was the highest ever made at a gem
auction, officials said, it was deemed too low and rejected.
   ``This was an experiment,'' said Francois Curiel, head of
Christie's jewelry department.
   The bidding took place as a Christie's employee dressed in black
appeared from behind a revolving wall holding up the diamond amid
gasps from the audience.
   On Tuesday, the rival auction house Sotheby's was forced to
remove from auction the royal red Mandalay Ruby, which was supposed
to sell for $15 million. The high bid of $7.6 million was rejected
by the gem's owner.
   Christie's would not estimate how much its diamond would bring,
although Curiel noted that on April 19, an 85.91-carat white
diamond was auctioned for $9.31 million _ a record for any gem.
   ``I'm certain this jewel will set a record price for a single
precious stone,'' he said before the bidding.
   Several other lots at the Christie's sale also were withdrawn
because they failed to reach the minimum bid. Those that were sold
included a 59-carat, unmounted pear-shaped diamond for $5.55
million, a diamond necklace for $1.3 million and a 23.95-carat
diamond ring for $1.2 million.
   The prices do not include a 10 percent buyer's premium.
   Christie's said the sale total was $26.8 million, including the
10 percent buyer's premium. Out of 402 lots, 314 sold, it said.
   Other items sold included a necklace and bracelet of emerald
beads once collected by the Shah Jehan, builder of the Taj Majal,
which fetched $370,000; and a diamond-fringed necklace from the
collection of prima ballerina Dame Margot Fonteyn for $55,000.
   Christie's diamond was described as the largest ever offered at
a public auction. It is second in size only to the 530.20-carat
Cullinan I, set in Britain's Imperial Sceptre as part of the Crown
Jewels.
   The diamond was purchased as an uncut 890-carat stone in August
1984 and took three years to cut and finish.
   Christie's said the gem was unusual both for its rich golden
color and shield shape and was the largest colored or fancy diamond
known. The gem measures more than 2 inches high, 1.38 inches wide
and 1.10 inches deep. It weighs about 3 ounces.
   Sotheby's auctioned another diamond Tuesday _ the Star of Sierra
Leone Diamond No. 2 _ for $3.52 million. It is one of 11 stones cut
from a 969-carat diamond discovered in the west African nation in
1972.
</TEXT>
