<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0702 10-19 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Killed, Shot as General Strike Closes Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with two dead in car crash, four
more Palestinians wounded. Edits to TRIM. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinians were
reported killed and 10 wounded Wednesday as a general strike to
protest Jewish settlements shut the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Despite the strike, a bus caravan of Israelis toured Gaza to
demand Israel keep the seaside strip.
   Shops and public transit were shut down and roads were blocked
with stones and burning tires in response to a strike call by
underground leaders who are backed by the Palestine Liberation
Organization. Outlawed Palestinian flags flew from utility poles
and mosques.
   Israeli cars were stoned outside West Bank refugee camps near
the Biblical city of Bethlehem and in Ramallah, north of Jerusalem.
No injuries were reported.
   Near the West Bank village of Beit Ummar, an Israeli police car
crashed into an Arab vehicle, killing two Palestinians and injuring
one, Israel radio said.
   It said the incident was caused by oil spread by Palestinian
activists to force vehicles off the road during the strike. The
army command had no comment.
   In the West Bank village of Jenin, a 24-year-old man was shot in
the stomach and a 50-year-old man wounded in the neck when troops
opened fire on stone-throwers, officials at Al-Ittihad hospital
said. They said both victims were in critical condition.
   Two teen-agers and a 10-year-old boy also were shot in the West
Bank when protesters threw rocks at soldiers in the village of
Bartaa, near Jenin, and in Palestinian refugee camps at Tulkarem
and Askar, said the hospital officials, who insisted on anonymity.
   In Gaza City, troops fired during a stone-throwing protest,
seriously wounding a 16-year-old, officials at the city's Ahli Arab
Hospital said.
   In Gaza Strip's town of Rafah, four Palestinians, including a
70-year-old woman, sustained wounds on their limbs from plastic
bullets, hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed five people wounded in the West Bank, but a
spokesman said reports of injuries in Gaza still were being checked.
   The caravan of 50 Israeli buses took a back road to skirt the
main street through Gaza City as it headed for Jewish settlements
where about 2,000 Jews live amid the strip's 650,000 Arabs.
   Dozens of soldiers stood guard in jeeps and on rooftops when the
buses, sponsored by the right-wing Likud bloc that opposes
returning any Arab land, stopped on the southern edge of Gaza City.
   The area was one of 11 neighborhoods, villages or Palestinian
refugee camps, altogether housing about 215,000 people, that was
put under curfew by the army for the strike and visit by the Likud
backers.
   Such curfews require residents to stay indoors, but Palestinians
peered from alleys at the Israelis, many wearing the blue and white
caps and T-shirts of the Likud. Some buses bore pictures of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, Likud's leader.
   An elderly woman got off one bus, did a mock Arab dance and
shouted, ``Let's drive them crazy!''
   Another Likud supporter said rocks were thrown at his bus, but
soldiers said they could not confirm that report.
   At a rally of about 3,000 people at the settlement of Gush
Katif, Likud candidate and Cabinet minister Moshe Katzoff denounced
the rival Labor Party's plan to give up parts of the West Bank and
Gaza in exchange for peace.
   ``They tell us if we give up Gaza, we prevent wars,'' he said.
``We tell them to prevent wars we have to stay in Gaza and Gush
Katif.''
   On Friday, the Israeli daily Hadashot reported that Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres, leader of the Labor Party challenging Likud
in Nov. 1 parliamentary elections, was opening contacts with
Jordan's King Hussein in hopes of a peace settlement.
   Peres has said if elected prime minister, he would hold
elections in the territories to chose Palestinian delegates to join
Jordanians in peace talks. Shamir called that an election gimmick.
   Also Wednesday, two Israeli parliament members from the
left-wing Progressive List for Peace announced they met with a PLO
delegation in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in violation of Israeli law.
   The legislators, Matityahu Peled and Muhammed Miari, called for
a Palestinian state beside Israel and said a similar statement,
also recognizing Israel's sovereignty, was being made by the PLO in
Belgrade. Their joint Arab-Jewish party supports contact with the
PLO and a Palestinian state.
   Wednesday's strike was the lastest of dozens in the 10-month-old
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza,
which were captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   In a leaflet issued last week, the underground leadership urged
the strike against Jewish settlers, saying in 65,000 settlers
living in occupied land ignited violence among the 1.5 million Arab
residents.
   At least 303 Palestinians and six Israelis have died in the
``intefadeh,'' the Arabic word for uprising by which the revolt has
become known.
</TEXT>
