<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Brazil     10-19 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Brazil,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Denies Crackdown on Brazilian Bishops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican denied on Wednesday that it was
cracking down on Brazilian bishops for being too progressive.
   Italian news agencies quoted the Brazilian newspaper Folha de
Sao Paolo as reporting that in the past month the Vatican's
Congregation for Bishops had sent letters of warning to several
Brazilian bishops considered too liberal.
   The paper reportedly said the Vatican had gone on the offensive
against the bishops for straying from Roman Catholic teaching,
especially regarding control of seminaries and Catholic
universities.
   Asked about the report, the Vatican deputy spokesman, the Rev.
Giovanni d'Ercole, told reporters, ``There is no basis for such an
assertion: it is completely false.''
   A month ago, the Vatican cautioned liberal Bishop Petro
Casaldaliga of Sao Felix do Araguaia to remain faithful to the
teachings of the church.
   The Brazilian bishop is an exponent of liberation theology,
which sometimes uses Marxist analysis, and has publicly supported
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government and leftist opposition
forces in Honduras, Guatemala and El Salvador.
   ``The bishop was reminded of some of his duties'' during a
recent trip to Rome, d`Ercole said on Sept. 24. ``In particular,
this bishop has been asked to always be fully faithful to the
teachings of the church and not to interfere in the affairs of
other (Roman Catholic) churches by going to dioceses in other
countries without the consent of local bishops.''
   The newspaper reportedly said a new crackdown began after the
warning to Casaldaliga. Cardinal Aloisio Lorscheider, archbishop of
Fortaleza, Brazil, was among those reportedly receiving the letters.
</TEXT>
