<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     10-19 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Mark Anniversary With Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels marked their
army's eighth anniversary Wednesday with coordinated attacks on
army-defended coffee plantations and a prison in eastern Usulutan
province.
   Two soldiers were killed and eight wounded in the attacks, said
military authorities in the capital and those contacted by
telephone in Santiago de Maria, the scene of fighting 70 miles east
of San Salvador.
   The fighting began hours after two car bomb explosions wounded
six civilians in an affluent district of San Salvador. The rebels
were presumed to be behind the bombings.
   Military officers said the attacks on Santiago de Maria's
outskirts began minutes before Tuesday midnight and lasted until
approximately 3 a.m. Wednesday. The town has about 20,000 people.
   The main targets were three plantations surrounding the town;
their processing plants; the local prison, and an electricity
transmission plant.
   Prudencio Llach, owner of one of the plantations attacked, is
the father-in-law of Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Vides and also
father-in-law of rightist presidential candidate Alfredo Cristiani.
   About 50 common criminals were reported freed in the prison
attack. Military officials said the electric plant was slightly
damaged. The guerrillas said it was destroyed.
   The rebels formed a unified command, the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, in October 1980. They celebrate its
anniversary thoughout October.
   Sabotage is a key element in the guerrilla war against the
U.S.-backed forces. Coffee, cotton and sugar plantations are common
targets because they bring in most of El Salvador's foreign
exchange.
   The rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos (We Will Win) said the
attacks were part of an operation called ``With the people we
advance toward victory on the eighth anniversary of the FMLN.''
   Neither military officials nor Radio Venceremos mentioned rebel
casualties.
   Military officers estimate there are between 6,000 and 7,000
full-time guerrillas and perhaps twice as many men and women who
serve part-time in the militia. There are 55,000 men in the armed
forces.
   Rebel radio also said air force planes and helicopters attacked
Torola, in eastern Morazan province, with bombs, rockets and
machine guns on Monday. It said a rocket hit the town's church
while ``numerous'' people were inside, and three townspeople were
``gravely wounded.''
   Calls to the air force brought only the response that no officer
was available to comment on the allegation.
</TEXT>
