<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sheets     10-19 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sheets,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Husband of Bombing Victim Charged With 34 Counts of Fraud,
Embezzlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J. Gary Sheets, whose wife and former
business partner were killed by confessed bomber Mark Hofmann, was
charged Wednesday with 34 counts of fraud and embezzlement
involving $1.8 million.
   The charges announced by U.S. Attorney Brent Ward concern three
businesses in which Sheets allegedly misrepresented financial
resources, diverted pension funds and promised returns to investors
that he knew were impossible.
   Investors included members of the Osmond entertainment family.
   ``Basically, Mr. Sheets is charged with failing to tell people
what he was going to do with their money, doing something other
than what he said he would do and embezzling money from pension
plans,'' Ward said.
   ``We will have to prove that he had knowledge that what he was
doing was making false representations,'' he added.
   Ward said Sheets, who lives in San Diego, would appear for
arraignment in the next two weeks. A summons and copy of the
indictment was issued to Sheets' Salt Lake City attorney, Peter
Stirba, he said.
   Stirba said the charges were ``merely allegations'' and that his
client must be presumed innocent.
   ``The only comment I can give you is that we are going to do all
our talking in court, where it should be,'' Stirba said. He
declined to provide a telephone number for Sheets and there was
none listed.
   Sheets, 54, is charged with 10 counts of mail fraud, six counts
of securities fraud, 13 counts of interstate transportation of
money taken by fraud and five counts of embezzlement from pension
plans. The allegations cover the years 1984 and 1985.
   Each transportation count carries a maximum possible sentence of
10 years in prison. The other counts each carry a maximum penalty
of five years in prison.
   The allegations involve Sheets' Working Funds I and II, through
which limited partnerships were sold, and through Arrowhead Village
General Partnership.
   The indictment said Working Funds I and II were created in 1984
to generate capital that would be loaned to Sheets' financially
ailing J. Gary Sheets & Associates, a subsidiary of CFS Financial
Corp.
   Sheets did not disclose the financial condition of CFS and JGSA
to the 75 investors in the two securities, the indictment said, and
in some cases failed to show investors a prospectus. It also
alleged Sheets promised a 17 percent return, while knowing it was
not possible, and later failed to tell investors how their money
had been spent.
   Ward said some of the funds were diverted to Sheets' personal
use, and others were used to prop up other failing Sheets
enterprises, although he declined to be more specific.
   Six of the Working Fund counts involve alleged losses suffered
by members of the Osmond family. Sheets is charged with one count
of securities fraud and one count of pension fund embezzlement
against Marie Osmond.
   It alleged $30,000 was embezzled from Marie Inc., Profit Sharing
Plan, an employee benefit plan of which Mrs. Osmond was a trustee.
The indictment did not list an amount regarding the securities
fraud count.
   Sheets, CFS chairman, filed for personal bankruptcy in January
1986, 3{ months after his wife, Kathleen Sheets, and former CFS
vice president Steve Christensen were killed in the second of two
booby-trap bombings Oct. 15, 1985.
   Hofmann, 33, confessed to the bombings and is serving a life
sentence in Utah State Prison. He said he set the bombs to avoid
detection as a master forger and trafficker in bogus early Mormon
documents that had netted him hundreds of thousands of dollars.
   Sheets remarried in July 1987 and at the time was working as an
insurance agent and writing a book about overcoming grief and
tragedy.
</TEXT>
