<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OfficersShot     10-19 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Officers Shot,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York City Police Ordered to Wear Vests After Two Cop Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers were ordered to wear bulletproof
vests on city streets Wednesday after two officers, who didn't have
on vests, were shot to death in separate incidents.
   The order, issued by Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward just
hours after the Tuesday night shootings, said the two officers
``might have survived if they were wearing their vests.''
   Officers are issued bullet-proof vests during their training at
the Police Academy, but were not previously required to wear them
on the job. The officers' union immediately agreed to the order.
   The order covers uniformed officers on patrol but not undercover
officers and would not have saved the life of one of the men
killed, undercover Officer Christopher Hoban, 26, of Brooklyn.
   He was shot at 7:10 p.m. Tuesday during an Upper West Side drug
raid when one of three cocaine dealers guessed that he and his
partner were policemen. One of the alleged dealers was also killed.
   Less than three hours later, at 9:45 p.m., Officer Michael J.
Buczek, 24, of Suffern, was killed when he and his partner
responded to a routine medical emergency call in Harlem and ended
up chasing two ``suspicious'' men.
   The officers asked them to stop, but they fled. The officers
chased them less than a block before each officer caught up with
one suspect. But one of the suspects spun around and killed Buczek
with two blasts from a semiautomatic weapon, Ward said.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch on Wednesday called for suspects in
drug-related murders, including those of police officers, to be
prosecuted under stricter federal laws by U.S. attorneys rather
than the city's district attorneys.
   The stricter federal penalties would include the death penalty
under proposed federal legislation now on President Reagan's desk.
   In his letter, Koch described Tuesday night as ``one of the
worst nights I have ever had as mayor.'' After each killing, Koch
and Ward met with the families of the officers and reported each
case at hospital news conferences.
   ``I share the mayor's and the police commissioner's concern that
these murderers receive the maximum penalty permitted by law. In
the event the pending federal drug law is passed, this office will
use it as often and as effectively as we can,'' U.S. Attorney
Andrew Maloney said in a statement.
   Hobans was shot in the chest and head as he and his partner,
Officer Michael Jermyn, 25, both assigned to Manhattan North
Narcotics, prepared to buy a gram of cocaine at an apartment.
Hobans was taken to St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, where he
died around 10 p.m., police said.
   One of three suspected drug dealers in the room, Manuel
DeLarosa, 23, of Puerto Rico, was killed by the officers during the
struggle.
   Jermyn ran into the street and alerted back-up police forces,
who caught a second suspect. A third suspect, identified by police
as Bienvenido Castillo, 24, remained at large Wednesday.
   After the second shooting, Buczek was taken to
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center, where he died from wounds to
the chest and abdomen, said O'Donnell.
   Elvin Roberto Pena Peralta, 27, one of the suspects, was
arrested at the scene and was to face a second-degree murder
charge, police said. A second suspect fled and was being sought.
   Police did not know which of the suspects fired the shots that
killed Buczek.
   A private group of business leaders immediately offered a
$10,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction
of the suspects being sought.
   Ward said he knew of no previous cases where two officers were
slain in separate incidents in the same night.
</TEXT>
