<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrappedWhales 2ndLd-Writethru a0829 10-19 1000</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Whales, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0829,1022</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescue Effort Takes Off</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with helicopter picking up
speed, plan to shut down overnight for maintenance; CORRECTS style
on Hovercraft; picks up 6th graf: `Workers labored ...; SUBS 19th
graf: `The fuel ..., to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BAR1, BAR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eskimo whalers wielding chainsaws worked
Wednesday in a race against time to keep alive three whales trapped
by Arctic ice, while a rescue effort using an ice-breaking barge
got under way from Prudhoe Bay.
   Two Army National Guard Skycrane helicopters were rigged to
alternately tow a 185-ton Hovercraft-type ice-breaking barge to the
whales' location about 230 miles to the west.
   Bitter weather hampered the journey over desolate Arctic Ocean
ice, expected to take 25 to 40 hours.
   The first of the powerful transport helicopters lifted off at
noon (4 p.m. EDT), and the early going was ``real, real slow,''
said Sheryl Deveau, a spokeswoman for the rescue effort.
   The Skycrane was dragging the barge along ``an inch at a time,''
she said, with 10 miles of sand bars, mud and shallow water before
the barge would reach smooth ocean ice where the going would be
easier.
   By 4:30 p.m., the helicopter had towed the barge about four
miles from the dock and it appeared things were looking up.
   ``It's moving about 7 miles an hour now,'' said Mike Haller, a
National Guard spokesman. ``They've picked up some speed. They'll
continue on until darkness, and then they'll return here for some
maintenance before picking up the mission again at first light.''
   Workers labored through the night to unload 70 tons of aviation
fuel to lighten the VECO Inc. barge, which has no propulsion
system. The start of the rescue operation was delayed Monday while
the barge was repaired, then again Tuesday after the craft bogged
down in mud near shore.
   Bitter cold and constantly shifting ice trapped the animals in
shallow water two weeks ago as they were migrating south to warmer
waters. Since then, they have surfaced every few moments for air in
holes about 18 miles northeast of this Inupiat Eskimo village.
   North Slope whalers have cut at least two new breathing holes
for the whales, but by midday Wednesday the animals had shown no
interest in them. The whales appeared tired but holding their own,
biologists said.
   John Lien, professor of animal behavior at Memorial University
in Canada, said Wednesday that the whales should survive for
several more weeks despite being battered and bleeding from grating
against jagged ice.
   ``They can bleed a barrel and still be fine,'' said Lien, who
has helped free whales from ice for 20 years. ``We're talking about
a big animal here, between five to 20 tons.''
   While a National Weather Service ice analysis showed no open
water in the whales' vicinity, Jim Brooks, the acting director of
the National Marine Fisheries Service in Alaska, said a lead, or
pathway, through the ice had been spotted about five miles from the
whales.
   ``There are open water leads throughout the Chukchi Sea and
Beaufort Sea, out for a long ways. The ice is always moving. It's
very dynamic,'' he said.
   Brooks said there was no guarantee the whales could reach open
water even if they could get to the leads.
   ``But the hope is that they will be able to make it through the
leads via these open leads used by bowheads and belugas in their
migration. But the gray whale is not an ice-adapted animal. It just
doesn't seem to be able to contend with the ice as well as other
species of whale,'' he said.
   Bowhead whales and the smaller belugas migrate together through
the Arctic Ocean ice, he said. The belugas breathe through holes
smashed in the ice by the larger whales. It was hoped that the
grays might join bowheads migrating nearby and use the same air
holes, Brooks said.
   ``On the other hand, belugas and bowheads have evolved together
for thousands of years. That makes it highly speculative that the
grays would do the same thing,'' he said.
   The rescue operation stalled late Tuesday when the
helicopter-towed barge bogged down in mud just offshore.
   ``It was a goopy mess,'' said Chief Warrant Officer Tom
Williams, the helicopter's co-pilot. ``We were able to move the
barge without that much effort. The problem was that apparently we
went over some shallow mud in that area and the barge doesn't
operate well unless it's over water or ice. It bogged down. Up
until that point we were moving it.''
   The fuel taken off the barge by early Wednesday was to be used
for refueling the helicopters, said Haller. He said the helicopters
would have to fly back to Prudhoe Bay to refuel.
   If it does arrive, the barge is to use its fans and its bulk to
pulverize the ice beneath it and fashion a 40-foot swath to open
water.
   But if more hitches caused the mission to be scrubbed, the
helicopter crews were experimenting with an alternative which
involved using a 9,000-pound steel-reinforced concrete cylinder to
smash holes in the ice, Williams said.
   He said a leftover support from construction of the trans-Alaska
oil pipeline had been fitted so that it could be carried by the
helicopters. ``It's cylindrical, about four feet in diameter by
five feet tall, with points on one end to make it go through the
ice easier,'' he said.
   Rescuers had hoped the support could be dropped through the ice
and dragged to create a channel.
   ``We went out and experimented with it,'' Williams said. ``We
weren't able to drag it. If we used it we would have to punch hole
after hole after hole. The dragging part didn't work. Everytime you
punch a hole, the cracks get larger, they expand and seem to
enlarge.
   ``It would be very laborious if we had to make a solid string of
water six miles long,'' he said.
</TEXT>
