<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     10-19 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass Held in Palace For Army; Youths Sit In For Radical Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haitian leader Lt. Gen. Prosper
Avril joined hundreds of troops Wednesday at a special Mass for
army unity after a group of soldiers tried to overthrow the new
military government this week.
   Hours after the Mass, about 100 young people held a sit-in in
front of the Port-au-Prince Cathedral to protest a church order
telling a popular priest, Rev. Jean Bertrand Aristide, to leave the
country.
   It was the fifth such demonstration in a week. An attack on
Aristide's congregation by armed thugs who killed 12 people and
wounded 70 helped bring about the coup that swept Avril into power
last month.
   The Mass at the National Palace in this capital city, broadcast
by the state-run Television Nationale, was attended by members of
the army high command, hundreds of uniformed soldiers of the
Presidential Guard, Cabinet members, and Avril's wife and daughter.
   Television Nationale said Tuesday night that six officers and
soldiers were discharged from the army because of their role in
Sunday's coup attempt.
   Centrist politicians say the failed coup was an attempt by a
handful of soldiers close to the deposed Duvalier dynasty to regain
control after a soldiers' revolt ousted Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy as
the national leader on Sept. 17.The revolt also forced out dozens
of unpopular officers.
   However, leftist groups claim the coup attempt was a move
engineered by Avril to get rid of soldiers demanding radical
reforms.
   Namphy took over after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to
France in February 1986, ending 29 years of repressive family rule.
Namphy left power for four months after a military-backed civilian
won national elections but seized control again earlier this year.
   The young protesters, meanwhile, accused Haiti's conservative
bishops of trying to get rid of Aristide because of his radical
sermons urging the poor to fight for social justice.
   ``It is obvious that the decision to transfer Aristide against
the manifest desire of the majority of Haitians is inexplicable
without the persistent influence of Rome on certain personalities
in Haiti,'' the Rev. Antoine Adrien, another member of the church's
radical wing, said Wednesday.
   Aristide said in a statement read by the church's Radio Soleil
that he had received an order from Rome to leave Haiti by last
Monday. However, a friend of the priest, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Aristide was still in Haiti on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
