<HEAD>Three Quakes Rattle Tehachapis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs to UPDATE with quakes near Bishop and El
Centro.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GORMAN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tehachapi Mountains were rattled early
Wednesday by three small aftershocks from a summer earthquake. No
damage or injuries were reported.
   The quakes occurred 11 miles north-northeast of Gorman and were
aftershocks of a June 10 quake that measured 5.4 on the Richter
scale, said Robert Finn, spokesman for California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena.
   The first aftershock hit at 3:50 a.m. and measured 3.6, followed
by a 4.1 jolt at 6:44 a.m. and a 3.4 quake at 7:04 a.m., Finn said.
   The California Aqueduct crosses the Tehachapis but the quakes
caused no problems, said David Kessler, an official of the state
Department of Water Resources earthquake engineering department in
Sacramento.
   Sheriff's deputies reported getting a few calls from curious
residents.
   A 4.0 quake occurred at 9:08 a.m. 18 miles south-southeast of
Bishop, according to seismologists at the University of California
in Berkeley. Police received no reports of damage or injury. Bishop
is 220 miles east of Berkeley.
   At 3:47 p.m., a 3.8 earthquake occurred 27 miles north of El
Centro, an Imperial Valley town near the California-Mexico border,
Finn said. Police reported no damage.
</TEXT>
