<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nobel-Reax     10-19 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nobel-Reax,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One of American Nobel Winners Boosts Science As `Tremendous
Career'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FX1, CX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winning the Nobel Prize on Wednesday gave an Illinois physicist
who plans to return to teaching a platform to promote science as
``a tremendous career to follow'' as four of six winners received
the good news in the United States.
   Johann Deisenhofer, a Dallas-based researcher, and West German
colleagues Robert Huber and Hartmut Michel won the Nobel Prize in
chemistry for work done in Germany to determine the structure of
certain proteins needed in photosynthesis.
   Michel, 42, was visiting Yale University's medical school in New
Haven, Conn., when he learned he had been selected by the Nobel
awarding committee of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
   ``Actually, I was starting to tremble. I had my coffee in my
hand. I had to put it away.'' Later, he delivered a scheduled
lecture to an audience whose members were not surprised their guest
had become a Nobel recipient, said Yale professor Donald Engelman.
   Deisenhofer, 45, said he was in the shower when the phone rang,
and was ``really upset'' until he learned that it was a call to
Nobel fame.
   ``I am not a quick starter in the morning. It took me about an
hour to really be sure that this was not a dream,'' he said
   Americans Leon Lederman, Melvin Schwartz and Jack Steinberger
won the Nobel Prize in physics for research conducted at Columbia
University in 1961 into the subatomic particle called a neutrino.
   The award announcement said the work ``opened entirely new
opportunities for research into the innermost structure and
dynamics of matter.''
   The research has ``no practical significance other than very
long term,'' said Schwartz, head of Digital Pathways Inc., in
Mountain View, Calif. ``If you understand something better, sooner
or later it will be practical.''
   ``Someday some kid who is now in high school will find out how
to use this information to bring benefits to all of society,'' said
Lederman, 66, director of the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory
in Batavia, Ill.
   With hopes of encouraging young people to get interested in
science, Lederman is giving up his job as head of the government's
atom smashing laboratory to take a teaching position at the
University of Chicago.
   University spokesman Larry Arbeiter said Lederman would in March
begin teaching not only graduate students in physics, but also
undergraduate science students and liberal arts majors.
   ``It's unusual for somebody of his stature to be teaching people
so early in their careers _ and even people who aren't scientists
at all,'' Arbeiter said. ``He's a very articulate, energetic man
and he's the perfect person to get people interested in science.''
   ``Science is a tremendous career to follow,'' Lederman said.
   ``You have fun all the time _ some blood, sweat and tears too,
but it is ultimately rewarding,'' he said.
   Each Nobel Prize carries a $390,000 award. None of the winners
announced any immediate plans for spending the money.
   Schwartz, a 55-year-old former Stanford University professor,
founded Digital Pathways in the 1970s as ``an attempt to
participate in all the excitement of Silicon Valley.'' He said the
firm deals with data communications in the security field, building
computer systems with an ability ``to keep hackers out.''
   Steinberger, 67, a German-born American citizen, is a physicist
at the European Organization for Nuclear Research, or CERN, in
Geneva, Switzerland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     10-19 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Agrees POW Exchange Can Begin But Says Issues Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's U.N. ambassador said Wednesday that
Iran has no objection to starting the process of sending home all
prisoners of war from the Persian Gulf conflict and hinted the sick
and injured might be freed first.
   Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati noted, however, that some technical
issues still must be resolved in the Iran-Iraq peace talks and
repatriation cannot be completed until they are settled.
   According to the Red Cross, Iran has 50,182 prisoners from the
8-year-old conflict and Iraq 19,284. But U.N. officials and
diplomats in Iran and Iraq believe Iran has 60,000 to 70,000
prisoners and Iraq 30,000 to 50,000.
   Mahallati was responding to a proposal Iraq sent to the
International Committee of the Red Cross and to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar this week saying
repatriation could begin on humanitarian grounds if Iran
reciprocated.
   Mahallati said medical examinations and registration of all
prisoners could go forward. He said Tehran encourages the Red Cross
to continue humanitarian exchanges, which in the past have sent
home sick and injured soldiers.
   ``On our part, we are ready to cooperate with the
secretary-general and the ICRC in order to do our best to
repatriate unfortunate POWs,'' he said.
   He said the Red Cross should encourage further exchanges of
``certain categories'' of prisoners.
   But he said technical issues must be agreed upon, such as the
numbers of prisoners to be released, their ranks, whether prisoners
who were detained the longest would be freed first, the pace of
releases, and other questions.
   He said these issues ``cannot be regarded outside Resolution
598,'' the U.N. peace plan that is the basis for the peace talks.
   Iraq, however, said the releases would be on a humanitarian
basis ``unrelated to the other issues referred to in Security
Council Resolution 598.''
   Resolution 598 called for an immediate cease-fire, withdrawal of
troops to internationally recognized boundries and exchange of
prisoners.
   A U.N.-mediated cease-fire began Aug. 20, but peace talks have
been deadlocked since just after they began Aug. 25.
   The talks stalled over Iraqi insistence the waterway forming
their southern border be cleared of silt and sunken ships.
   Iraq calls the passage the Shatt-al-Arab. To Iran it is the
Arvand River.
   Iran rejected the demand as a secondary issue that could be
settled later, and Mahallati made clear Wednesday that Tehran wants
withdrawal to the border to be the next step.
   Both sides have blamed each other for the stalemate in
negotiations, which Perez de Cuellar said he expects to resume next
week in Geneva.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
