<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DiscriminationSuit     10-19 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Discrimination Suit,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Levee District Head Discriminated Against Woman, Says Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of a suburban levee district
discriminated against a woman employee by refusing to promote her
even though she was best qualified for the job, a federal appeals
court has ruled.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in a decision released
late Tuesday, said the East Jefferson Levee District must pay Sgt.
Callie Walsdorf as if she had received the promotion she was denied
in April 1984.
   John Lauricella Jr., the former district president, ``was heard
to declare, at the time he considered the candidates for the
promotion, `Ain't no bitch gonna get this job,''' the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals wrote.
   ``There may exist a more unequivocal way to express an intent to
exclude women from consideration for a promotion, but none come
readily to mind,'' the court said.
   Lauricella did not return a telephone message left at his
office. He remains a member of the district, which supervises and
maintains the flood protection levees in western New Orleans
suburbs.
   Walsdorf, whose discrimination claim had been rejected by a
lower court, also did not return a telephone message left at the
district office.
   Levee Board President Greg Gambel said Wednesday that he did not
know whether the board would appeal the ruling.
   The federal appeals court declined to order Walsdorf's promotion
to assistant district superintendent, the job in question, because
it would mean firing or demoting John T. Prados, the man Lauricella
appointed.
   ``It is undisputed that plaintiff was the most qualified
applicant. It is likewise undisputed that Prados, who was
eventually appointed to fill the vacancy, was unqualified at the
time he applied,'' the court said, noting that Prados was
Lauricella's ``life-long friend.''
   The ruling said Walsdorf later was rejected for promotion to
lieutenant, even though she had the highest score of all candidates
on a competitive examination.
   The court also Lauricella retaliated against her in five
separate incidents because she had filed charges with the Equal
Employment Opportunities Commission and the state Civil Service
Commission.
   Those incidents included assigning her for six months to a job
in which she did little but run errands and refusing to begin a
meeting of district employees until she and the officer who
testified about Lauricella's discriminatory comment had left.
   U.S. Magistrate Ronald A. Fonseca found that Lauricella had
retaliated against Walsdorf but awarded her only $1 in damages and
cut her attorneys' fees by 60 percent because he said she had not
proved discrimination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
