<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HelicopterCrash     10-19 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helicopter Crash,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denver TV News Helicopter Crashes; Kills 2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUVIERS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television news helicopter crashed and
broke into pieces Wednesday, killing the pilot-reporter and a
photographer, apparently after the aircraft snagged a power line,
the station reported.
   KUSA-TV said pilot Leo Galanis and photographer Brian Hostetler
were returning to Denver from the scene of a plane crash on Monarch
Pass in west-central Colorado. The helicopter crash occurred about
2:20 p.m. about 15 miles southwest of metropolitan Denver.
   A Public Service Co. of Colorado helicopter pilot sent to check
out a report of a downed power line discovered the crash in a
remote, hilly area and found no signs of life in the wreckage,
utility company officials said.
   It was the sixth serious helicopter incident since Denver
television news stations began using the aircraft for news
gathering more than 10 years ago.
   A pilot and an aviation mechanic working for another station
were killed in 1982 when their copter went down while flying
through a snowstorm to the scene of a plane crash. The other
previous incidents, three involving KUSA helicopters, were forced
or crash landings that resulted in at least four injuries total.
</TEXT>
