<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     10-19 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Leader Denounces Syrian Influence in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Michel Aoun, head of the Christian
military government, accused Syria on Wednesday of usurping
Lebanon's sovereignty in his strongest condemnation to date of the
Damascus government.
   Aoun denied charges by Lebanon's rival pro-Syrian Moslem Cabinet
that he was blocking a settlement of a monthlong constitutional
crisis that threatens to divide the country into sectarian cantons.
   ``We should regain our sovereignty from the Syrian brothers,
because they have been directly ruling Lebanon,'' Aoun said in an
interview with The Associated Press at the presidential palace at
Baabda, northeast of Beirut.
   ``The Syrians rule the streets, the police stations and the
(district) governors, in the hope of controlling the head of
state,'' he said. ``There won't be a sound relationship between
Lebanon and Syria unless Syrian troops withdraw from Lebanon.''
   Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon with 40,000 troops in
70 percent of the country.
   Rival governments emerged here after Parliament failed to elect
a successor to President Amin Gemayel when his six-year term ended
Sept. 23. Gemayel named Aoun as prime minister of a caretaker
Cabinet, although that position is traditionally occupied by a
Moslem. The existing Moslem Cabinet of Prime Minister Salim Hoss
refused to step down.
   Aoun, a 52-year-old Maronite Catholic, was dressed in camouflage
fatigues during Wednesday's interview.
   He waved his fist for emphasis while declaring that his Cabinet
will continue to rule ``until a new president is elected.''
   ``We shall preserve Lebanon's unity,'' he said.
   Parliament has failed three times since Aug. 18 to gather the
necessary quorum to vote in a new president. Christian members have
boycotted the sessions, saying they reject pressure to elect a
president who would turn Lebanon into a Syrian satellite.
</TEXT>
