<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LostBoy     10-19 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Boy,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Found After Three Days in Mountains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUYAMACA RANCHO STATE PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old boy was
found safe Wednesday after wandering for three days and nights in a
mountain park and was hospitalized in good condition, authorities
said.
   Jesus Antonio ``Pepin'' Garcia of Mexicali was found by a Marine
searcher nearly two miles from the Green Valley Falls campsite
where he disappeared on Sunday, said San Diego sheriff's Deputy
Christie Guerin.
   The youngster, dressed only in jeans, sneakers and a T-shirt,
was flown by helicopter to Children's Hospital in San Diego, where
he is listed in ``good to fair condition,'' hospital spokeswoman
Vickie Hearst said.
   ``It looks like he just has some superficial scratches,'' Hearst
said. ``He'll be in (the hospital) for observation, but I don't
know how long it will be. He's hungry. He asked for a hamburger.''
   More than 200 inmate volunteers, Marines and sheriff's deputies
joined in the search for Pepin, who became separated from his
family during a pine-cone hunting expedition after they arrived at
the eastern San Diego County park.
   The search began when the youngster failed to return with his
twin brother, Fernando, and a 4-year-old friend, Efren Chavez, to
the family campsite in the mountain park some 40 miles east of San
Diego.
</TEXT>
