<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissileDestruction     10-19 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missile Destruction,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Missile Destruction Completed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three dozen cruise missiles once
capable of wreaking nuclear havoc have been destroyed, completing a
weapons death sentence Wednesday imposed under a Soviet-American
arms treaty.
   Under the watch of Soviet inspectors, the last of 41 Air Force
ground-launched cruise missiles targeted for destruction was
dismantled at 5:45 p.m., cut apart by handheld saws and plasma arc
torches at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base, said Air Force spokesman
Capt. Chuck Roque.
   In addition, 41 protective canisters for the mobile weapons, and
seven launch vehicles, called transporter erector launchers, had
been halved, he said. Only seven launchers were set for destruction
during the current Soviet elimination inspection.
   ``As far as I can tell everybody's happy,'' Roque said. ``Things
are progressing smoothly. The Soviets are seeing what they have to
see. I'm sure they're pleased, though I haven't talked to them.
There doesn't seem to be any problem.''
   The completion was well ahead of the original Friday estimate,
72 hours after the 9 a.m. Tuesday arrival of 11 Soviet inspectors.
   The Soviets' departure for Travis Air Force Base in California,
from where they will return home, is set for about noon Thursday,
Roque said.
   Under the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty, 443 Air
Force land-based cruise missiles, many of which have been deployed
in Europe, are to be destroyed within the pact's first three years.
   In addition, 403 Army Pershing missiles are slated for
destruction, along with 1,846 Soviet missiles of six types.
   Teams of civilian workers assigned to the Air Force's Aerospace
Maintenance and Regeneration Center at Davis-Monthan worked in
eight-hour shifts around the clock, while at least four Soviets
remained at the open-air compound until 7 a.m., when the others
returned, a spokeswoman said earlier.
   On Tuesday, Soviet and American generals watched the destruction
of the first cruise missile. They expressed confidence that the
work would lead to more understanding between their countries.
   Soviet Army Major Gen. Vladimir Medvedev, who heads the Soviet
on-site inspection agency, also said more needs to be done to
expand arms control horizons to strategic, conventional and
chemical weapons.
   He said the INF treaty ``is one of the most critical steps''
toward ending the Cold War. Speaking through an interpreter,
Medvedev said watching destruction of a weapon that could have been
used against his country was ``an unusual event and I completely
feel it.''
   He added, ``I think such acts will make us much closer.''
   Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie, Medvedev's American counterpart, said
on-site inspections will result in more military contacts for the
countries, ``more knowledge and hopefully more understanding,'' and
should generate ``more confidence and predictability in our
relations.''
   He said minimal tension involved with 146 inspections conducted
by both sides showed ``a lot of flexibility and an amazing amount
of good will on both sides.''
   Warheads from the missiles being destroyed have been removed for
storage by the Department of Energy, along with fuel and guidance
systems, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
