<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RocketTest     10-19 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rocket Test,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rocket Test Revived As John Denver Watches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA unleashed more than 100,000
horsepower Wednesday in the first major firing of a large rocket
engine at the Marshall Space Flight Center in almost 20 years.
   Singer John Denver watched the 15-second static firing with
Marshall Director J.R. Thompson and the several hundred other
people and then commented, ``With the technology behind that and
the power it put out, it's spectacular.''
   The firing was held so that the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration could test new propulsion technology hardware and
ideas applicable to liquid oxygen-hydrogen engines. Officials said
the engines should provide more reliability and lower costs for
future space missions.
   The $43 million engine, positioned upright on a test stand,
burned 1,400 gallons of liquid oxygen and 3,800 gallons of
hydrogen, producing a huge ball of flame below the engine which
turned into steam when it hit water in the cooling tank below.
   A 45-second test of the engine is scheduled sometime next month
at the same test stand, which cost close to $10 million in
modifications for the current series of firings.
   Denver came to the space center as part of a three-day
celebration of the recent successful firing of the Discovery space
shuttle. He will be joined Thursday and Friday by the five-man crew
of Discovery, the nation's first space shuttle mission in more than
2{ years.
   The last large firing of a big rocket engine at Marshall was a
Saturn test on Feb. 13, 1969, in preparation for manned flights to
the moon.
</TEXT>
