<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     10-19 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Rebel Leader Sent To Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man thought by authorities to be the No. 2
leader and military strategist of the Shining Path guerrillas was
imprisoned for a maximum 15 years Wednesday for ordering terrorist
attacks that killed five policemen.
   Elsewhere, suspected Shining Path assassins shot and killed two
miners in who opposed a strike, police said Wednesday.
   One miner was shot Monday and another Tuesday in their homes
near La Oroya, a metal refining center 90 miles east of Lima,
police said.
   A three-judge tribunal imposed the sentence against Osman
Morote, 42, after finding him guilty of being the ``intellectual
author'' of several attacks by the Maoist-oriented Shining Path in
Lima state in 1981-82.
   Morote was arrested in Lima last June.
   At his first trial, Morote was cleared of other terrorist
charges for lack of evidence. He still faces six trials in Lima and
provincial capitals for murder and terrorism in attacks stretching
throughout the 1980s.
   The 8-year-old Shining Path insurgency, which is fighting to
topple the democratic government and installing Marxist rule, has
claimed more than 12,000 lives and caused $10 billion in damage,
according to the government.
   The Lima tribunal said violence dictated by Morote included an
attack on a police post on Lima's outskirts in which four officers
were slain and a bank bombing that killed one officer.
   Peruvian law prohibits capital punishment. As amended in 1987,
the law sets 25 years in prison as the maximum term for terrorist
crimes. But the tribunal ruled Morote was subject to the 15-year
maximum in effect when the crimes were committed in the early 1980s.
</TEXT>
