<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Japan-Blood Adv24   10-19 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Blood, Adv 24,0542</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release on Monday, Oct. 24, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Excessive Use Makes Japan Massive Importer of Blood Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors use such huge amounts of blood products,
despite criticism from the government and medical experts, that
some news reports call Japan ``the vampire of the world.''
   Its 122 million people consume up to one-third the world's
available supplies, which makes enormous imports necessary.
   Critics say many patients are given blood products when other
treatments would be both effective and cheaper.
   ``The problem is that Japan has been using too much serum
albumin,'' said Masao Nakashima, chief of the Health and Welfare
Ministry's blood program.
   Serum albumin is a protein component of blood. A low albumin
level can be caused by burns or malfunctions of the liver and
kidneys.
   A government-sponsored committee that investigated consumption
of blood products two years ago said doctors often use the
expensive products when medication is more appropriate.
   ``The committee reported that albumin is often used as a
nutrient, although albumin is not effective for that purpose,''
Nakashima said. His ministry has not issued guidelines limiting the
use of blood products to certain symptoms.
   Toshiharu Yamaguchi, a surgeon at Kyoto Prefectural University
of Medicine, gave another example: ``To improve low protein in
blood after an operation, many doctors administer albumin although
amino acid can be used instead.''
   ``It's only Japan that uses so much albumin,'' he added. ``I
guess part of the reason is that the health insurance system here
can offer (it) cheaper than abroad.''
   Nearly all Japanese belong either to private health plans that
pay 90 percent of medical expenses for salaried workers or a
government plan that pays 70 percent for the unemployed or
self-employed.
   Under the 90 percent formula, treatment with blood products can
cost the patient only 470 to 1,000 yen _ about $4 to $8.
   Yamaguchi attributed the abuse to medical custom and inadequate
government guidelines.
   Nakashima said, ``In the end, it's all up to physicians'
decisions.''
   He said blood donations in Japan meet the demand for whole-blood
transfusions, but about 90 percent of the products used are
imported, primarily from the the United States. All imports since
1985 have been heat-treated to guard against AIDS and hepatitis.
   To reach self-sufficiency, Nakashima's ministry has begun a
campaign to reduce annual imports by March 1991 to 1 million
liters, or about 2.1 million pints, from the current 5.6 million
pints.
   More donations may be hard to achieve because people began
shunning donor buses and centers after the first case of acquired
immune deficiency symdrome was identified in Japan three years ago.
Nakashima said some people think they can get AIDS, for which no
cure has been found, by giving blood.
   The Japan Red Cross, the only organization allowed to collect
blood, received 3.9 million pints from 8.2 million donors in 1987.
   ``Although the number of donors in Japan is not any smaller than
other countries, most people donate only the minimum requirement of
200cc (0.43 pint), whereas the United States and European countries
require more,'' Nakashima said.
   End Adv for Monday, Oct. 24
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv20   10-19 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On the Money, Adv 20,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Oct. 20</NOTE>
<HEAD>Contrary to Fears, Junk Bond Funds Still Shining</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors who ignored many dire warnings and
stuck with so-called ``junk'' or ``high yield'' bond mutual funds
have been rewarded for their faith so far this year.
   As a group, these funds have outperformed funds that concentrate
on top-quality corporate bonds or on government securities, through
a dicey period when many financial advisers were urging extreme
caution.
   For the nine months through Sept. 30, high-yield funds averaged
a total return (yield plus change in net asset value) of 9.6
percent, according to Sheldon Jacobs, publisher of the advisory
letter No-Load Fund Investor.
   That compared with a return of 7.4 percent for funds confining
themselves to investment grade bonds, which are rated as much less
prone to default and therefore substantially safer.
   The junk bond funds recently were yielding 11.6 percent,
significantly higher than the 7.9 percent yield available on
investment-grade bond funds, Jacobs added.
   If you had tried to tell many of the experts last winter that
the results would turn out that way, you probably would have found
yourself in an argument.
   The stock market crash last fall raised fears of an economic
slump that would strain the ability of many companies with lower
credit ratings to meet their obligations.
   Analysts pointed out that the junk bond market, which has grown
from about $60 billion to $180 billion just since the start of
1985, had never been subjected to the acid test of a recession.
   It still hasn't. ``Widespread fears that investors in the high
yield market would suffer severe losses have been unfounded,''
declares the Alliance for Capital Access, a group that represents
many companies that have issued these bonds.
   ``This year the market has significantly outperformed the
Treasury bond market, the investment-grade bond market and the
stock market, as it did in 1987,'' said David Aylward, the group's
executive director.
   Does that mean that conservative investors who stick with
government-guaranteed bonds or bank certificates of deposit are
missing a bet? Not necessarily, says Jacobs.
   Jacobs is well aware of studies finding that the extra yield
investors get in a diversified portfolio of junk bonds more than
compensates them over time for losses suffered when individual
defaults occur.
   ``Risk, as always, has its reward,'' he says. ``People investing
in lower-rated bonds receive greater rewards OVER THE LONG RUN than
investors selecting investment-quality bonds.
   ``Nevertheless, a good investment over the long run is not
necessarily a good investment in the immediate future.''
   For one thing, he says, figures compiled by the investment firm
of Salomon Brothers show that the yield advantage offered by junk
bonds over Treasury bonds has narrowed of late, to less than 3
percentage points from nearly 4 points early this year.
   ``Experts in the field anticipate that the supply of new issues
may soon increase,'' he adds. If that happens, the shift in the
supply-demand balance could exert downward pressure on junk bond
prices.
   ``In sum,'' Jacobs says, ``we believe this is a time for
caution. While current economic data are strong, recessions have a
way of arriving unannounced, and even conservatively positioned
funds could have losses in that eventuality.''
   It seems certain that many financial advisers will remain
skeptical about high-yield bonds and funds until experience can
show how they weather a period of economic decline.
   A few scattered defaults would be no big problem for investors
owning junk bond funds. A more widespread credit crisis would be
another matter entirely.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Oct 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-MarkiePost Adv20   10-19 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Markie Post, Adv 20,0827</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, Oct. 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Markie Post Plays `Shady Ladies' in TV Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Markie Post is temporarily abandoning her
white bread, vanilla pudding image from NBC's ``Night Court'' to
play shady ladies in two television movies.
   She's a casino singer in ``Glitz,'' an NBC movie based on Elmore
Leonard's detective thriller that will be broadcast Friday, and a
hooker in the CBS comedy ``Tricks of the Trade.''
   ``They're shady ladies,'' said Post, who plays defense attorney
Christine Sullivan on ``Night Court.'' ``You can only get shadier
with Christine. There's nowhere else to go, she's so pure.''
   In ``Glitz,'' Jimmy Smits of ``L.A. Law'' stars as Vincent Mora,
a Miami detective who tracks the killer of a call girl through the
gambling casinos of Atlantic City and Puerto Rico. Post is the
murdered woman's former roommate and becomes romantically involved
with the detective.
   ``I read the book when it came out and knew I wanted to play the
role of Linda Moon,'' said Post. ``It's like a 1980s Raymond
Chandler gumshoe story. Well, it's Elmore Leonard. Linda is
independent. I call her a broad.
   ``She knows the ways of the casinos. She's got a lot of heart
and guts. I first described her as definitely not a California
girl. She doesn't drink Perrier, eat sushi or jog. She falls in
love with Jimmy Smits, who's recovering from a bullet wound in
Puerto Rico. He's not sure he wants to go back. He's wasting away
in Margaritaville.''
   Linda takes a singing job in a casino in Atlantic City, where
Mora follows in his search for the killer.
   ``I like to think of it as bringing Jimmy back to life,'' Post
said. ``He's not looking for love. I don't want to get involved,
but I spill my guts to him and fall in love. Then he falls in
love.''
   Post said she was pleased she was offered the role without
having to read for it. ``They did want to see some film,'' she
said, ``so I sent them something from `Night Court' and `The
Gangster Chronicles.' I was a prostitute in that. I played Lucky
Luciano's old girlfriend.
   ``I was also offered `Tricks of the Trade.' I'm a hooker and
Cindy Williams is a Brentwood housewife. We get together to solve a
crime. John Ritter's also in it. It's an out-and-out comedy. What's
different from `Night Court,' though, is that I'm not the straight
man. I'd one of the people Dan Fielding (the lecherous prosecutor
of ``Night Court,'' played by John Larroquette) would go for.
   ``Her name's Marla Waleski and she wears a leather bustier,
leopard-spotted Spandex pants and red boots. It was really neat to
work with another woman. We could talk girl talk between takes.''
   Post also is back at work on ``Night Court,'' which has been
moved to Wednesday. Harry Anderson also stars as Judge Harry Stone.
   ``Christine's in love with Harry, but they can never get
together,'' she said. ``Whenever he gets another girlfriend I'm
always personally jealous. I say let me be a spoilsport. Or let us
both get knocked on the head and get together for at least one
episode.
   ``I don't think Christine's changed. I'm more inclined to slap
her these days. She's so positive. She hasn't changed, but the
public's seen more sides of her. Last year, Harry saw a little scar
over my eye. I'd never noticed it before. I spent the whole show
holding a hand over my eye. She's so vain.''
   She admits that the show's writers are shaping Christine close
to her own personality. ``I do love Prince Charles and Lady
Diana,'' she said. ``They've picked up on that. Christine had a
party celebrating their wedding anniversary.''
   Before ``Night Court'' she starred in ``The Fall Guy'' as the
person who gave Lee Majors his jobs. She compares the role to the
tape recorder on ``Mission: Impossible.''
   She grew up in Palo Alto, where her father was a nuclear
physicist and her mother a poet. She's married to actor Michael
Ross and they have a 16-month-old daughter, Kate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   GRAPEVINE GROWS _ Those raisins dancing to ``I Heard It On the
Grapevine'' in award-winning animated commercials now have their
own program. CBS will broadcast ``Meet the Raisins: The story of
the California Raisins'' on Friday, Nov. 4. Network publicists
describe it as the story of three raisins from the time ``they were
tender young grapes performing near their Modesto, Calif., vines,
through musical eras and onto the road to stardom with the help of
their manager, Rudy Bagaman, a rutabaga.'' The commercials and the
program are the creations of Emmy and Oscar award winner Will
Vinton, inventor of the Claymation process.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, Oct. 20</NOTE>
