<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-StuartLevin ADV23-1stAdd   10-19 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Stuart Levin, ADV 23 - 1st Add,0875</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: my day.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One recent day, that meant first fixing a breakfast of coffee
(``my own special blend'') and cake for three guests.
   He greets his company looking sophisticated, dapper in a blue
blazer with gold buttons, striped shirt and gray flannel slacks. A
gold bracelet on one wrist, a gold watch on the other.
   ``I eat in restaurants, go to museums, theater. I do everything,
but I had to build up confidence in myself,'' he said. ``You've got
to get on in this world and do the most you can. That's what it's
all about, what it's really all about.''
   ``But when I do go out, I think out every detail of the day and
allow for any mishaps. First off, I have to think, `Where are the
bathrooms?'''
   Just leaving his apartment building demands patience and
perseverance.
   He goes down a floor in the elevator but still must negotiate a
set of two steps and a set of three before he reaches the sidewalk.
Then there's getting in the car, the hired driver folding up the
walker and stashing it in the trunk.
   The process is repeated, in reverse, upon arrival, fewer than 10
blocks away. A short drive but a long way, from Central Park West
to the headquarters of Phoenix House Foundation.
   Levin is greeted by his students like a returning hero, but he
quickly settles them back to work.
   At the entrance to the dining room, two young people stand
straight, dressed in uniform: black pants or skirt, pressed white
shirt, a folded restaurant apron at the waist, waiters' pads and
pens in their waistbands.
   Tables are set for a feast, two forks, two spoons, just so on
the edge of the table, even though some of the Phoenix House
employees dining there are having hot dogs.
   ``The food may be rather modest _ it's not Lutece fare _ but the
kids serve it as if it were,'' said Arlene Spiller, assistant
director of public information at the foundation. Levin ``is
demanding and exacting. Before any platter is served, he inspects
it. He corrects every little thing.''
   It's Ronnie Grein's second day in the course. ``I'm like really
nervous, but Mr. Levin is making it comfortable for me to learn,''
said Grein, who came to Phoenix House four months ago as a
condition of probation.
   Grein and Levin hit it off immediately.
   ``I took his hands and I said I love you. I love you for being
here,'' Levin recalled. The next day was Grein's 22nd birthday, and
Levin brought a card.
   ``I don't think anyone ever gave him a birthday card before,''
Levin said, breaking into tears. ``He was so empty.''
   About 60 young people have taken part in Levin's programs. He
lists his successes _ the students and the restaurants where they
work. His friends in the industry donate food, give lectures, even
invite students into their professional kitchens.
   ``No question about it. In time, these young people will have
their own businesses,'' said Levin, fairly bursting with pride.
   The culinary arts program is part of Phoenix Academy, a
residential high school Phoenix House runs with the Board of
Education.
   Students learn menu planning and writing, setting a formal
table, cooking, service. Once a week, they begin the day with a
lecture from Levin and end with the meal they prepared, usually for
12 to 15 people, including guests. After 10 weeks, there's a test
meal, and then Levin takes the class to lunch at a ``tablecloth
restaurant.''
   Students agree Levin is strict _ no eating while cooking, clean
as you go, follow directions, presentation counts as well as taste.
And they agree he teaches more than fine dining, things like
patience, consistency, respect.
   ``These kids are so stupendous,'' said Levin. ``They have a lust
for learning. They want to know, they want to learn, they want to
be. They're just like me.''
   That sameness is not always apparent.
   Gameal Abdo, for example, started using drugs at 13, went to six
junior high schools, eight boys' homes, even jail before he came to
Phoenix House in April 1986.
   Levin grew up in a nice part of Queens, served in the Korean War
and went to the University of Wyoming. He lives in a spacious
apartment overlooking Central Park. There are Picasso prints on his
walls and famous names in his telephone directory.
   But make no mistake: Abdo and Levin both touched bottom and
learned a new way to live.
   At 22, Abdo just landed a full-time job in Tony May's restaurant
as a prep cook, and he'll move to a transitional house while he
saves enough to rent his own apartment. He hopes to open his own
restaurant one day.
   And these days, Levin is on top of the world: ``I'm not a
president or a king, but I sure feel like one.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The National Multiple Sclerosis Society operates a 24-hour
information hot line. The number is 1-800-624-8236.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
