<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0535</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurice Allais, a prolific theorist
whose ideas on balancing supply and demand helped rebuild the
French economy after World War II, won the Nobel Prize for
economics.
   Allais, who received the prize Tuesday, was a Paris shopkeeper's
son who became mentor to a generation of economists.
   He developed formulas to enable large enterprises, particularly
public ones, to keep an economy in balance by regulating prices and
allocating their resources.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of companies allied with American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. raised the stakes in a battle with other
computer giants over control of Unix, a base layer of software that
makes it easier for different brands of computers to work together.
   By banding together Tuesday, the big computer makers gained more
bargaining power in the contest with the Open Software Foundation,
a group that includes International Business Machines Corp.,
Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   Unix is portrayed by enthusiasts as a great hope of the computer
industry because it would allow programs to run on a wide variety
of computers without expensive alteration.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., accused by the
Securities and Exchange Commission last month of extensive fraud,
disclosed that federal prosecutors have formally notifiedthe Wall
Street firm it is the target of a grand jury investigation.
   The firm repeated its contention that it is innocent of any
wrongdoing.
   Tuesday's disclosure marked the first time that the Manhattan
U.S. attorney's office, which had never confirmed such an
investigation, officially notified Drexel that it was the subject
of a possible criminal indictment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States remains committed to a goal
of eliminating global farm subsidies but is willing to consider a
far less sweeping proposal as an interim step, U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter said.
   Yeutter said Tuesday that the United States would be willing to
agree to interim goals for reducing farm subsidies for 1989 and
1990.
   He said those proposals could be adopted at a December meeting
of the 96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade in Montreal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every year about this time the very rich are
thrown into a quandary by a nagging question: What do you tell
Santa Claus to bring when he can go shopping with a blank check?
   In an effort to relieve this yuletide headache, the Robb Report,
a monthly magazine for people with megabucks, on Tuesday offered
its latest annual list of ultimate gifts.
   Starting at the top in the Let Them Eat Cake Department is a $20
million slice of ersatz cake made of 2,500 diamonds by jeweler
Harry Winston, who created this inedible confection for the 75th
anniversary of Beverly Hills, Calif.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose Tuesday to their highest point since the crash
exactly one year ago. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
jumped 19.38 points to 2,159.85.
   Bond prices finished mixed in subdued trading. The dollar
finished higher, gold prices fell, energy prices dropped sharply
and other commodities were mixed.
</TEXT>
