<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-19 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Drop Sharply As Volatility Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The optimism that swept over the oil futures
market in recent sessions disappeared as traders began to fear that
OPEC members might not be able to rein in their continuing
overproduction.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, plunged 60 cents Tuesday to close at $14.61 a 42-gallon
barrel in New York Mercantile Exchange trading. On Monday, the
November contract jumped 29 cents.
   Traders with large positions were unnerved by a report that
pegged current production by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries at 21 million to 22 million barrels a day, said
Richard Kane, a vice president with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Although the report contained no surprises, it was enough to
unsettle the oil market, which has been volatile in recent weeks
because of a series of upcoming OPEC meetings, Kane said.
   Last week traders bought heavily amid optimism that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries could agree to lower
production and stabilize prices. But Tuesday, ``people were wanting
to get flat'' before OPEC members met, Kane said.
   ``People like the market one day, they hate it the next day,''
he said.
   Over the weekend, oil ministers of the six-nation Gulf
Cooperation Council met and proposed a production ceiling of 18.5
million to 19 million barrels a day for the 13 OPEC nations.
   The GCC proposal is expected to be presented to OPEC's
committees on strategy and pricing, which are meeting in Madrid,
Spain, on Thursday. OPEC also has a ministerial conference
scheduled for Nov. 21.
   Refined products traded on the exchange were mostly lower
Tuesday. The November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose
0.16 cent to settle at 46.92 cents a gallon, but subsequent months
declined.
   The November contract for home heating oil fell 1.59 cents to
42.29 cents a gallon. Subsequent months also declined.
</TEXT>
