<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PhilipMorris Bjt   10-19 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philip Morris, Bjt,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Sees Cheese In Its Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY48 of Oct. 18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cigarette profits are the driving power behind
Philip Morris Companies Inc., but the maker of Marlboro and
Virginia Slims sees cheese in its future.
   Philip Morris's $11 billion cash bid for Kraft Inc., which
formally began Tuesday, would give it control of a company that has
a 26 percent wedge of the U.S. market for natural cheese and 60
percent of the processed cheese market, according to market
researcher Find-SVP.
   Buying Kraft would make Philip Morris the undisputed king of the
supermarket aisles, with products ranging from Miller Lite and
Jell-O to such non-cheese Kraft brands as Miracle Whip, Sealtest
and Breyer's ice cream, Celestial Seasonings tea and Lender's
bagels.
   Even after swallowing Glenview, Ill.-based Kraft, though, New
York-based Philip Morris would lean heavily on cigarettes.
   Philip Morris currently gets 52 percent of its revenue and 77
percent of its operating profit from its tobacco business,
according to Mary English, an analyst for the Furman Selz
investment firm.
   Including Kraft, 40 percent of Philip Morris's revenue and 65
percent of operating income would come from tobacco, she said.
   Kraft's stock shot up $28.12{ a share to $88.25 on Tuesday, just
under the $90-a-share offer. But Philip Morris stock fell $4.50 a
share to $95.50, reflecting investors' worries that the expense of
the acquisition would hurt the company's profits. Trading was
extremely heavy in both stocks.
   Separately, a report published today said buyout specialist
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. is interested in Kraft and might be
posturing to rescue the company from Philip Morris.
   According to unidentified sources quoted in today's editions of
The New York Times, the buyout firm either has or is planning to
volunteer its services to Kraft management.
   The aggressive New York firm, with a $5.6 billion investment
pool that can leverage many times that amount, is financially
capable of competing against Philip Morris, the sources said.
   It is the immense profitability of cigarettes that gives Philip
Morris the muscle to bid for Kraft in a deal that would give the
company more control of supermarket shelf space and an entree to
the important European market.
   The purchase becomes especially important in light of the recent
$5.23 billion bid by Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC for Pillsbury
Co. Pillsbury's directors urged stockholders to reject the offer
Tuesday.
   In another deal, Holly Farms Inc. on Tuesday rejected an $891
million purchase offer from Tyson Foods Inc. that would have united
two of the nation's largest poultry processors.
   If successful, the bids would accelerate a trend in which the
food business is being concentrated in the hands of a few giant
multinational companies.
   Philip Morris contends the purchase of Kraft would not raise
antitrust concerns because Kraft and Philip Morris's General Foods
Corp. make different kinds of food.
   Analysts said the two companies combined would be able to make
more effective use of techniques such as cooperative advertising
with supermarkets in order to increase their all-important share of
shelf space.
   Kraft and General Foods also could share trucks, warehouses and
sales representatives. Meanwhile, Kraft's presence overseas could
help get General Foods brands distributed abroad.
   ``These American companies have got to get bigger and strong
before the other guys do, so they can compete head-to-head with the
European conglomerates,'' Miss English said.
   Contrary to the impression given by the backlash against smoking
in the United States, tobacco is not a dying industry. American
companies are selling cigarettes effectively abroad, and the global
industry is growing 1.5 percent to 2 percent a year, she said.
   But the impression that tobacco is a languishing market has kept
Philip Morris's stock lower than it otherwise might be, Hamish
Maxwell, Philip Morris's chairman and chief executive, said in an
interview Monday night.
   Philip Morris expects to generate $11 billion to $12 billion in
excess cash over the next five years, which would be used to pay
for the deal.
   In a sign of its financial strength, the company said Tuesday it
intended to pay for the deal up front by borrowing entirely from
commercial banks, rather than by selling debt securities to the
public.
   The excess cash is what Philip Morris will have left over after
taking care of dividend payouts and what it believes are its needs
for internal reinvestment. Philip Morris already has
state-of-the-art plants that churn out cigarettes far more cheaply
than they can be produced by low-cost labor in less developed
nations.
   In the past, the company's excess cash has gone into increased
dividends and share buybacks, which directly benefit shareholders,
but even after that there is money left over.
</TEXT>
