<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel     10-19 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Formally Notified Its Targeted in Grand Jury Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors officially notified Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. that it is targeted in a criminal grand jury
probe, raising the prospect that the investment giant will be
indicted.
   Drexel, which claims it is innocent of any wrongdoing, repeated
that assertion Tuesday in disclosing receipt of a so-called
``target letter'' from the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office.
   The disclosure came a month after Drexel, one of the biggest
Wall Street firms, was accused by the Securities and Exchange
Commission of extensive securities fraud in an alleged conspiracy
involving four key employees and now-imprisoned insider trader Ivan
F. Boesky.
   Although it has been widely known for months that a grand jury
has been probing Drexel's activities, formal notification often is
seen as a strong signal that prosecutors believe they have enough
evidence to bring charges.
   Bruce Baird, the assistant U.S. attorney in charge of securities
fraud cases, was out of the office and unavailable for comment, an
aide said. Office spokeswoman Deborah Corley said she could not
comment.
   ``The U.S. attorney has advised Drexel Burnham by letter that it
is a target of a grand jury investigation looking into alleged
violations of the federal criminal laws,'' the firm said in a
statement.
   ``According to the staff of the U.S. attorney, no determination
has been made by the U.S. attorney to seek an indictment. Drexel
Burnham believes that any such indictment would be unwarranted and
unfair.''
   Drexel, a pioneer in the ``junk bond'' high-yield debt market,
has been under intense scrutiny by both the U.S. attorney's office
and the SEC because of disclosures by Boesky, who once had
extensive dealings with the firm and who settled insider trading
charges two years ago by paying a $100 million fine.
   In exchange for his cooperation in implicating others, Boesky
was allowed to plead guilty to a single criminal charge, conspiracy
to lie to the SEC.
   On Sept. 7 the SEC filed a long-awaited civil complaint alleging
Drexel, its high-yield bond financier Michael Milken and others
schemed with Boesky to profit on inside information, cheat Drexel
clients, hide stock in each other's names to avoid reporting
requirements and commit other frauds.
   Drexel, Milken and the other defendants denied those
accusations. If a grand jury were to indict them, the SEC suit
likely would be delayed by the more serious criminal charges.
   The SEC suit already has been delayed by pretrial haggling over
evidence gathering and the impartiality of the federal judge
presiding over the case, Milton Pollack.
   On Monday, Pollack rejected defense attorney requests that he
disqualify himself, calling their arguments unfounded. The defense
has vowed to appeal his ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
