<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   10-19 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Doughboy Gets Tough</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP1, MP3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s Doughboy isn't being shy
about the company's rejection of a $5.23 billion unsolicited
takeover by Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   A day after Pillsbury urged shareholders to turn down Grand
Met's $60-a-share tender offer, a snarling Doughboy sporting boxing
gloves and rolled-up sleeves appeared today in full-page newspaper
ads designed to convince shareholders the company is serious about
remaining independent.
   In selected newspapers around the country, Pillsbury's
once-jovial mascot appeared under the headline: ``Grand Met must
have had one too many if they thought we wouldn't put up a fight.''
   Pillsbury said it is ``not going to sit idly by while an
opportunistic British liquor and gambling company takes advantage
of a weak U.S. dollar and tries to buy respectability with the
purchase of a classic American company.''
   On Tuesday, Grand Met continued to press for a friendly deal,
but Pillsbury Chairman Philip L. Smith stressed that now is not the
time to sell. ``Greater values are available to the shareholders in
the long term.''
   The options could include a special dividend to shareholders,
the selling of some of the company's businesses in a financial
restructuring, a leveraged buyout, or ``the sale of an equity
interest to a third party,'' Smith said.
   ``There are options that include not putting the company up for
sale,'' Smith said.
   He said the company's directors will decide on an alternative
before shareholders are required to decide whether to tender their
shares. Grand Met's offer expires Nov. 1, but could be extended.
   Ian A. Martin, chief executive of U.S. operations for Grand Met,
said he was surprised Pillsbury's board concluded the all-cash
offer was inadequate.
   ``Our price represents more than 50 percent over the Pillsbury
market price prior to the announcement of our offer,'' Martin said.
``We doubt that Pillsbury stockholders will agree with their
board's conclusion.''
   Pillsbury's stock rose 37{ cents a share to $59 a share in
consolidated trading on the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday.
   Grand Met spokesman Walter Montgomery said Smith was vague in
explaining why Pillsbury shareholders should hold on to their stock.
   ``The company's eagerly awaited but unsatisfactory response to
this generous offer exhibits the same indecisiveness that has
prevented Pillsbury from taking advantage of its many previous
oportunities to produce value for its shareholders,'' Montgomery
said.
   Asked what direction the board was leaning in chosing an
alternative to accepting the offer, Smith said, ``There really
isn't at this particular time any real favorite.''
   Smith said the Pillsbury board rejected the offer after deciding
that significant investments have been made to improve slumping
Burger King operations and the full-service restaurant chain of
Steak & Ale.
   Grand Met has said it would sell Pillsbury's full-service
restaurants to comply with laws that forbid liquor distillers from
selling liquor at retail outlets, but it has said it would retain
Burger King and other core businesses. The British company also has
said it would cut some senior management jobs at Pillsbury if the
bid is successful.
   Pillsbury is suing Grand Met in 14 states on grounds that the
takeover would violate the so-called ``tied-house'' liquor
statutes. Additional legal action was taken Tuesday with a lawsuit
filed in Washington D.C., alleging that Grand Met's tender offer
violates a section of the 1916 Shipping Act.
   According to the suit, it would be illegal for Pillsbury to
transfer ownership of its TPC Transportation Co. to Grand Met
because it is a foreign company. Such a transfer requires the
approval of the U.S. Secretary of Transportation, according to the
lawsuit. TPC is a water carrier operating towboats and barges,
Pillsbury said.
   Montgomery said Grand Met lawyers have said the proposed
takeover would not violate the Shipping Act.
</TEXT>
