<1ST_LINE>r f PM-APMEAwards     10-19 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-APME Awards,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Performance Awards Presented By APME
^Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Annual Top Performance awards of the Associated
Press Managing Editors association have been presented to the AP
Business News department, the AP Mountain States regional reporter,
Tad Bartimus, and AP photographers Max Nash of Tel Aviv, Israel,
and Jeff Widener of Bangkok, Thailand.
   APME also has awarded special citations to Fred Bayles, AP
national writer, and Scott McCartney, AP Southwest regional
reporter.
   The organization named newsman Ron Blum of the AP Sports
Department winner of its eighth annual John L. Dougherty award.
   The Top Performance awards, presented Tuesday, are given
annually to recognize outstanding work by AP reporters and
photographers during the previous year. There are two categories:
performing under deadline pressure, and feature writing or feature
photography.
   The winners, as well as Bayles and McCartney, were awarded
$1,500 and a plaque at the APME convention here.
   The John L. Dougherty award recognizes excellence in the work of
a young AP writer. Dougherty, a former APME leader and managing
editor of the Rochester, N.Y., newspapers, had an abiding interest
in helping young writers improve their skills. Dougherty died in
1980. Blum received a $1,000 cash award and a plaque.
   The AP Business News department was honored for its wide-ranging
and in-depth coverage of the October 1987 stock market crash, and
Bartimus for her moving article on the accidental drowning of three
young brothers.
   Nash was selected for his spot photo coverage of Israel's
troubled occupied territories, and Widener for a series of feature
photos of Afghan refugees.
   Bayles and McCartney were awarded the special citation for their
six-part series, ``Guardianship of the Elderly.''
   Awards for excellence in the Top Performance reporting-writing
competition went to the AP staff in Israel for its coverage of the
West Bank rebellion; Joan Mower and Michael Sniffen of AP's
Washington bureau for stories reporting possibly unethical
activities by former Attorney General Edwin Meese; Nancy Shulins,
AP Newsfeatures, for her two-part series on people who have
undergone operations removing one side of their brains, and Sharon
Cohen, Midwest regional reporter, for her series on workers
displaced by the industrial slump in the Rust Belt.
   Awards for excellence in photography were given to Martin
Cleaver of London for photos of clashes between Palestinians and
Israeli soldiers; Al Behrman of Cincinnati for photographs of track
stars Valerie Brisco and Florence Griffith-Joyner in action; John
Gapps III of Des Moines, Iowa, for his picture of a farmer in his
drought-parched field; Scott Applewhite of Washington for a photo
of Vice President George Bush with his granddaughter, and Liu Heung
Shing of New Delhi for a picture of a weeping exiled Tibetan woman.
</TEXT>
