<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0742EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HollyFarms-Tyson     10-19 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holly Farms-Tyson,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Rejects Tyson Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poultry processing giant Tyson Foods Inc.
expressed disappointment that its $900 million buyout offer for
Holly Farms Corp. was rejected as inadequate.
   But officials at Springdale, Ark.-based Tyson had no comment
Tuesday on whether they might sweeten their bid for the rival
poultry company.
   Tyson Foods, the nation's largest poultry processor, offered $45
a share plus a quarter share of Tyson Class A stock for each of
Holly Farms' 18.1 million outstanding shares.
   Bob Justice, a spokesman for Tyson Foods, declined to comment on
whether his company plans to pursue its takeover bid.
   ``We're very disappointed that they did not sit down and talk
with us about the matter. At this time, we have no further comment
to make,'' Justice said.
   In a statement, Holly Farms said its board of directors voted
unanimously to reject Tyson's offer, which was made last week.
   ``We just decided that the offer is inadequate and not in the
best long-term interest of the shareholders,'' said Ted Bailey, a
Holly Farms vice president.
   He refused to comment on whether Holly Farms would consider a
higher proposal from Tyson.
   ``Our company achieved record results in the first quarter, and
we have told our shareholders that the prospects are excellent for
all of our businesses for the remainder of the year,'' Holly Farms
President R. Lee Taylor said in the statement.
   ``For over 20 years Holly Farms shareholders have experienced
superior long-term investment returns,'' he noted.
   Holly Farms stock fell 75 cents a share to 50.12{ Tuesday in
consolidated trading on the New York Sock Exchange.
   Holly Farms is a diversified foods company with about 50 percent
of its sales in chicken. The company had sales of $1.6 billion last
year and net income of $36.2 million, or $2.06 a share.
   Tyson Foods produces 14 million pounds of chicken meat a week.
The company had sales in 1987 totaling $1.8 billion and a net
income of $67 million. The company's operations include hatcheries,
feed mills, processing plants and a marketing branch.
</TEXT>
