<DOCNO> AP881019-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-Economy     10-19 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Economy,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Cites Accomplishments In Opening of Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Miguel de la Madrid boasted of his
government's efforts to reduce its role in the economy and declared
that the era of state economic interventionism was over in Mexico.
   Meanwhile, new government figures released Tuesday confirmed a
dramatic shrinkage in Mexico's trade surplus, with oil revenues
sinking and imports skyrocketing by more than 50 percent above
their 1987 level.
   De la Madrid, whose six-year term ends Nov. 30, cited reductions
in government spending, a tighter rein on public accounts and the
liquidation of unprofitable state-run enterprises under his tenure
in a meeting with Commerce Department officials on Tuesday.
   ``Without bragging, I can affirm that there is no other
government in the world that has accomplished a rationalization of
its administrative apparatus with the rapidity that we Mexicans
have,'' he said.
   De la Madrid ordered more than $250 million in budget cuts this
month after prices for oil, a staple Mexican export, dropped to
record lows.
   The cuts were linked to an agreement with the U.S. Treasury
Department and Federal Reserve that permits Mexico to draw up to
$3.5 billion in bridge loans until the government reaches new loan
agreements with the World Bank and possibly other multilateral
agencies.
   A World Bank mission is visiting Mexico City to discuss with
Mexican officials possible arrangements for new long-term financing.
   In announcing the loan package on Monday, the Treasury
Department said it was intended to support Mexico's budget-cutting
and anti-inflation programs by cushioning the impact of the oil
price plunge, which will cost Mexico billions of dollars in
anticipated revenues this year.
   De la Madrid also cited Mexico's accession in 1986 to the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, under which the government
has dismantled a decades-old import substitution policy and opened
up the economy to foreign imports.
   ``Mexico now has a full role in large-scale trade negotiations
that are taking place in the world. Had we stayed at the margin of
a badly understood nationalism, the country today would have been
gravely damaged,'' the president said.
   Mexico's trade surplus for the first eight months of the year
slipped to $2.5 billion, well below the $6 billion surplus
registered between January and August of 1987, the government-run
National Statistics Institute reported Tuesday.
   Exports reached $14.2 billion during the January-August period,
with non-oil goods, at $9.4 billion, well outpacing petroleum
exports, at $4.7 billion. In 1987, crude oil and petroleum-derived
exports totalled $5.8 billion.
   Oil accounted for 29.6 percent of total export revenues in 1988,
compared to 39.3 percent for the eight-month period in 1987.
   Imports between January and August surged to $11.7 billion, or
53 percent more than last year's $7.6 billion figure, the institute
said.
   Capital goods imports worth $8.2 billion accounted for the bulk
of the increase, rising 57 percent over the same eight-month period
in 1987. The institute attributed the rise to greater demand for
manufactures inputs by a healthier industrial sector.
   The institute said imports of consumer goods jumped by 133.4
percent, to just over $1 billion.
   De la Madrid's administration paved the way for the import surge
by reducing tariffs, abolishing official prices for imports and
eliminating a prior import permit requirement for most products.
   The maximum import tariff, which once stood at 40 percent, now
is 20 percent. Most tariffs currently in effect are below that
figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0838EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BurgerKing-Olcott     10-19 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burger King-Olcott,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Pillsbury May Sell Burger King</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. may be forced to sell its Burger King
fast-food chain to fend off an unwanted $5.23 billion takeover bid
from the British conglomerate Grand Metropolitan PLC., analysts say.
   Pillsbury's board unanimously rejected Grand Met's $60-a-share
offer Tuesday, calling it ``inadequate and not in the best
interests of the company and its shareholders.''
   Minneapolis-based Pillsbury said it would consider other
alternatives, including selling the company to a third party,
restructuring Pillsbury's finances by selling some businesses.
   Speculation of an possible Burger King sale was fueled Tuesday
by the resignation of Burger King President Charles S. Olcutt.
Appointed Burger King chairman was Jerry W. Levin, a Pillsbury
executive vice president known for his work on mergers and
acquisitions.
   ``The guy's good at doing deals,'' John McMillin, an analyst
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York said of Levin.
``I've got to think he's been brought in to do a deal.''
   Analysts speculated that the sale of the Miami-based restaurant
chain could bring Pillsbury as much as $2 billion.
   Burger King accounts for about one-third of Pillsbury's sales
and about two-thirds of its profits but has not done well recently.
The company reported its pre-tax profits have declined more than 50
percent, to $48.2 million in the fiscal year ended May 31 from
$119.2 million in fiscal 1986.
   William Maguire, an analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co. in New
York, said Olcott, who quit after just over two years in the post,
``wasn't a marketing man when they needed a marketing man badly.''
   During Olcott's administration, the company ran an expensive but
disappointing advertising campaign touting its hamburgers based on
the slogan: ``We do it like you'd do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
