<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Industrial Sector On The Road To Recovery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: leads with 7 grafs with Commerce Department report on
September housing starts, picks up 3rd graf, Separately, the.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction rebounded in September as a sharp rise in
apartment construction offset a drop in single-family home
building, the government said today.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were built
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.45 million units last
month, up 22,000 units, or 1.5 percent, from August, when housing
starts fell a sharp 3.1 percent.
   Analysts had been expecting a modest recovery in housing starts
for last month because fixed-rate mortgages retreated a bit after
rising steadily from late March through mid-August, when they
peaked for the year so far at 10.71 percent.
   Last week, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Co.,
rates averaged 10.33 percent, the lowest since early May.
   Building permits, a good indicator of future housing activity,
fell 4.4 percent in September to an annual rate of 1.40 million
units, after rising 3.1 percent in August.
   On Tuesday, two reports indicated the nation's industrial sector
is on the road to recovery, while the stock market rose to a
post-crash high on the eve of the first anniversary of Black Monday.
   Speculation in takeover issues pushed the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials up 19.38 points to 2,159.85, its highest point since
the Oct. 19 market crash last year.
   Separately, the Federal Reserve reported that a surge in exports
is responsible for boom times at the nation's factories.
   In a review of the economy based on reports from its 12 regional
banks, the Fed said all areas of the nation's industrial sector
show signs of strength and expansion _ including chemicals, paper
and pulp, steel, autos and trucks and machinery.
   Economists noted the drop in the value of the dollar over the
last three years has made U.S. goods less expensive on overseas
markets and has fueled a boom in export sales this year.
   In another report, the Commerce Department said that income
growth in the ``Rust Belt'' is staging a comeback after trailing
the national average for most of the decade.
   In its report on non-farm personal income, the Commerce
Department said that states bordering the Pacific and Atlantic
coasts continue to have generally better income growth than the
states in between, but the gap in the growth rates is narrowing.
   The government attributed gains in the Great Lakes states to
strength in the manufacturing of durable goods, ``big ticket''
items expected to last three or more years, and in construction. It
said the Mid-Atlantic region also benefited from a pickup in
manufacturing.
   The latest government reports supported bond prices, driving
interest rates lower. In foreign-exchange trading, the dollar rose
against most major currencies. Oil futures prices fell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
