<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Economy     10-19 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Economy,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Raises Economic Growth Forecast For 1988, 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
predicted Wednesday the economy of the 12-nation trading bloc will
grow by an average 3.5 percent this year and by 2.75 percent in
1989.
   The figures are up sharply from the EEC's July 1, which
predicted growth of 2.75 and 2.25 percent respectively.
   ``The forecasts this year are indeed very positive,'' the EEC
Commission said in a report to the 12 EEC states.
   ``The economic prospects for the Community have significantly
improved in recent months'' and 1988 and 1989 should see the
strongest economic growth ``since the end of the 1970s,'' the
report said.
   The EEC report predicted 4 percent growth in the United States
in 1988 and 2.25 percent in 1989, and 5.5 percent and 3.75 percent
growth in Japan.
   The EEC economy grew by 2.9 percent last year, 2.6 percent in
1986 and 2.5 percent in 1985.
   The EEC Commission said investments in the EEC will rise by 7
percent in 1988 _ the highest rate in 20 years and up from July's
forecast of 4.8 percent _ and the EEC's average inflation rate of 3
percent will match that of the economic boom years of 1960s.
   ``The success in fighting inflation and the convergence of
inflationary performances in the (12 EEC) member countries are
impressive,'' the Commision said. ``Exactly one year after the
stock market crash, the Community is in an advantageous position
from which to tackle the economic problems of the coming years.''
   It credited the rosy outlook to healthy growth rates forecast
notably for Spain, Portugal, Italy and Britain.
</TEXT>
