<HEAD>3M Reports 18.7 Percent Increase In Earnings For Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Co. on
Wednesday reported a 19 percent increase in its third-quarter
profit on strong sales.
   3M said that for the three months ended Sept. 30 earnings rose
to $296 million, or $1.30 a share, from $249 million, or $1.09 a
share, in 1987. Sales totaled $2.69 billion, vs. $2.47 billion a
year ago.
   For the first nine months, 3M's profit was $882 million, or
$3.88 a share, on sales of $8 billion. A year ago it earned $702
million, or $3.07 a share, and had sales of $7.05 billion.
   3M Chairman Allen F. Jacobson said sales were strong, especially
overseas, due to the weaker dollar.
   ``Our international unit volume rose about 12 percent for the
quarter, as we continued to benefit from efforts to increase
penetration of international markets,'' he said. ``These volume
gains helped our international companies surpass $1 billion in
sales for the third consecutive quarter.''
   Jacobson said the company also benefited from changes in the tax
law.
