<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ContinentalRoute     10-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Route,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOT Says It Will Reconsider Awarding Of United Route To
Continental</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Transportation will
reconsider its award to Continental Airlines of the Seattle-Tokyo
air route once given to rival United Airlines.
   The announcement Tuesday postponed for another month a decision
in a two-year battle over a route worth more than $100 million in
revenue annually.
   Both United and American Airlines had asked for the review,
claiming they were more qualified and competent to fly the route
than Continental.
   ``Although this does not represent a final decision, we are
confident that the clear merits of our case will speak for
themselves in an objective review by the department,'' said Chuck
Novak, a spokesman for Chicago-based United.
   In a five-page order, the department said that despite a federal
appeals decision ordering that Houston-based Continental be awarded
the route, it had decided to take another look at the case.
   ``The department clearly has the authority to reconsider its own
decision,'' the order said. ``Reconsideration of a final agency
decision is inherent in the agency's power to decide.''
   The order said that United and American had raised questions as
to whether an administrative law judge in initially awarding the
route to Continental had failed to properly consider the
department's ``criteria'' for selecting a carrier for the route.
   ``We agree with this argument,'' the order said.
   The administrative law judge's decision was the basis for the
appeals court decision ordering the department to give the route to
Continental.
   The review will be conducted by a senior department official and
a decision is due no later than Nov. 21. The department refused to
reopen the hearing record.
   Tuesday's decision was the latest twist in the hotly-contested
fight over the route, which at various times has been awarded to
all three airlines by different administrative law judges and
department officials.
   ``It's absolutely good news,'' Steve McGregor, an American
spokesman in Dallas, said of the department's decision to
reconsider. ``The appeals court decision was based on procedural
grounds and we would hate to see such an important route be awarded
on such a basis.''
   The Seattle-Tokyo route had previously been flown by Pan
American World Airways, but United assumed the route temporarily
when it purchased Pan Am Corp.'s Pacific Division in 1986.
   The department approved the purchase but only on the condition
that the Seattle-Tokyo route be dealt with separately.
   United has warned that it would be forced to cancel its
Seattle-Hong Kong route and lay off many of its 2,500 workers at
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport unless it was allowed to
continue flying the Tokyo route.
   A $20 million expansion of United facilities at the airport was
put on hold pending a decision.
   American Airlines officials have said their airline was prepared
to build a new $100 million to $150 million hub at the
Seattle-Tacoma airport if it received the route.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0250 </DOCNO>
