<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Robins     10-19 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Robins,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robins Posts Earnings Decline of 12 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Robins Co. said Wednesday that
expenses associated with its Chapter 11 bankruptcy plan and its
merger with American Home Products Corp. contributed to a 12
percent decline in third-quarter earnings.
   Robins said earnings for the three-month period that ended Sept.
30 were $23.4 million, or 97 cents a share, down from $26.6
million, or $1.10 a share, a year earlier.
   Excluding the bankruptcy and merger expenses, net earnings would
have increased 63 percent to $43.4 million, the pharmaceutical
company said.
   Sales for the third quarter were $264.1 million, a 15 percent
increase over the $229 million for the corresponding period in
1987. Operating earnings were $63.1 million, up 25 percent from
$50.6 million a year earlier.
   Net earnings for the first nine months of this year were $45.5
million, or $1.88 a share, down 25 percent from $60.3 million, or
$2.50 a share, for the same period in 1987. Operating earnings for
the first three quarters increased 11 percent from $122.8 million
last year to $136 million in 1988.
   Nine-month sales rose 12 percent to $692.8 million from $621
million last year.
   Robins filed for protection under Chapter 11 of federal
bankruptcy laws in August 1985 in the wake of mounting claims from
women who alleged they had been injured by the company's Dalkon
Shield birth control device. Among the company's other products are
Robitussin cough medicine and Dimetapp cold remedy.
   Robins' merger with American Home Products Corp. of New York is
part of the company's Chapter 11 reorganization plan.
</TEXT>
