<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NuclearPlants 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Plants, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0050,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Ask for Restrictions on Nuclear Weapons Material</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve members of Congress today asked
President Reagan not to permit production of nuclear weapons
material to resume without a certification to Congress that it can
be done safely.
   ``We're trying to change the debate of the past two weeks,'' to
``get away from finger-pointing'' and address institutional and
policy problems, said one of the organizers of the letter, Rep.
Mike Synar, D-Okla., chairman of the environment subcommittee of
the House Goverment Operations Committee.
   ``The Energy Department is not in control of its own plants; it
is the captive of its contractors,'' was how Synar decribed the
chief problem.
   The letter was released shortly after Energy Secretary John
Herrington told television interviewers that safety standards at
the nation's aging nuclear weapons plants have been adequate but
are not acceptable under modern standards.
   Herrington, interviewed on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, said the
Energy Department has doubled its cleanup budget to $1.5 billion a
year and plans further increases.
   He said in another interview, on ``CBS This Morning,'' that
cleaning up will cost $100 billion to $150 billion, which is close
to the estimate of a congressional study released earlier this
month. The General Accounting Office, according to Synar, has put
the cost at $150 billiont to $175 billion over the next 20 to 30
years.
   The department has shut down all of its facilities producing
plutonium and tritium for nuclear weapons because of safety
problems. Herrington announced last week that one of three
tritium-producing reactors at the Savannah River Plant near Aiken,
S.C., would be restarted by January.
   Three environmental groups, however, threatened today to seek a
court injunction to stop the reopening unless Herrington prepares
an environmental impact statement first. Those statements can take
a year or two to prepare.
   The letter to Reagan asked that he require the department to
develop, within 90 days, a plan ``which will put the department
back in control of its facilities, establish clear lines of
authority and communication, and firmly identify who is
responsible.''
   It also asked that no reactor be restarted until the
department's new Advisory Committee on Nuclear Facility Safety
certifies to both Congress and the department ``that public health
and safety will be adequately protected during reactor operations.''
   Synar said the group had no objection to contractors operating
government weapons plants as long as they were properly supervised.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, a long-time critic of the deparment's
operations and a signer of the letter, said he thought a restart
could be accomplished ``reasonably soon,'' but not within 90 days.
   Spokesmen at the Energy Department who could comment on the
letter were not available.
   In addition to Synar and Glenn, the letter was signed by House
Democratic Committee Chairmen Jack Brooks of Texas, Government
Operations; Mo Udall of Arizona, Interior; John Dingell of
Michigan, Energy and Commerce; and House Democrats Phil Sharp of
Indiana, Dave McCurdy of Oklahoma; David E. Skaggs of Colorado,
Albert Bustamente of Texas and Norman Dicks of Washington, and
Republicans Frank Horton of New York and William F. Clinger of
Pennsylvania.
   The department stopped the only operating reactor at Savannah
River in Augst after the plant operator, Du Pont Co., ignored an
unexplained power surge during startup.
   The government also has closed its Rocky Flats plutonium
production plant at Golden, Colo., after three workers were exposed
to radiation last month. Herrington said there is no shortage of
plutonium but tritium deteriorates and supplies need to be replaced.
   The plants were built in the 1950s, and energy officials have
said they will have to be used for another decade, even though the
normal life of a nuclear plant is 25 years.
   ``There has been a good margin of safety. It's been adequate,''
Herrington told CBS. But he said it was not acceptable under
standards for the future.
   He noted that no one had been killed or hurt as a result of 30
major mishaps reported at the Savannah River Plant or incidents at
other weapons facilities.
   ``But I think that margin of safety has to be widened, and
that's what you're seeing today,'' Herrington said.
   He said none of the problems at the Savannah River plant
approached a meltdown, which could have endangered the public and
no commercial power plant has been affected by the safety problems.
   Herrington said in the NBC interview that the department plans
to release a report ranking nuclear production sites and saying
what is wrong with each one and what needs to be done to clean up
and modernize.
   ``It's the right way to do business today, and we are turning
this giant industrial complex in a good way in my estimation,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
