<2ND_LINE>BC-Ford-Paint Shop,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Plans to Spend $200 Million on Paint Shop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. announced Wednesday that
it will spend $200 million for a modernized paint shop at its light
truck assembly plant outside Kansas City, Mo.
   The company will add 330,000 square feet to the plant in
Claycomo north of Kansas City. The expansion will include a new
enamel paint system and will extend the current corrosion
protection system.
   The plant builds Ford's F-series pickup line and the Ford Tempo
and Mercury Topaz automobiles. The plant employs about 4,300 people
and the expansion will not change that.
   Work at the new paint shop will begin in late 1990. Until then,
the current paint facility will be used, Ford spokesman Bert Serre
said.
