<DOCNO> AP881019-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Genoese Adv21   10-19 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Genoese, Adv 21,0944</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday Oct. 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bill Genoese: Labor Thorn in the Side of Big Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY95 of Oct. 18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airline executives who've faced him across a
bargaining table and union militants who've stood with him in
picket lines use the same word to describe Teamsters leader William
F. Genoese: feisty.
   Some call him downright ornery. Not a few detractors portray him
as a fire-breathing dragon who is big on threats but short on
delivering tangible benefits to his rank and file.
   Genoese, 62, the director of the Teamsters union's Airline
Division, is an old-style labor leader and a perpetual thorn in the
side of big carriers like Pan Am Corp.
   Shy and retiring he's not. ``I'm known to be able to steal the
socks off your feet with your shoes still on `em,'' Genoese said in
a recent interview, vaunting his reputed prowess in negotiating
with company officials.
   ``We call him the magician,'' said Joe Konowe, director of the
union's industrial trades division, who was an assistant to former
Teamsters boss Jimmy Hoffa in the 1950s and `60s.
   Genoese represents around 40,000 Teamsters union employees at
several major airlines: notably Pan Am, Northwest Airlines, USAir
Group Inc. and Braniff Inc. (Not all big airlines have a Teamsters
local.) The union also recently won representation at privately
owned United Parcel Service, which operates a fleet of around 250
planes as part of its delivery network.
   The airline Teamsters include passenger service, cargo and
reservations agents, baggage handlers, clerical workers and nurses.
Unlike pilots and flight engineers, they can be fairly easily
replaced by airlines in labor disputes _ but they can disrupt a
carrier's operations if they strike.
   Together, Teamsters employees at the airlines provide Genoese
with a war chest of around $300,000 a year in union dues.
   Genoese's biggest battle is at Pan Am. The beleaguered airline,
which lost $88.4 million in the first half of this year, imposed
$35 million in pay cuts on its 4,200 Teamsters under federal labor
rules after they rejected a new cost-cutting contract last February.
   Genoese has threatened to call the Teamsters out on strike
against Pan Am under the same rules, but so far hasn't done so.
When the union's strike deadline passed in February, he vowed
``guerrilla warfare'' against Pan Am _ including deliberate
diversion of baggage and cargo and cancellation of passengers'
reservations.
   It's that kind of behavior that has sparked tough criticism of
the Teamsters leader.
   ``I don't like the way Genoese is playing,'' said a Pan Am union
member, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The tactics that
Genoese is using now are the tactics of the past.''
   Genoese doesn't see it that way. ``Any company of any size can
beat any union unless the union is on top of it and knows how to
muster its strength,'' he said in the interview in his Manhattan
office.
   A visit to the sprawling union office, with its staff of 25
(including Genoese's son Bill Jr.), is a walk down the memory lane
of the U.S. labor movement. The walls of the conference room are
lined with poster-size photographs of union leaders exhorting
crowds of rank-and-file members, and of World Airways stewardesses
stripping off their clothes on a picket line in the 1960s in a
contract dispute.
   ``I've been out on the ground,'' Genoese said, looking back on
his early days as a general organizer around the country for the
Teamsters.
   In the 1950s, as an engineer and union activist at the phone
company in New York, Genoese was galvanized by labor titans like
Hoffa and former United Auto Workers chief Walter Reuther. It was
the flamboyant Hoffa who tapped Genoese to join the Teamsters as an
organizer.
   Genoese, a slight man with penetrating blue eyes, grew up in the
tough Navy Yard section of Brooklyn, N.Y. ``Our neighborhood was so
poor they ripped it down to put a slum up,'' he reminisced in his
pungent Brooklyn accent. After serving in the Navy, he got an
engineering degree from Pratt Institute in New York and went to
work as a phone company engineer before joining the Teamsters in
1961.
   Genoese has long advocated selling Pan Am to cure its financial
ills and has allied himself with several suitors, most recently
Towers Financial Corp. Towers, a debt-collection and insurance
holding company based in New York, has said it intends to launch a
takeover bid for Pan Am with the Teamsters' backing.
   But Towers' overture, already viewed with skepticism by Wall
Street analysts, probably lost more credibility in August, when the
Securities and Exchange Commission charged Towers with selling $20
million in unregistered securities to finance a debt-collection
program.
   Towers Chairman Steven Hoffenberg admitted recently that it
would be extremely difficult to acquire Pan Am at this point
without the cooperation of the airline's management.
   In addition to his continuing relationship with Towers, Genoese
also persuaded a coalition of Pan Am unions to hire the powerhouse
investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to explore a possible
buyout.
   His ability to wire these networks across the traditional
boundaries of the haves and have-nots, mixing old-style labor
politics with new-style wheeling and dealing on Wall Street, is
what helps Genoese keep management off balance, observers say.
   ``People on Wall Street know the Teamsters have money behind
them; they understand economics,'' Genoese asserted. ``It opens any
door.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Oct. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
