<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0319</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices set no clear course today in a mood
of caution as Wall Street marked the first anniversary of the crash
of 1987.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which closed Tuesday at
its highest level since the collapse a year ago, slipped back 9.25
to 2,150.60 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 652 up, 603 down and 566
unchanged.
   Trading activity, which has been sluggish for the past several
months, got a boost on Tuesday following word of Philip Morris's
$11.4 billion takeover bid for Kraft Inc.
   That triggered buying interest in other food stocks, and blue
chips as well.
   But analysts said the memory of the market's record drop a year
ago still was acting as a damper on traders' enthusiasm.
   In addition, some investors seemed to be leery of making big
commitments before the government's scheduled report Friday on the
consumer price index for September.
   Kraft climbed 2 to 90\ and Philip Morris shares dropped 1\ to
94\.
   Besides Philip Morris, losers among the blue chips included
General Electric, down [ at 44{; International Business Machines,
down \ at 124[, and American Telephone & Telegraph, down [ at 27].
   Apple Computer rose ~ to 40\ in the over-the-counter market. The
company reported earnings for the fiscal fourth quarter ended Sept.
30 of 84 cents a share, up from 54 cents in the comparable period a
year earlier.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.25 to 157.07. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .68 at 304.83.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 92.56 million shares at
noontime, up from 78.48 million at the same point Tuesday.
</TEXT>
