<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Kodak-IBM     10-19 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kodak-IBM,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Agrees to Buy Some Foreign IBM Service, Sales and Lease
Agreements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. has agreed to buy
International Business Machine Corp.'s existing copier service,
sales and lease agreements in 16 countries, a Kodak spokesman said
Wednesday.
   The agreement follows a similar one in April that transferred
IBM's U.S. copier service and sales agreements to Kodak, effective
July 1, said Kodak spokesman Ron Roberts.
   Terms were not disclosed in either deal.
   At the time of the first deal, stock analysts said the move
would benefit both companies, allowing Kodak to gain a stronger
presence in the copier market and giving IBM the opportunity to
concentrate on its forte, computers.
   Thirteen European countries are covered under the agreement
including Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, West Germany,
Italy, the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the
United Kingdom.
   The three non-European countries are Argentina, Australia and
Canada.
   The transition from IBM to Kodak will be made on a
country-by-country basis and will involve further discussions and
agreements with respective subsidiaries and be subject to local
laws and customs, Roberts said.
   He said Kodak may recruit IBM copier service employees in some
countries. Those who wish to remain with IBM will be offered other
opportunities in the company.
</TEXT>
