<DOCNO> AP881019-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Kraft 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0827</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kraft, 1st Ld-Writethru,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Size Of Philip Morris Bid Leaves Kraft Nearly Defenseless: Experts</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY48</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 20th graf pvs bgn, In its ... to CORRECT ending date of
3rd quarter to Sept. 24 sted March 24. Picks up 21st graf bgng,
Revenues for ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. officials began mulling an $11
billion takeover offer, but industry analysts said the sheer size
of Philip Morris Cos. Inc.'s cash bid left the processed-foods
giant nearly defenseless.
   ``My own feeling is that Philip Morris is not going to take no
for an answer,'' said John C. McMillin, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Meanwhile, Kraft on Tuesday reported a 17 percent profit gain in
the third quarter, reflecting the strong earnings growth that is
part of its appeal to Philip Morris.
   Kraft said it was studying Philip Morris' $90-per-share tender
offer, announced Monday, and expected to make a recommendation to
its shareholders by Oct. 31. A purchase at that price would be the
second biggest business acquisition in U.S. history.
   Unidentified sources quoted in today's editions of The New York
Times said the leveraged buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
& Co. may be offering its services to Kraft management. The paper
said the bidding for Kraft could climb by another $1 billion if
Kohlberg enters the fray.
   Kraft closed at $88.37{, up $28.25 Tuesday on the New York Stock
Exchange in reaction to Philip Morris' unsolicited offer.
   Kraft, based north of Chicago in Glenview, already has indicated
its desire to remain independent. But many analysts who follow the
company say Kraft would be hard-pressed to devise a plan for
raising the value of its stock to the price being offered by
deep-pocketed Philip Morris.
   ``Their options are very limited by the bidder being Philip
Morris and the willingness of Philip Morris to go further if they
have to,'' McMillin said.
   Philip Morris Chairman Hamish Maxwell has indicated his
willingness to ``negotiate an amicable transaction,'' which is
believed to mean he is willing to offer more for Kraft.
   Analysts likened Kraft's situation to that of Pillsbury Co.,
which urged its stockholders on Tuesday to reject Grand
Metropolitan PLC's unsolicited $5.23 billion bid for the food and
restaurant company.
   Grand Met's offer for Pillsbury is about 21 times the company's
earnings; Philip Morris' bid for Kraft is about 26 times Kraft's
earnings.
   ``When you get a pass at you of 22, 23, 24 times earnings, I'd
take the money and run,'' said John Maxwell Jr., an analyst with
Wheat First Securities Inc. in Richmond, Va.
   ``I don't see how you can turn premiums like that down if you're
taking care of your shareholders.''
   Analyst Roger Spencer of PaineWebber Inc. in Chicago said Philip
Morris' bid could spark a bidding war for Kraft, which boasts
strong growth potential and very little debt. But other analysts
dismissed that notion, saying few companies could better the Philip
Morris offer.
   Philip Morris has filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Chicago challenging Kraft's first line of defense, a ``poison
pill'' that kicks in when an unwanted suitor acquires 20 percent of
Kraft stock. In that event, Kraft would double the number of shares
held by all other stockholders, making a buyout prohibitively
expensive.
   But analysts said poison pill challenges were standard procedure
in takeover wars and they doubted a battle for Kraft would turn on
the court case.
   Analyst Roy Burry of Kidder, Peabody & Co. in New York said
Kraft might bring in a white knight _ a third company with which it
would merge to defeat Philip Morris.
   McMillin said Kraft's only chance to remain independent might be
a ``Pac Man'' defense in which Kraft would turn attacker and offer
to buy Philip Morris in a deal that would be financed by selling
some assets of the New York-based tobacco and food company.
   But McMillin acknowledged that such a scenario was ``a bit
far-fetched.''
   In its third-quarter earnings statement Tuesday, Kraft reported
net income of $148.7 million, or $1.20 per share, for the 13 weeks
ending Sept. 24, compared with $126.9 million, or 92 cents per
share, for the same period a year ago.
   Revenues for the period advanced 12 percent to $2.8 billion from
$2.5 billion.
   The quarterly results include net income of $10 million from
Duracell, the battery division that Kraft sold to a management
group for $685.6 million in the second quarter and which Kraft
counted as a discontinued operation.
   For the first three quarters of 1988, Kraft reported net income
of $1.1 billion, or $8.20 per share, compared with $391.8 million,
or $2.86 per share, for the same period in 1987.
   Sales for the first three quarters advanced 13 percent to $8.3
billion from $7.3 billion.
   The cumulative results for the first three quarters of 1987 were
restated to reflect a $45.2 million gain in the first quarter
resulting from an accounting change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
