<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Drugs     10-19 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Drugs,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bristol-Myers Reports 16 Percent Rise In Third-Quarter Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bristol-Myers Co. said Wednesday its profits
rose 16 percent in the third quarter, helped by a healthy increase
in international sales.
   For the three-month period ended Sept. 30, the pharmaceutical
and health products company said it earned $232 million, or 81
cents a share, up from $200 million, or 70 cents a share, a year
earlier. Third-quarter revenue rose 10 percent to $1.52 billion
from $1.38 billion in 1987.
   For the first nine months of the year, Bristol-Myers reported
its net earnings grew 18.3 percent to $633 million, or $2.20 a
share, from $536 million, or $1.87 a share, in the same period in
1987. Revenue totaled $4.49 billion, up 11.2 percent from $4.04
billion in the same nine-month period last year.
   Richard L. Gelb, chairman of Bristol-Myers, which makes
toiletries, pharmaceuticals, vitamins and infant formula, said the
company's international sales increased 19 percent in the third
quarter.
</TEXT>
