<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EEC-US     10-19 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-US,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Trade Officials Seek to Allay American Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European trade officials sought
Wednesday to put to rest American fears that the giant consumer
market that will be formed in Western Europe in 1992 will
discriminate against U.S. and other foreign firms.
   Willy De Clercq, the top trade official of the European Economic
Community, told reporters, ``1992 will not mean protectionism. ...
It would be absurd for the community to move toward a policy of
protectionism.''
   De Clercq and other top officials of the 12-nation trading bloc
issued a statement designed to spell out the implications for other
countries of the move to create a single, European-wide market by
the end of 1992.
   To meet that goal, the 12 nations of the European Community,
also known as the Common Market, are dismantling trade barriers
that separate them.
   The United States has repeatedly expressed concern that in
lifting restrictions on internal trade, the Europeans might try to
keep out U.S. and other foreign competition.
   But De Clercq insisted that fears the Europeans will set up new
barriers to trade and form a ``Fortress Europe'' were ``senseless
and groundless.''
   ``I hope the very clear signals that this commission (the bloc's
executive body) has given in order to show its willingness ... to
be a world partner and not a fortress can help alleviate all kinds
of fears,'' he said.
   De Clercq and Lord Cockfield, the top official for the internal
market, also sought to allay concerns about the community's use of
the word reciprocity in discussing how much access foreign firms
will have in business fields such as financial services not yet
governed by international trade rules.
   ``I would like to express my astonishment,'' said De Clercq,
``that this word gives rise to such emotional reactions.''
   ``What we do not want is for reciprocity to mean something other
than the same advantages for everyone,'' he said.
   ``We do not have the intention of asking all our partners to
make the same concessions,'' he said.
   The Common Market, he said, was not considering ``identical
reciprocity'' but rather ``equivalent reciprocity,'' which he
described as ``the balance of advantages, a fair deal, where
everyone stands to benefit.''
   The statement issued by the trade group said the community
``will offer free access to 1992 benefits for firms from countries
whose market is already open or which are prepared to open up their
markets.''
   U.S. officials fear the use of a reciprocity guideline will
subject U.S. banks to crippling restrictions because American
banking rules are much tighter than those in some European
countries. The Glass-Steagall Act separates commercial and
investment banking in the United States, a distinction not
recognized in parts of Europe.
   U.S. officials want the Common Market to apply a standard of
national treatment to foreign firms so that U.S. banks and other
operations will be treated in the new market just like European
companies.
   Cockfield said the reciprocity clause was put in a draft
proposal on 1992 banking rules as a bargaining tool to open up
other countries' markets during the current round of international
trade negotiations.
   ``Our objective here,'' he said, ``is not a restrictive one. It
is ultimately one of getting the most liberal regime that can be
negotiated in the world as a whole.''
   He said, however, that the community would take a look at the
amount of access given European firms in a foreign country when one
of its companies makes an initial application to operate in the
European market.
   He dismissed speculation that the community would try to limit
the operations of companies that are already established in the
community.
   ``I find it difficult to envisage a situation in which we would
want to do that sort of thing,'' he said.
   Spokesmen for the U.S. mission to the Common Market were in a
meeting and could not be immediately reached for comment.
   Cockfield also cautioned the United States and Japan against
taking protectionist steps that would force the Europeans to
respond.
   ``The great threat to a liberal world trading system is
protectionist legislation in America and protectionist attitudes in
Japan,'' he said. ``It is this sort of thing that generates a mood
in which people talk about retaliation.''
   The trading group is made up of Britain, Ireland, Belgium,
France, the Netherlands, Germany, Denmark, Greece, Portugal, Spain,
Luxembourg and Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1722EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Banks     10-19 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Banks,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Report Mixed Quarterly Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   First Interstate Bancorp and Mellon Bank Corp. on Wednesday
reported huge third-quarter losses due to restructuring projects,
while another large banking company, Bankers Trust New York Corp.,
had higher earnings.
   Meanwhile, Great Western Financial Corp., one of the nation's
largest thrift holding companies, said its net income jumped about
20 percent in the July-September period.
   First Interstate, ranked eighth among the nation's banking
companies, said its third-quarter loss more than doubled to $214.4
million from $78.75 a year ago. For the first nine months, it lost
$14.63 million, vs. a $508.48 million shortfall in 1987.
   The Los Angeles company said it was in the red due to its
decision to spin off about $400 million in non-performing assets
and add $180 million for loan and foreclosed property reserves of
its Texas subsidiary.
   Excluding those special items, First Interstate said, it would
have earned $94.2 million, or $1.95 a share, in the third quarter
and $268.1 million, or $5.72 a share, for the year to date.
   Pittsburgh-based Mellon also attributed its financial woes _ a
$166 million quarterly loss, compared with a year-ago profit of $16
million, or 47 cents a share _ to several one-time expenses. For
the nine-month period Mellon recorded a $113 million loss, compared
with a $610 million loss in 1987.
   The nation's 15th largest banking concern said its quarterly
results included a $203 million restructuring expense from the
anticipated sale of several assets to Grant Street National Bank.
   Bankers Trust, ranked ninth, said it netted $162.1 million, or
$2.01 a share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, up 11 percent
from the $15.7 million, or $2.03 a share, it earned a year ago.
   For the first three quarters of 1988, net income totaled $462.2
million, compared with a net loss of $283.3 million last year, when
the New York company added $700 million to its loan-loss provision
to cover troubled Third World debt.
   Bankers Trust said its loan-loss provision totaled $5 million in
the third quarter, $15 million less than a year earlier, and that
helped improve earnings. The company also reported strong interest
and non-interest income.
   Great Western, based in Beverly Hills, Calif., and ranked third
among savings and loan companies, said it earned $68 million, or 53
cents per share, in the third quarter. That was 21 percent higher
than year-ago earnings of $56 million, or 44 cents a share.
   For the nine months, net income totaled $189 million, or $1.48 a
share, vs. $198 million, or $1.55 a share, in 1987.
   The company said increased real estate loan commitments were at
an all-time high and helped earnings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
