<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat, Soybeans Close Higher; Corn, Oats Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and soybean futures, bolstered by a slight
pickup in foreign demand, closed modestly higher Wednesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade while corn and oat futures prices finished
mostly lower.
   Exporters said Egypt had purchased 250,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices and China bought 170,000 metric tons,
also at prices subsidized under an Agriculture Department program
to boost exports.
   Taiwan was said to have purchased 27,000 metric tons of U.S.
soybeans at market prices and was expected to bid for another
54,000 metric tons tonight.
   The sales lifted the spirits of market bulls, who have been
dismayed by a general slowdown in export business and by the
failure of government negotiators to hammer out a new long-term
agreement for Soviet purchases of U.S. grain, analysts said.
   Until the trade picture improves or some other major change in
market fundamentals occurs, ``the markets will continue to lack
conviction and meander in a fairly narrow range without any real
force behind them,'' said Rich Feltes, director of commodities
research for Refco Inc., a commodities brokerage based in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 2} cents to 3} cents higher with
December at $4.26} a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1} cents lower
with December at $2.90{ a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower to } cent
higher with December at $2.58\ a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent
to 7 cents higher with November at $8.06{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
