<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was little changed Wednesday in
slow trading in Europe. Gold prices finished lower after a choppy
session.
   Foreign exchange dealers said that in the absence of
market-affecting news, the dollar traded in a narrow range.
   ``Bearish sentiment is intact, but there is a lack of confidence
and a lack of ammunition to push the dollar below its recent
range,'' said Nigel Green, assistant director at EBC Amro Bank Ltd.
in London.
   A report in Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading financial
daily, said U.S. and Japanese central banks might be willing to
coordinate action to prevent the dollar falling further against the
yen.
   Some dealers said speculation about central bank intervention
was keeping the market jittery about pushing the dollar lower,
although the major central banks have not been sighted supporting
the American currency in the open market this week.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.85 yen to a closing 126.85 yen from
127.70 yen late Tuesday. Later, in London, it was quoted at 127.20
yen.
   In London, the dollar was unchanged against the British pound.
It cost $1.7515 to buy one pound, the same price as late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates: 1.8115 West German marks, up from 1.8050; 1.5275 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5280; 6.1710 French francs, down from 6.1735;
2.0380 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0390; 1,347.625 Italian lire, up
from 1,345.50; and 1.19955 Canadian dollars, down from 1.20095.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $411.05 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $412.95. In Zurich, gold was lower,
closing at a bid $410.00 compared with $411.00 late Tuesday.
   Hong Kong financial institutions were closed for a Chinese
festival.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.35 a troy ounce, compared
with Tuesday's $6.39.
</TEXT>
