<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Computers     10-19 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Computers,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apple Computer, Microsoft Report Big Quarterly Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. on Wednesday reported a 51 percent earnings
gain in its fiscal fourth quarter while Wang Laboratories Inc. said
its first-quarter profit fell 41 percent.
   Meanwhile, computer software maker Microsoft Corp. said its
first-quarter net income soared 72 percent.
   Apple, a major producer of personal computers based in
Cupertino, Calif., said net income for its final quarter ended
Sept. 30 was $107.9 million, or 84 cents per share, on sales of
$1.1 billion. That compared with earnings of $71.7 million, or 54
cents a share, and sales of $786 million in 1987.
   For the full fiscal year, Apple earned $400.3 million, or $3.08
a share, up 84 percent from the $217.5 million, or $1.65 per share,
netted a year ago. Sales rose 53 percent, to $4.1 billion from $2.7
billion.
   Wang, a producer of office computers based in Lowell, Mass.,
reported net income of $13.1 million, or 8 cents a share, in its
first quarter ended Sept. 30, compared with a profit of $22.5
million, or 14 cents a share, a year ago. Revenue rose to $723
million from $693 million.
   Microsoft, based in Redmond, Wash., earned $36.6 million, or 65
cents a share, on revenue of $176.4 million for its fiscal first
quarter ended Sept. 30. A year ago it had a profit of $21.3
million, or 38 cents a share, and $102.6 million in revenue.
   Apple Chairman John Sculley said its latest earnings report
marked the company's 10th consecutive quarterly growth in sales and
earnings.
   ``This performance underscores the continued success of Apple
Computer and is due, in large part, to our success with the
Macintosh product family in business markets around the world,'' he
said.
   Wang said international revenue grew about 11 percent but was
offset by sluggish domestic demand. The company also blamed its
earnings decline on the costs of recent product introductions and
associated marketing programs.
   For Microsoft, the first-quarter results represented the 12th
consecutive record for revenue.
   Chief Financial Officer Frank Gaudette said Microsoft's
international sales remained strong, accounting for 48.8 percent of
the company's business for the quarter.
   During the past quarter, Microsoft introduced an updated version
of its Excel spreadsheet program and an expanded version of its
MS-DOS computer operating system for International Business
Machines Corp. and compatible personal computers.
</TEXT>
