<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilProduction     10-19 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Production,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Storms Reduce Domestic Oil Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Storms in the Gulf of Mexico last month forced
domestic oil production to its lowest level in more than a decade,
the American Petroleum Institute reported Wednesday.
   September's oil production was estimated at 7.94 million barrels
a day, a reduction of some 267,000 barrels a day from a year ago.
It was the first time in more than 10 years that domestic oil
production fell below 8 million barrels, the trade group said.
   More than 100,000 barrels a day of the loss was attributed to
two hurricanes, one that passed across offshore oil fields as it
moved into Louisiana and another that threatened the same area
before eventually hitting northern Mexico. Both forced the shutdown
of several refineries and production platforms.
   Meanwhile, petroleum imports remained at 6.9 million barrels a
day in September the despite storm-related shipment delays, the
trade group said. For the first nine months of the year, imports
were up 6.8 percent, or 440,000 barrels a day, from last year.
   In other areas, the report said:
   _Deliveries of refined petroleum products climbed 1.1 percent to
16.9 million barrels in September, compared with a year ago.
   _Gasoline deliveries increased 1.2 percent to 7.3 million
barrels, with premium unleaded gasoline's share of the market
climbing to 23 percent from 20 percent last year, and leaded
gasoline's share dropping to 17 percent.
   _Deliveries of distillate oil, which includes home heating oil
and diesel fuel fell 0.2 percent in September, due in part to the
technical corrections bill now before Congress.
   The measure, which may become law before the end of the year,
includes a provision making it unnecessary for farmers and other
off-highway users of diesel fuel to pre-pay the federal excise tax.
Many users apparently have postponed their purchases in
anticipation of the bill's passage, the oil group said.
   _Crude oil inventories fell for the third month in a row to 324
million barrels, the lowest level in more than a year. Distillate
stocks, meanwhile, rose 7 million barrels and stood at 3 million
barrels higher than a year earlier. Total stocks exceeded 1 billion
barrels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
