<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-GoldFields     10-19 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gold Fields,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government To Investigage Consolidated Gold Share Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday appointed inspectors to
investigate possible insider trading of stock in Consolidated Gold
Fields PLC ahead of a takeover bid by South African-controlled
Minorco SA.
   Trade and Industry Secretary Lord Young said the investigators
have been asked to report to him ``as quickly as possible''
concerning possible insider trading and concert-party share
ownership of the company's stock. This occurs when one company
secretly agrees to buy stock for another firm.
   The investigation, announced shortly after the close of the
London stock market, is being conducted at the request of the
company, Young said.
   Consolidated Gold Fields has alleged that insider dealing and
share building by parties related to Minorco occurred in the weeks
ahead of the Sept. 21 launch of the bid, which it is fighting.
   It said the activity was ``fully consistent with insider dealers
having knowledge of both the time and value of the bid.''
   The company claims that the activity affected its chances of
fending off the takeover attempt.
   The investigation comes less than a week ahead of the Oct. 25
close of the Minorco bid. Minorco is offering 19 pounds ($33) cash
and one new Minorco share for every two Gold Fields shares.
   A spokesman for the Department of Trade and Industry said the
Minorco bid would not necessarily be stopped if the investigation
turns up evidence of insider trading or concert-party purchases.
Minorco has also called for an investigation of share dealings
ahead of the bid.
   The Department of Trade's Office of Fair Trading is also
expected to make a recommendation shortly on whether the bid should
be investigated for its impact on competition.
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares closed Wednesday at 12.20
pounds ($21.35), off 35 pence (61 cents) from Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0274 </DOCNO>
