<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Phones     10-19 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Phones,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BellSouth Reports Flat Earnings, Ameritech Profits Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two regional Bell telephone companies reported lackluster
third-quarter results Tuesday, with BellSouth Corp. announcing its
profits were flat and Ameritech posting a 23 percent earnings
decline.
   Atlanta-based BellSouth said its earnings totaled $419.6
million, or 89 cents a share, compared with $418.6 million, or 87
cents a share, in the third quarter of 1987.
   Revenue increased to $3.46 billion from $3.11 billion a year
earlier.
   The company, whose telephone units include Southern Bell and
South Central Bell, said earnings growth was held in check partly
because of accounting changes ordered by the Federal Communications
Commission.
   BellSouth said its earnings for the first nine months of the
year totaled $597.1 million, or $2.61 per share, down 23 percent
from $777.5 million, or $2.61 per share, in the same period of 1987.
   The company had sharply higher expenses during the first three
quarters of this year.
   Revenue for the period totaled $10.02 billion, compared with
$9.08 billion a year earlier.
   Chicago-based Ameritech said its earnings for the third quarter
totaled $281.1 million, or $2.07 per share, compared with $301.1
million, or $2.16 per share, in the same period a year earlier.
   The company, the parent of Bell telephone companies serving
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin, said its earnings
were reduced by charges related to the sale of its systems software
subsidiary, Applied Data Research Inc.
   The company reported third-quarter revenue of $2.51 billion, up
from $2.43 billion in the 1987 quarter.
   Ameritech reported nine-month earnings of $927.7 million, or
$6.80 a share, up 7 percent from $865.9 million, or $6.14 a share,
in the same period a year ago.
   Revenue for the first three quarters increased to $7.4 billion
from $7.1 billion.
