<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GeneralDynamics     10-19 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Dynamics,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor's Earnings for Quarter Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp. said Wednesday an
Electric Boat division strike and continued investments in advanced
aerospace programs combined to lower the defense contractor's
third-quarter earnings by 13.5 percent.
   General Dynamics had earnings of $96.4 million, or $2.29 per
share, compared with $111.5 million, or $2.62 per share, for the
same period in 1987. Earnings for the year's first nine months were
$268.8 million, or $6.39 per share, compared with $342 million, or
$7.99 per share, one year earlier.
   Sales of $2.3 billion for the third quarter and $7 billion for
the first nine months compared with those of $2.3 billion and $6.9
billion in 1987.
   General Dynamics' funded backlog at the end of the third quarter
was $15.8 billion and its total backlog, funded and unfunded, was
$22.9 billion, representing approximately 2.4 years of sales, the
company said. Comparable figures a year ago were $15.2 billion and
$22.9 billion.
   Stanley C. Pace, chairman and chief executive officer, said the
work stoppage at the Electric Boat division in Groton, Conn., was
the principal cause of General Dynamics' third-quarter decline.
   ``However, we believe that terms of the Oct. 11 (Electric Boat)
labor settlement improve our position for future submarine
competitions,'' Pace said. ``Our recent award of the 16th Trident
submarine continues our role as the sole builder of that very
important class.''
   Cited also by Pace were continued investments in the Atlas
expendable launch vehicle program and advanced aerospace programs,
particularly the Air Force's advanced tactical fighter.
   ``While these programs are currently incurring high development
costs, we expect them to make significant contributions to
operating earnings in the long term,'' Pace said. ``Our overall
commitment to cost containment is evidenced at Land Systems and at
Cessna, both of which show improved earnings.''
</TEXT>
