<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1638EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Crash-Suits Bjt   10-19 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Suits, Bjt,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crash-Suit Mania Never Came, But Out-Of Court Arbitrations Up
Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most investors hurt by the stock crash a year
ago Wednesday didn't rush into court to sue brokers for negligence,
contrary to expectations of a litigation tidal wave, lawyers and
securities professionals say.
   Reviewing what happened a year after the collapse erased $500
billion in paper profits, they offered several explanations for the
surprisingly few suits. For one thing, many disputes were
arbitrated outside of court; for another, many investors simply
realized that severe risk is part of the stock market game.
   ``I think people sort of assessed this as a freak act of
nature,'' said William Fitzpatrick, general counsel of the
Securities Industry Association, a trade group of brokerages.
``Certain things happen in life that are nobody's fault, like a
hurricane.''
   At this time last year, Fitzpatrick and others in the securities
business were bracing for an onslaught of suits by investors who
felt betrayed by the stunning collapse in prices after five years
of record growth.
   Many complained about their inability to execute orders or even
get brokers on the telephone as their portfolios tumbled in value.
Some accused brokers of panicking and selling their own positions
before taking care of clients.
   The number of crash-related lawsuits remains unclear, partly
because there is no one single group that keeps track of such
statistics.
   ``All I have are anecdotal things which I've discussed with
others,'' said Fitzpatrick. ``Almost universally, they've said they
anticipated a dramatic increase and it just hasn't materialized.''
   Part of the reason is that as the emotions raised by the crash
eased, a good deal of these gripes were resolved by rational
discussions between investors and brokers.
   Other investors reckoned that even with their losses, they had
still done better in the market over the past several years.
   ``Some realized it was an overall market situation and decided
to be big boys and girls and take their lumps,'' said Edward
McDevitt, a prominent securities-law litigator in Charleston, W.
Va. ``Many of these people are still way ahead.''
   Some securities industry critics say the lack of lawsuits is
deceptive and to a great extent reflects the language in many
brokerage contracts requiring disputes to be settled by arbitration.
   The North American Securities Administrators Assocation, a group
of state securities regulators, says the number of arbitration
cases soared after crash.
   In a survey released earlier this month, the association also
said two out of three small investors who encountered problems with
brokers during the crash have not been able to resolve their
complaints.
   The New York Stock Exchange, American Stock Exchange and
National Association of Securities Dealers, the electronic
over-the-counter market, have all experienced sharp rises in the
number of arbitration cases.
   At the American Arbitration Association, which also handles
securities-related disputes, the number of broker-investor cases
more than quadrupled in the 12 months since the crash compared with
the 12 months preceding it, said George Friedman, vice president
for case administration.
   ``It's also very clear from talking to people who've gone into
arbitration that if they had the option of going to court, they
definitely would have,'' said Scott Stapf, director of investor
education for the North American Securities Administrators group.
   Others strongly disagree. Stephen Ratner, a New York attorney
who represents Bear, Stearns & Co., a defendant in one of the few
prominent crash-related suits filed, said: ``The story with the
crash is there's no story. It's a situation in which the brokers
aren't to blame.''
   He has moved to dismiss the complaint against Bear Stearns by a
group of investors who blame the firm for several million dollars
in stock losses during the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
