<DOCNO> AP881019-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ColtStrike     10-19 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colt Strike,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Progress In First Colt Negotiations In 17 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WETHERSFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first negotiating session in
nearly 17 months between striking United Auto Workers and officials
of the Colt Firearms Division broke off Wednesday after just 14
minutes of mediated talks.
   ``There was no movement,'' said Robert Madore, president of UAW
Local 376. ``We met (separately) for about 12 minutes, broke up,
came back face to face for another two minutes and broke up.''
   Madore said the company and the union are still deadlocked over
the issue of whether the company can keep the 725 replacement
workers it has hired to replace the strikers.
   ``The company's position is that the replacement workers stay,''
Madore said. ``We're not going to cave in on that. All the strikers
have to go back.''
   Richard Reibeling, vice president for personnel at Colt Firearms
Division and the company's chief negotiator, said the two parties
are ``180 degrees apart,'' with the issue of replacement workers at
the center of the dispute.
   The strike began in January 1986 when 1,000 members of UAW Local
376 struck over a failure of both sides to reach a new contract
after months of negotiations.
   The company hired replacements at its Hartford and West Hartford
plants and production has continued throughout the strike. In
addition, 200 union members have returned to work, company
officials said.
   Wednesday's talks, held under the guidance of state and federal
mediators at the state Department of Labor offices in Wethersfield,
were the first since negotiators for the union and Colt met on May
27, 1987.
   State Department of Labor spokesman Richard Ficks said no date
has been set for future talks.
</TEXT>
