<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher In US Trading; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened slightly in U.S. trading
Wednesday after barely budging abroad, but foreign exchange traders
said the late movement was caused largely by internal market
conditions and not outside news.
   Gold prices were narrowly mixed in the United States after
falling slightly overseas in choppy trading, which bullion brokers
attributed largely to the effect of vacillating oil prices on the
gold market.
   Oil prices jumped 79 cents a barrel in hectic trading one day
after they fell 60 cents, reflecting ambivalence about the effect
of an Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries ministerial
meeting. Gold, an historical hedge against inflation, tends to move
in the opposite direction of oil prices.
   Currency brokers said the dollar continued to trade in a narrow
range based on technical factors and was unaffected by external
events. Many expected that trend to persist at least until after
the November election.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.85 yen to 126.85 yen. Later in
London it was quoted at 127.20 yen. By the time trading ended in
New York, the dollar fetched 127.38 yen, up from 127.15 yen late
Tuesday.
   The dollar was unchanged against the British pound in London,
where it cost $1.7515 to buy one pound, the same as late Tuesday.
Later in New York, the pound strengthened to $1.7517 vs. $1.7480
late Tuesday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. rates late Tuesday
included: 1.8120 West German marks, up from 1.8112; 1.5312 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5292; 1.1994 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2007;
6.1905 French francs, up from 6.1675; and 1,348.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,346.50.
   Other late-dollar rates in Europe vs. rates late Tuesday: 1.8115
marks, up from 1.8050; 1.5275 Swiss francs, down from 1.5280;
6.1710 French francs, down from 6.1735; 2.0380 Dutch guilders, down
from 2.0390; 1,347.625 Italian lire, up from 1,345.50; and 1.19955
Canadian dollars, down from 1.20095.
   In gold trading, Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$411.80 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up $1.10 from the same time
Tuesday.
   Gold for current delivery fell 40 cents a troy ounce to $411.40
on the Commodity Exchange in New York. Earlier in London gold fell
$1.90 an ounce to $411.05 and in Zurich if fell $1 to $410. Gold
didn't trade in Hong Kong because markets were closed for a holiday.
   Silver for current delivery fell 1.8 cents a troy ounce on the
New York Comex to $6.337. In London, silver fell 4 cents to $6.35.
</TEXT>
