<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Brokerages 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Brokerages, 1st Ld-Writethru,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shearson's Third-Quarter Net Tumbles; PaineWebber Posts Slight
Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout to include PaineWebber. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., one of the nation's
biggest investment firms, reported an 85 percent drop in
third-quarter earnings Wednesday, attributing it to post-crash
investor apathy, expenses from the purchase of E.F. Hutton Group
Inc. and higher short-term interest rates.
   PaineWebber Group Inc. also reported a lack of retail and
institutional activity, but the firm managed to post a sharp gain
in the quarter partly on the sale of its interest in a car rental
company.
   Issuing its third-quarter results on the anniversary of the
stock crash a year ago, Shearson said it earned $8 million or 2
cents a share in the three months ended Sept. 30, vs. $54 million
or 54 cents a share a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenues totaled $2.63 billion, up 67 percent from
the $1.57 billion a year earlier, prior to the December acquisition
of Hutton.
   For the first nine months of the year, Shearson reported
earnings of $140 million or $1.39 a share, down 29 percent from the
$196 million or $2.16 a share reported a year earlier. Results this
year included $144 million in pretax, one-time acquisition-related
expenses.
   Nine-month revenues totaled $7.64 billion, up 54 percent from
$4.96 billion a year earlier.
   ``The decline in the third quarter and year-to-date earnings
reflects a significant decrease in investor participation in the
financial markets, along with non-recurring, merger-related
expenses that we are incurring this year,'' Peter A. Cohen,
chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
   ``In addition, third-quarter net interest income declined from
the year-ago period, due largely to a narrower interest margin
caused by a rise in short-term rates,'' he said. ``These factors
more than offset strong results in investment banking, market
making and principal transactions and investment advisory
businesses.''
   The company largely has completed the incorporation of Hutton
and a major cost-cutting program, which resulted in the layoffs of
thousands of ex-Hutton employees. Nevertheless, Cohen said, because
of business conditions, ``we plan to continue company-wide efforts
to further reduce operating expenses.''
   There was no elaboration, but many Wall Street professionals
have said privately that unless business improves in the next six
months, they expect further layoffs and cutbacks.
   At PaineWebber, third-quarter earnings jumped 41 percent to
$20.9 million, or 50 cents a share, from $14.8 million, or 44 cents
a share a year ago.
   Revenue during the period advanced at a much slower pace,
however. Revenue totaled $642.4 million in the quarter, up 2
percent from $628.6 million a year ago.
   The company noted that the sale of its investment in National
Car Rental System Inc. contributed a $46 million pretax gain during
the third quarter. Otherwise, the company said overall results
continue to be negatively affected by a lack of investor activity
since the market crash.
   For the first nine months, earnings fell 36 percent to $41.8
million, or 77 cents a share, from $65 million, or $2.01 a share a
year earlier. Revenue for the year-to-date totaled $1.8 billion,
down from $1.9 billion in the first nine months of 1987.
</TEXT>
