<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CrashAnniversary-Amex     10-19 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Anniversary-Amex,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Head Is Skeptical About Circuit Breakers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly approved circuit breakers designed to halt
trading if stock prices take a sudden plunge could actually provoke
a frenzied sell-off as investors rush to beat the deadline, the
president of the American Stock Exchange said Wednesday.
   Speaking on the first anniversary of the October stock crash,
Amex President Kenneth R. Leibler said circuit breakers are ``the
most visible change'' that has been made to prevent a repeat of the
crash.
   But he said their effect is uncertain.
   ``There is a school of thought that says that as the market
moves toward (the circuit breaker), investors may rush to get out
knowing that the market's going to close, and it may even
exacerbate the trend,'' Leibler said during a news conference.
   ``There is no experience with this in the markets, and I don't
think there is any guarantee that this will be productive,'' he
added.
   Leibler, in Boston to address an executive symposium, said he
believed Wall Street and the U.S. government must go further,
addressing ``larger structural issues'' and not just the
``mechanical or technical causes'' of the crash.
   The circuit breaker plan was approved Tuesday as a one-year
experiment by the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission. If the Dow Jones average of
30 industrial stocks drops 250 points in a single day, trading on
the major U.S. exchanges will automatically be halted for one hour.
   If there is an additional 150-point plunge, for a total of 400
points in a single day, a second circuit breaker will impose a
two-hour halt.
   Leibling said the American Stock Exchange will cooperate with
the plan, which is intended to provide ``a cooling-off period''
during a panic like the one that hit Wall Street on Oct. 19, 1987,
when the Dow Jones average fell 508 points.
   He also said he thought the chances of another crash are slight,
because ``the market appears to be quite reasonably valued by
historic standards and in relation to corporate profits.''
   But he said additional steps are needed to win back the
confidence of small investors.
   ``I think instead of focusing so much on the symptoms, which is
trying to eliminate or change rules about particular products, I
think we have to focus on the infrastructure, which is to continue
to invest at the exchanges in greater technology to be able to
handle greater activity,'' he said.
   In addition, Leibler said, there are steps that should be taken
in Washington.
   ``The situation that we currently have today _ where the markets
are all independently regulated, where the futures markets and the
securities markets are regulated by two entities, who in turn are
overseen by two different congressional committees _ I think that
long term places us at a severe disadvantage with other world
markets, and I think it is a very, very inefficient system and a
potential cause for instability,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
