<HEAD>Conrail's Profit Up 34 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD that company was privatized last year;
picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, Third-quarter revenue ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Rail Corp. on Wednesday
reported a 34 percent rise in third-quarter profit from a year
earlier, attributing the increase to improved volume and cost
control.
   The freight company, which was sold by the government in March
1987, said its net income in the third quarter jumped to $83
million, or $1.21 a share, from $62 million, or 90 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $876 million from $800 million.
   ``Our performance this quarter reflects our continuing ability
to control costs while attracting significantly increased
business,'' Chairman L. Stanley Crane said.
   ``While we expect freight traffic to remain strong in the fourth
quarter, we do not expect the same percentage increases in traffic
over the prior year, since the fourth quarter of 1987 reflected
substantial increases in coal and steel traffic,'' he said.
   Freight traffic in the third quarter increased 7.3 percent over
a year earlier, Conrail said.
   In the first nine months of the year, Conrail's net income rose
to $228 million, or $3.31 a share, from $220 million, or $3.20 a
share.
   Nine-month revenue increased to $2.59 billion from $2.41 billion.
