<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Japan-Scandal     10-19 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Scandal,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Of Alleged Insider Trading Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors Wednesday searched the headquarters of
two companies linked to an insider trading scandal involving some
of Japan's top leaders, officials said.
   Investigators from the Tokyo District Prosecutor's Office also
searched the home of Hiroshi Matsubara, chief aide to the former
president of the two companies: Recruit-Cosmos, a real estate firm,
and its parent Recruit Co.
   Officials from the prosecutor's office confirmed the searches
had been made, but refused further comment.
   The Japan Broadcasting Corp. said Wednesday night investigators
had removed more than 1,000 boxes of financial records and other
documents from the Recruit headquarters in Tokyo's Ginza district.
   The searches and investigation were expected to have a strong
impact on deliberations in Japan's parliament on a key tax reform
package.
   On Tuesday, opposition parties boycotted committee hearings on
the proposed tax measures, demanding witnesses be called to testify
on the growing insider trading scandal and its connection to top
politicians.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa and other officials have admitted their aides bought
shares in Recruit-Cosmos before they were offered to the public and
made large profits after the stock began trading on the
over-the-counter market and jumped in value.
   Last month, Yanosuke Narazaki, a member of parliament from the
opposition United Social Democratic Party, filed a complaint with
the prosecutor's office charging Matsubara had offered him bribes
of 5 million yen ($39,000) to end his investigation into the case.
   Recruit officials have maintained Matsubara acted alone in
offering money to Narazaki, but government investigators suspect
there was an organized attempt by Recruit to stifle a parliamentary
probe, news reports said.
   The searches Wednesday were in response to Narazaki's complaint,
the reports said.
   In a reference to the Watergate scandal that resulted in the
resignation of President Richard Nixon, Narazaki welcomed the
prosecutor's actions Wednesday and said they had ``opened up the
`gate' of the `Recruit-gate' scandal.''
   Ruling Liberal Democratic Party leaders met Wednesday to discuss
how to respond to opposition demands for the summoning of witnesses
to a parliamentary probe of the scandal, but did not agree on how
to proceed, the broadcasting corporation, or NHK, reported. The
party had hoped to begin formal debate on the tax bills by next
week.
   The insider trading scandal surfaced last summer when it was
disclosed that dozens of unidentified politicians, business leaders
and journalists had acquired and resold shares in Recruit-Cosmos.
   Last week, the Japan Communist Party released a list of nine
people, including Miyazawa and aides to other key political
leaders, who it said had purchased shares in the company.
   On Tuesday, Miyazawa apologized for having failed to properly
supervise an aide who he said had allowed a friend to buy 10,000
shares of stock in Miyazawa's name. But Miyazawa denied previous
knowledge of the dealings.
   The government has said the Recruit-Cosmos purchases were legal,
but opposition parties charge they were unethical.
   Trading stocks on privileged information has been a common
practice in Japan, but new laws passed since the scandal unfolded
deal more stringently with insider trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
