<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CSXBuyback     10-19 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CSX Buyback,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX Sets Stock Purchase Price At $32 A Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. set the price on 40 million
shares of company stock it offered to buy back last month at $32 a
share.
   The offer was overscribed when it expired Tuesday at midnight,
the company said Wednesday.
   As part of a major restructuring, CSX offered on Sept. 19 to buy
back shares in a ``Dutch auction.'' Stockholders were offered a
price between $28 and $33 per share under the understanding that
the company would set the price once the offer expired.
   The company set a limit of 40 million shares, or 26 percent of
its outstanding common stock. CSX said shares tendered but not
purchased would be returned promptly. The company also said it
would buy back another 20 million shares of common stock, for a
total of 38 percent of the outstanding stock, over time on the open
market.
   According to analysts, reducing the number of shares outstanding
will increase the return to those who continue to hold stock. CSX
stock has been lagging about 25 percent below its pre-October 1987
price, disappointing many institutional stockholders.
   As part of its restructuring plan, the company is selling off
several non-transportation divisions and has offered early
retirement programs to numerous classes of employees.
   Hays T. Watkins, CSX chairman and chief executive officer, has
said the restructuring ``evidences our continued commitment to
increasing stockholder value by concentrating our resources on our
core transportation businesses.''
</TEXT>
