<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 1951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Teamsters-Contracts     10-19 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Contracts,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Vote To Scrap Rule Requiring Two-Thirds Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters union, facing rank-and-file
resistance to its major contracts, on Wednesday abolished a
decades-old requirement for a two-thirds membership vote to reject
tentative accords negotiated by its officers, union sources said.
   The change in the union's constitution allowing for a simple
majority _ any ``no'' vote greater than 50 percent _ to reject a
proposed contract was approved by the Teamster's 18-member
executive board, meeting in Greenelefe, Fla., the sources said,
speaking on the condition of anonymity.
   The issue had been a major bone of contention in several
contracts negotiated this year and in Boston Teamster leader
William McCarthy's upset victory over Secretary-Treasurer Weldon
Mathis in claiming the union's presidency last July following the
death of Jackie Presser.
   It also was the target of a suit filed last May in U.S. District
Court here against the union by a 10,000-member dissident faction,
Teamsters for a Democratic Union.
   Duke Zeller, a Teamster spokesman reached at Greenelefe, would
not confirm or deny any changes in the union's constitution, saying
McCarthy planned to meet with representatives from 750 locals in
Chicago later this month to ``talk about new directions in the
union.''
   However, sources at Greenelefe, at the union's headquarters here
and at some locals in the Midwest confirmed that the board had
voted to do away with the two-thirds membership vote requirement
for turning down a proposed contract.
   Ken Paff, an organizer for the Detroit-based dissident faction,
called Wednesday's decision a major victory, saying Teamster
leaders had agreed to the change as ``part of an attempt to work
out a settlement'' to the court suit.
   ``We have been fighting for this steadily for 12 years,'' Paff
said. ``They called us nuts and screwballs, but we finally have
majority rule in this union.''
   Paff said the change had nothing to do with another suit _ by
the Justice Department _ seeking to wrest control of the Teamsters
from its top officers on grounds they are influenced by organized
crime figures. That suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
last June, would empower a court-appointed trustee to run the union.
   ``The Feds have shown no interest in this; it's not a
racketeering issue,'' Paff said. ``There's no law there has to be
any membership vote on approving contracts.''
   TDU had sought at the union's last convention in 1986 to change
the Teamsters' constitution to require a majority rank-and-file
approval for any contract with a petition signed by 100 of the
1,800 delegates. It was soundly defeated.
   The issue came to a boil in May when 63.5 percent of voting
truck drivers and warehouse workers under the nationwide Master
Freight Agreement covering some 200,000 Teamsters voted against a
new three-year contract with the trucking industry.
   Mathis, then acting as the union's president while Presser was
hospitalized with brain and lung cancer, declared the contract
ratified, saying the two-thirds requirement for rejecting it had
not been met.
   McCarthy and several other Teamster leaders had actively
campaigned against signing the accord and had lobbied to reopen
negotiations with bargaining agents for trucking company owners.
   The trucking industry contract is one of several negotiated this
year that has failed to garner majority support in rank-and-file
ratification votes.
   Others include signed contracts with United Parcel Service,
rejected by 53 percent of the covered voting members, and Stroh
Brewery Co., rejected by 54 percent.
   A proposed contract covering some 20,000 Teamsters who drive
auto transport trucks was renegotiated after it was rejected by 72
percent on a first ratification vote. Results of a second
ratification vote are due Friday.
   The only major contract approved by a majority of affected
Teamster members this year was with Anheuser-Busch Cos. covering
some 9,000 brewery workers.
   Paff and the Teamster sources said the new language requiring
majority approval of new contracts covers both nationwide and
locally negotiated accords.
   However, they said it also includes a provision reverting to the
two-thirds rule if less than 50 percent of the affected members
return ballots in any ratification vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881019-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Media     10-19 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Media,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dun & Bradstreet, McGraw-Hill Post Double-Digit Profit Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp. said Wednesday its third-quarter net
income from operations climbed 16.5 percent, while another
publishing and information services concern, McGraw-Hill Inc.,
posted a 12.1 percent profit rise.
   Dun & Bradstreet said its income from operations, net of income
taxes, rose to $134.8 million, or 72 cents a share, in the three
months ended Sept. 30, compared with $115.7 million, or 62 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 15.8 percent to $1.07 billion, from
$921 million.
   For the first nine months of 1988, net income from operations
rose 12.3 percent to to $375.9 million, or $2.01 per share, from
$334.6 million, or $1.80 per share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 13.3 percent to $3.13 billion, from
$2.77 billion a year ago.
   New York-based Dun & Bradstreet is the world's largest marketer
of business information and related services. Its businesses
include Nielsen Media Research, which compiles television ratings,
and Moody's Investors Service, which rates debt.
   McGraw-Hill, also based in New York, said it earned $58.8
million, or $1.21 a share, in the three months ended Sept. 30,
compared with $52.4 million, or $1.03 a share, a year ago.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 3.5 percent to $471 million, from
$455 million a year earlier.
   For the first nine months, McGraw-Hill said its profit rose 13.6
percent to $130.5 million, or $2.69 a share, from $114.9 million,
or $2.26 a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 4.6 percent to $1.31 billion, from $1.25
billion a year earlier.
   McGraw-Hill said operating profit for the quarter rose in its
information services and financial services companies, but fell in
publishing operations because of softness in some aspects of its
education group's operations and in the broadcasting unit.
</TEXT>
