<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Harcourt Brace,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harcourt Reports 3rd Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. on Wednesday
reported a 4 percent drop in third-quarter profits despite a more
than $80 million rise in sales at the publishing-entertainment
conglomerate.
   For the three months ended Sept. 30, the Orlando-based company
earned $60.4 million, or $1 a share, on sales of $625.6 million,
compared with earnings of $63.2 million, or $1.21 a share, on sales
of $543.1 million in the same period last year.
   HBJ, the nation's largest textbook publisher, also owns
insurance operations and theme parks, including Sea Worlds in
Orlando, San Diego, San Antonio, Texas and Aurora, Ohio.
   Some of the decline in earnings is linked to restructuring costs
to thwart a hostile takeover bid by Maxwell Communication Corp.
   Since mid-August, HBJ has laid off 10 percent of its parks
division staff, replaced or relocated a number of executives and
canceled advertising in key markets.
   For the nine-month period ended Sept. 30, HBJ lost $55 million
on sales of $1.4 billion, compared with a net loss of $17 million
on sales of $1.2 billion for the same period last year.
   The company earlier this month announced plans to raise $500
million from the sale of junk bonds and common stock. Executives
recently returned from meetings in Europe to tout the securities.
   ``They couldn't come out with this deal with a quarter that was
horrendous,'' said Elizabeth Bramwell, an analyst at Gabelli & Co.
in New York. ``You can't come out and sell stock when a quarter is
really disappointing financially.''
</TEXT>
