<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HousingStarts 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Up 1.5 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs bgng, `However, David' to add dropped
words; picks up 8th graf pvs: `We're looking,'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AP LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rebound in apartment construction offset a
decline in single-family home building, boosting overall housing
activity by a moderate 1.5 percent last month, the government said
Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were built
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.45 million units in
September, the fourth consecutive month that starts have held
steady between a rate of 1.43 million and 1.48 million units.
   ``We've had fairly stable interest rates and an economy that
continues to grow at a moderate pace. As a result, we have had
about the same rate of housing activity for the past four months,''
said Mark Obrinsky, an economist with the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions.
   Economists have been expecting significant drops in housing
activity this year as interest rates increased. But the sector has
held up somewhat better than anticipated.
   The Federal Reserve, as an inflation-fighting measure, began
pushing up interest rates in late March, but the rise has been
fairly gradual and in the last two month rates have declined
slightly.
   According to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgages hit a low of 9.84 percent in early spring,
climbed to 10.71 percent in mid-August and by last week eased to
10.33 percent.
   However, David Seiders, chief economist of the National
Association of Home Builders, said mortgage rates will begin
climbing again this year, dampening building activity.
   ``We're looking for rates to start going up again, not long
after election. We're looking for a percentage point increase from
now until the middle of next year,'' Seiders said.
   Housing construction during the current economic expansion
peaked at 1.81 million units in 1986, falling to 1.62 million units
last year.
   In the first nine months of this year, starts are running 10.5
percent behind the same period of last year, on track for about
1.45 million units by year end. Economists anticipate a further
decline next year.
   Building permits, a good indicator of future housing activity,
fell 4.4 percent in September to an annual rate of 1.40 million
units, after rising 3.1 percent in August.
   Single-family homes in September were built at an annual rate of
1.05 million units, down 2.3 percent from August.
   However, apartment construction shot up 13.2 percent to 403,000
units. In August, apartment construction had dipped 13.0 percent to
the lowest levels since the end of the last recession in 1982.
   Apartment construction swings widely from month to month.
Analysts say it has been depressed by high vacancy rates and the
elimination of tax benefits in January 1987.
   By region, housing starts shot up 12.4 percent in the West to
435,000 units, the highest since June 1987. Starts also increased
6.3 percent in the Midwest to 254,000 units and 3.9 percent in the
Northeast to 212,000. However, they fell 2.0 percent in the South
to 552,000.
   Seiders said builders are working overtime in California,
fearing the eventual imposition of growth limits by local
governments in crowded southern counties in the state. Activity in
the Northeast, despite the September increase, has been cooling
this year from an earlier boom, he said.
   Obrinsky said housing activity will likely pick up in
manufacturing areas of the Midwest, where the regional economy is
being powered by a surge in export sales. However, the summer
drought has hurt farming areas in the Midwest.
   Activity in the South has been hurt by high vacancy rates in
Texas and other oil-dependent states in the Southwest, he said.
</TEXT>
