<HEAD>Earnings Up 30 Pct. for Parent of Home Savings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.F. Ahmanson & Co., the nation's largest
thrift holding company, Wednesday reported earnings in the third
quarter rose 30 percent over the year-ago period.
   Ahmanson, parent of Home Savings of America, said earnings for
the quarter ended Sept. 30 rose to $56 million, or 57 cents per
share, compared with $43.4 million, or 44 cents a share, for the
same period in 1987.
   But earnings for the first nine months slipped 19 percent to
$135 million, or $1.37 per share, compared to $167 million, or
$1.70 a share, for the same period a year ago.
   The decline was attributed to a 74 percent reduction in
after-tax gains on loan sales.
   ``Core earnings _ which exclude gains from sales of loans _
increased by 69 percent from the third quarter of 1987 to nearly
$51 million, and accounted for 91 percent of total earnings,'' said
Ahmanson Chairman Richard Deihl.
   Additionally, net interest income rose 30 percent to a record
$228.2 million, he said.
   Ahmanson, with assets of $38 billion and net worth of $1.84
billion, is the parent company of Home Savings of America, the
nation's largest savings and loan and the largest residential
mortgage lender in the thrift industry.
   Home Savings operates 353 savings branches in nine states and
113 mortgage lending offices in 19 states. Its $29.4 billion
deposit base is the largest of any U.S. savings institution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
